\section*{Equilibrium Solution}

For specific models (see Modified Ohmic Contacts on page 274, Barrier Lowering at Schottky Contacts on page 279, Floating Semiconductor Contacts on page 296, and Conductive Insulators on page 315), the equilibrium electrostatic potential is required internally. In this case, the Poisson equation is solved with equilibrium boundary conditions before any other coupled statement and the solution is saved for use during the simulation.

You can control the parameters of the nonlinear solver for the equilibrium Poisson equation. The parameters Iterations, Digits, NotDamped, LineSearchDamping, and RelErrControl, described in Table 348 on page 1772, can be specified as options to the keyword EquilibriumSolution in the Math section (see Table 221 on page 1652) to control the Newton solver behavior.

The following example forces the Newton solver to solve for an equilibrium solution with 7 digits as the target accuracy and a maximum number of 100 iterations:
```
Math {
    ...
    EquilibriumSolution(Iterations=100 Digits=7)
    ...
}
```


\section*{Quasi-Fermi Potential With Boltzmann Statistics}

Electron and hole densities can be computed from the electron and hole quasi-Fermi potentials, and vice versa.

If Boltzmann statistics is assumed, the formulas read:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& n=N_{\mathrm{C}} \exp \left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{\mathrm{C}}}{k T}\right) \tag{40} \\
& p=N_{\mathrm{V}} \exp \left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{\mathrm{F}, p}}{k T}\right) \tag{41}
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 245 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Fermi Statistics
where:
- \(\quad N_{\mathrm{C}}\) and \(N_{\mathrm{V}}\) are the effective density-of-states.
- \(E_{\mathrm{F}, n}=-q \Phi_{n}\) and \(E_{\mathrm{F}, p}=-q \Phi_{p}\) are the quasi-Fermi energies for electrons and holes.
- \(\Phi_{n}\) and \(\Phi_{p}\) are electron and hole quasi-Fermi potentials, respectively.
- \(\quad E_{\mathrm{C}}\) and \(E_{\mathrm{V}}\) are conduction and valence band edges, defined as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& E_{\mathrm{C}}=-\chi-q\left(\phi-\phi_{\mathrm{ref}}\right) \tag{42} \\
& E_{\mathrm{V}}=-\chi-E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}-q\left(\phi-\phi_{\mathrm{ref}}\right) \tag{43}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\chi\) denotes the electron affinity, \(E_{\mathrm{g}, \text { eff }}\) is the effective band gap, and \(\phi_{\text {ref }}\) is a constant reference potential (see below). The zero level for the quasi-Fermi potential agrees with the zero level for the voltages applied at the contacts.

In unipolar devices, such as MOSFETs, it is sometimes possible to assume that the value of quasi-Fermi potential for the minority carrier is constant in certain regions. In this case, the concentration of the minority carrier can be directly computed from Equation 40 or Equation 41. This strategy is applied in Sentaurus Device if one of the carriers (electron or hole) is not specified inside the Coupled statement of the Solve section. Sentaurus Device uses an approximation scheme to determine the constant value of the quasi-Fermi potential.

\section*{Note:}

In many cases if avalanche generation is important, the one carrier approximation cannot be applied even for unipolar devices.

The datasets for \(E_{\mathrm{F}, n} . \Phi_{n}, E_{\mathrm{F}, p}\), and \(\Phi_{p}\) are named equasiFermiEnergy, eQuasiFermiPotential, hQuasiFermiEnergy, and hQuasiFermiPotential, respectively.

The ConstRefPot parameter allows you to specify \(\phi_{\text {ref }}\) explicitly. Otherwise, Sentaurus Device computes \(\phi_{\text {ref }}\) from the vacuum level, using the following rules:
- If there is silicon in any simulated semiconductor structure, then the intrinsic Fermi level of silicon is selected as reference, \(\phi_{\text {ref }}=\Phi_{\text {intr }}(\mathrm{Si})\).
- Otherwise, if any simulated device structure contains GaAs, then \(\phi_{\text {ref }}=\Phi_{\text {intr }}(\mathrm{GaAs})\).
- In all other cases, Sentaurus Device selects the material with the smallest band gap (assuming a mole fraction of 0 ) and takes the value of its intrinsic Fermi level as \(\phi_{\text {ref }}\).

\section*{Fermi Statistics}

For the equations presented in the previous section, Boltzmann statistics was assumed for electrons and holes. Physically more correct, Fermi (also called Fermi-Dirac) statistics can

[Page 246 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Fermi Statistics

be used. Fermi statistics becomes important for high values of carrier densities, for example, \(n>1 \times 10^{19} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\) in the active regions of a silicon device.

For Fermi statistics, Equation 40 and for Equation 41 are replaced by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& n=N_{\mathrm{C}} F_{1 / 2}\left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{\mathrm{C}}}{k T}\right) \tag{44} \\
& p=N_{\mathrm{V}} F_{1 / 2}\left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{\mathrm{F}, p}}{k T}\right) \tag{45}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(F_{1 / 2}\) is the Fermi integral of order \(1 / 2\).
Alternatively, you can write these expressions as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& n=\gamma_{n} N_{\mathrm{C}} \exp \left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{\mathrm{C}}}{k T}\right) \tag{46} \\
& p=\gamma_{p} N_{\mathrm{V}} \exp \left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{\mathrm{F}, p}}{k T}\right) \tag{47}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\gamma_{n}\) and \(\gamma_{p}\) are the functions of \(\eta_{n}\) and \(\eta_{p}\) :
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \gamma_{n}=\frac{n}{N_{\mathrm{C}}} \exp \left(-\eta_{n}\right) \tag{48} \\
& \gamma_{p}=\frac{p}{N_{\mathrm{V}}} \exp \left(-\eta_{p}\right) \tag{49} \\
& \eta_{n}=\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{\mathrm{C}}}{k T} \tag{50} \\
& \eta_{p}=\frac{E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{\mathrm{F}, p}}{k T} \tag{51}
\end{aligned}
\]

\section*{Using Fermi Statistics}

To activate Fermi statistics, you must specify the keyword Fermi in the Physics section:
```
Physics {
    ...
    Fermi
}
```


\section*{Note:}

Fermi statistics can be activated only for the entire device. Region-specific or material-specific activation is not possible, and the keyword Fermi can be defined in any Physics section.

