\section*{Hydrodynamic Model for Temperatures}

Deep-submicron devices cannot be described properly using the conventional drift-diffusion transport model. In particular, the drift-diffusion approach cannot reproduce velocity overshoot and often overestimates the impact ionization generation rates. In this case, the hydrodynamic (or energy balance) model provides a good compromise between physical accuracy and computation time.

Since the work of Stratton [2] and Bløtekjær [3], there have been many variations of this model. The full formulation includes convective terms [4]. Sentaurus Device implements a simpler formulation without convective terms. In addition to the Poisson equation (Equation 38) and continuity equations (Equation 59), up to three additional equations for the lattice temperature \(T\) and the carrier temperatures \(T_{n}\) and \(T_{p}\) can be solved.
The energy balance equations read:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\partial W_{n}}{\partial t}+\nabla \cdot \vec{S}_{n}=\vec{J}_{n} \cdot \nabla E_{\mathrm{C}} / q+\left.\frac{d W_{n}}{d t}\right|_{\mathrm{coll}} \tag{78} \\
& \frac{\partial W_{p}}{\partial t}+\nabla \cdot \vec{S}_{p}=\vec{J}_{p} \cdot \nabla E_{\mathrm{V}} / q+\left.\frac{d W_{p}}{d t}\right|_{\mathrm{coll}} \tag{79} \\
& \frac{\partial W_{\mathrm{L}}}{\partial t}+\nabla \cdot \vec{S}_{\mathrm{L}}=\left.\frac{d W_{\mathrm{L}}}{d t}\right|_{\mathrm{coll}} \tag{80}
\end{aligned}
\]
where the energy fluxes are:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{S}_{n}=-\frac{5 r_{n} \lambda_{n}}{2}\left(\frac{k T_{n}}{q} J_{n}+f_{n}^{\mathrm{hf}} \hat{\kappa}_{n} \nabla T_{n}\right) \tag{81} \\
& \vec{S}_{p}=-\frac{5 r_{p} \lambda_{p}}{2}\left(\frac{-k T_{p}}{q} J_{p}+f_{p}^{\mathrm{hf}} \hat{\kappa}_{p} \nabla T_{p}\right) \tag{82} \\
& \vec{S}_{\mathrm{L}}=-\kappa_{\mathrm{L}} \cdot \nabla T_{\mathrm{L}} \tag{83} \\
& \hat{\kappa}_{n}=\frac{k^{2}}{q} n \mu_{n} T_{n} \tag{84} \\
& \hat{\kappa}_{p}=\frac{k^{2}}{q} p \mu_{p} T_{p} \tag{85}
\end{aligned}
\]
and \(\lambda_{n}\) and \(\lambda_{p}\) are defined as for Equation 66 and Equation 67.

[Page 267 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Hydrodynamic Model for Temperatures

The parameters \(r_{n}, r_{p}, f_{n}^{\mathrm{hf}}\), and \(f_{p}^{\mathrm{hf}}\) are accessible in the parameter file of Sentaurus Device. Different values of these parameters can significantly influence the physical results, such as velocity distribution and possible spurious velocity peaks. By changing these parameters, Sentaurus Device can be tuned to a very wide set of hydrodynamic or energy balance models as described in the literature. The default parameter values of Sentaurus Device are:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& r_{n}=r_{p}=0.6 \tag{86} \\
& f_{n}^{\text {hf }}=f_{p}^{\text {hf }}=1 \tag{87}
\end{aligned}
\]

By changing the constants \(f_{n}^{\mathrm{hf}}\) and \(r_{n}\), you can change the convective contribution and the diffusive contributions independently. With the default set of transport parameters of Sentaurus Device, the prefactor of the diffusive term has the form:
\[
\kappa_{n}=\frac{3}{2} \cdot \frac{k^{2} \lambda_{n}}{q} n \mu_{n} T_{n} \tag{88}
\]

The collision terms are expressed by this set of equations:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\left.\frac{\partial W_{n}}{\partial t}\right|_{\text {coll }} & =-H_{n}-\xi_{n} \frac{W_{n}-W_{n 0}}{\tau_{\mathrm{e} n}} \tag{89} \\
\left.\frac{\partial W_{p}}{\partial t}\right|_{\text {coll }} & =-H_{p}-\xi_{p} \frac{W_{p}-W_{p 0}}{\tau_{\mathrm{e} p}} \tag{90} \\
\left.\frac{\partial W_{\mathrm{L}}}{\partial t}\right|_{\text {coll }} & =H_{\mathrm{L}}+\xi_{n} \frac{W_{n}-W_{n 0}}{\tau_{\mathrm{e} n}}+\xi_{p} \frac{W_{p}-W_{p 0}}{\tau_{\mathrm{e} p}} \tag{91}
\end{aligned}
\]

Here, \(H_{n}, H_{p}\), and \(H_{\mathrm{L}}\) are the energy gain/loss terms due to generation-recombination processes. The expressions used for these terms are based on approximations [5] and have the following form for the major generation-recombination phenomena:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& H_{n}=1.5 k T_{n}\left(R_{\mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{SRH}}+R_{\mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{rad}}+R_{n, \mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{trap}}\right)-E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}\left(R_{n}^{\mathrm{A}}-G_{n}^{\mathrm{ii}}\right)-\alpha\left(h \omega-E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}\right) G^{\mathrm{opt}} \tag{92} \\
& H_{p}=1.5 k T_{p}\left(R_{\mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{SRH}}+R_{\mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{rad}}+R_{p, \mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{trap}}\right)-E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}\left(R_{p}^{\mathrm{A}}-G_{p}^{\mathrm{ii}}\right)-(1-\alpha)\left(h \omega-E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}\right) G^{\mathrm{opt}} \tag{93} \\
& H_{\mathrm{L}}=\left[R_{\mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{SRH}}+0.5\left(R_{n, \mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{trap}}+R_{p, \mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{trap}}\right)\right]\left(E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}+1.5 k T_{n}+1.5 k T_{p}\right) \tag{94}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(R_{\text {net }}^{\text {SRH }}\) is the Shockley-Read-Hall (SRH) recombination rate (see Shockley-Read-Hall Recombination on page 493).
- \(R_{\text {net }}^{\text {rad }}\) is the radiative recombination rate (see Radiative Recombination Model on page 508).
- \(R_{n}^{\mathrm{A}}\) and \(R_{p}^{\mathrm{A}}\) are Auger recombination rates related to electrons and holes (see Auger Recombination Model on page 509).
- \(\hbar \omega\) is the photon energy (see Hydrodynamic Model Parameters on page 269).

[Page 268 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Hydrodynamic Model for Temperatures
- \(\alpha\) is a dimensionless parameter that describes how the surplus energy of the photon splits between the bands (see Hydrodynamic Model Parameters on page 269).
- \(G_{n}^{\mathrm{ii}}\) and \(G_{p}^{\mathrm{ii}}\) are impact ionization rates (see Avalanche Generation on page 514).
- \(\quad R_{n, \text { net }}^{\text {trap }}\) and \(R_{p, \text { net }}^{\text {trap }}\) are the recombination rates through trap levels (see Chapter 17 on page 564).
- \(G^{\text {opt }}\) is the optical generation rate (see Chapter 21 on page 672 ).

Surface recombination is taken into account in a way similar to bulk SRH recombination. Usually, the influence of \(H_{n}, H_{p}\), and \(H_{\mathrm{L}}\) is small, so they are not activated by default. To take these energy sources into account, the keyword RecGenHeat must be specified in the Physics section.

The energy densities \(W_{n}, W_{p}\), and \(W_{\mathrm{L}}\) are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& W_{n}=n w_{n}=n\left(\frac{3 k T_{n}}{2}\right) \tag{95} \\
& W_{p}=p w_{p}=p\left(\frac{3 k T_{p}}{2}\right) \tag{96} \\
& W_{\mathrm{L}}=c_{\mathrm{L}} T \tag{97}
\end{aligned}
\]

The corresponding equilibrium energy densities are:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& W_{n 0}=n w_{0}=n \frac{3 k T}{2} \tag{98} \\
& W_{p 0}=p w_{0}=p \frac{3 k T}{2} \tag{99}
\end{aligned}
\]

The parameters \(\xi_{n}\) and \(\xi_{p}\) in Equation 89 to Equation 91 improve numeric stability. They speed up relaxation for small densities and they approach 1 for large densities:
\[
\xi_{n}=1+\frac{n_{\min }}{n}\left(\frac{n_{0}}{n_{\min }}\right)^{\max }\left[0,\left(T-T_{n}\right) / 100 \mathrm{~K}\right] \tag{100}
\]
and likewise for \(\xi_{p}\). Here, \(n_{\min }\) and \(n_{0}\) are adjustable small density parameters.

\section*{Hydrodynamic Model Parameters}

The default set of transport coefficients (Equation 86 and Equation 87) can be changed in the parameter file. The coefficients \(r\) and \(f^{\mathrm{hf}}\) are specified in the EnergyFlux and HeatFlux parameter sets, respectively. Energy relaxation times \(\tau_{\mathrm{e} n}\) and \(\tau_{\mathrm{e} p}\) can be modified in the EnergyRelaxationTime parameter set.
\(\alpha\) in Equation 92 and Equation 93 divides the contribution of the optical generation rate into the energy gain or loss terms \(H_{n}\) and \(H_{p}\). OptGenOffset specifies \(\alpha\), which can take values between 0 and 1 (default is 0.5 ). The angular frequency \(\omega\) in Equation 92 and Equation 93

[Page 269 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Hydrodynamic Model for Temperatures
corresponds to the wavelength specified to compute the optical generation rate. This wavelength is defined by OptGenWavelength if the optical generation is loaded from a file (see Optical AC Analysis on page 795).

Both OptGenOffset and OptGenWavelength are options to RecGenHeat (see Table 241 on page 1666).

The parameters \(n_{\text {min }}\) and \(n_{0}\) in Equation 100 are set with RelTermMinDensity and RelTermMinZeroDensity, respectively, in the global Math section. The default values for \(n_{\text {min }}\) and \(n_{0}\) are \(10^{3} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\) and \(2 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\), respectively.

\section*{Using the Hydrodynamic Model}

To activate the hydrodynamic model, you must specify the keyword Hydrodynamic in the Physics section. If only one carrier temperature equation is to be solved, Hydrodynamic must be specified with the appropriate parameter, either Hydrodynamic (eTemperature) or Hydrodynamic (hTemperature). If the hydrodynamic model is not activated for a particular carrier type, Sentaurus Device merges the temperature for this carrier with the lattice temperature. That is, these temperatures are equal, and their heating terms (see the right-hand sides of Equation 78, Equation 79, and Equation 80) are added.

In addition, you must specify the eTemperature, hTemperature, and Temperature keywords inside the Coupled statement of the Solve section (see Coupled Statement on page 203) to actually solve a carrier temperature equation or the lattice temperature equation. Temperatures remain fixed during Solve statements in which their equation is not solved.

By default, the energy conservation equations of Sentaurus Device do not include generation-recombination heat sources. To activate them, the keyword RecGenHeat must be specified in the Physics section.
To plot the electron, hole, and lattice heat flux vectors \(\vec{S}_{n}, \vec{S}_{p}, \vec{S}_{\mathrm{L}}\) (see Equation 81, Equation 82, and Equation 83), specify the corresponding keywords eHeatFlux, hHeatFlux, and lHeatFlux in the Plot section (see Device Plots on page 187).
