To emulate the barrier-lowering effect at a metal-semiconductor contact, with a thin virtual interfacial layer between the metal and the semiconductor, Sentaurus Device supports another barrier-lowering model that takes into account such an insulating interface layer. The model [6] assumes that a finite insulator layer is present between the metal and the semiconductor, and it includes both images with respect to the metal-insulator and insulator-semiconductor interfaces.

[Page 282 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Electrical Boundary Conditions

Sentaurus Device implements the barrier lowering with interfacial insulating layer model described in detail in [6] as:
\[
\Delta \Phi_{\mathrm{B}}\left(d_{0}\right)=\left\{\begin{array}{cl}
\frac{q}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{\mathrm{ins}}}\left(\frac{1}{d_{\varepsilon}}+\frac{\beta}{t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{\varepsilon}}\right) & 0 \leq d_{0} \leq d_{\varepsilon} \\
\frac{q}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{\mathrm{ins}}}\left(\frac{1}{d_{0}}+\frac{\beta}{t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{0}}\right) & d_{\varepsilon}<d_{0} \leq t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{\varepsilon} \\
\frac{q}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{\mathrm{ins}}}\left(\frac{1}{t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{\varepsilon}}+\frac{\beta}{d_{\varepsilon}}\right)-A \frac{t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{\varepsilon}}{2 d_{\varepsilon}}+\frac{A}{2 d_{\varepsilon}} d_{0} & t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{\varepsilon}<d_{0} \leq t_{\mathrm{ox}}+d_{\varepsilon} \\
\frac{q}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{\mathrm{sem}}}\left(\frac{1}{d_{0}}+\frac{\beta}{t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{0}}\right) & d_{0}>t_{\mathrm{ox}}+d_{\varepsilon}
\end{array}\right. \tag{117}
\]
where:
- \(\beta=\frac{\varepsilon_{\text {sem }}-\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}}{\varepsilon_{\text {sem }}+\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}}\).
- \(A=\frac{q}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{\mathrm{sem}}}\left(\frac{1}{t_{\mathrm{ox}}+d_{\varepsilon}}-\frac{\beta}{d_{\varepsilon}}\right)-\frac{q}{16 \pi \varepsilon_{\mathrm{ins}}}\left(\frac{1}{t_{\mathrm{ox}}-d_{\varepsilon}}+\frac{\beta}{d_{\varepsilon}}\right)\).
- \(\varepsilon_{\text {sem }}\) is the semiconductor layer permittivity.
- \(\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}\) is the insulator layer permittivity.
- \(t_{\mathrm{ox}}\) is the conforming insulator layer thickness.
- \(d_{o}\) is the distance from the metal surface (contact) to the point where the barrier lowering is evaluated.
- \(d_{\varepsilon}\) is a computational-adjustable parameter used to handle critical points in the model.

The second branch in Equation 117 represents the barrier lowering due to the image-force potential of the electron in the insulator layer, where a numeric adjustment is applied to the edges of the layer to avoid infinite values. The first branch is introduced to saturate the value of the image-force potential close to the metal surface (contact), which otherwise would become infinite for \(d_{o} \rightarrow 0\). The last branch represents the barrier lowering due to the image-force potential of the electron in the semiconductor layer.

To avoid discontinuity and infinite values at the insulator-semiconductor interface, a linear transitional region is introduced (the third branch).

The \(d_{\varepsilon}\) parameter, which should be smaller than \(t_{\mathrm{ox}}\) for geometric reasons, allows you to adjust the functional shape of the model around the model critical points).

For consistency, when \(t_{\mathrm{ox}}=0\), the model reverts to \(\Delta \Phi_{\mathrm{B}}\left(d_{0}, d_{0}>0\right)=q / 16 \pi \varepsilon_{\text {sem }} d_{0}\), which is the typical image-force barrier lowering for a metal-semiconductor interface.

As an option, you can select to compute a barrier-lowering average based on Equation 117 over the distance \(d_{o}\) from the contact or an average around \(d_{o}\).

[Page 283 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


The barrier lowering with interfacial insulator layer model can be combined as a weighted sum with any of the barrier-lowering models described by Equation 114 (or Equation 115) or Equation 116, but not with both.

To activate the barrier lowering with interfacial insulator layer model, specify InsBarrierLowering in the Schottky subsection of the Electrode or the electrode-specific Physics section:
```
Electrode { ...
    { name = "cnt1" voltage = 0 Schottky(InsBarrierLowering))
        Workfunction=4.75 }
}
Physics(Electrode = "cnt1") { ...
    Schottky(InsBarrierLowering)
}
```


To compute an average based on Equation 117 over the distance \(d_{o}\), specify also the keyword Average:
```
Physics(Electrode = "Gate") { InsBarrierLowering(Average) }
```


To compute an average based on Equation 117 over a symmetric interval delta, centered around \(d_{o}\), specify the keyword DeltaAverage in the InsBarrierLowering section of the command file:
```
Physics(Electrode = "Gate") { InsBarrierLowering(DeltaAverage) }
```


You can adjust the parameter InsBL_delta in the Schottky section of the parameter file:
```
Electrode = "anode" {
    Schottky {
        InsBL_delta = 1.0000e-08 * [cm]
    }
}
```


The model parameters \(t_{\mathrm{ox}}, \varepsilon_{\mathrm{ins}}, d_{\varepsilon}, d_{0}\), and nn can be specified in the schottky section of the parameter file (see Table 33). The parameter nn controls the number of equidistant intervals over which the integration is performed using the trapezoidal rule in the case of averaging. The \(t_{\mathrm{ox}}, \varepsilon_{\mathrm{ins}}\), and \(d_{\varepsilon}\) parameters are mole fraction dependent.

You can use the weight parameter to combine the barrier lowering with the interfacial insulator layer model with either the barrier model described by Equation 114 (or Equation 115) or Equation 116. If only the barrier lowering with interfacial insulator layer model is specified (by InsBarrierLowering in the electrode-specific Physics section), the value of weight is 1 regardless of the value specified in the parameter file by InsBL_c_weight. If the model is used together with other barrier-lowering models, the weight parameters in both models can be adjusted individually such that their sum is 1 . The overall barrier-lowering effect would be a weighted sum of the models.

