\section*{Resistive Contacts}

In single-device mode, contacts have a default resistance of zero. You can change this with Resist or DistResist or both in the Electrode section. When connected to a circuit node, the contact must be resistive (see Resistive Contacts in Mixed Mode on page 291).

The following example defines an emitter as a contact with resistance \(1 \Omega\) (assuming that AreaFactor is 1):
```
Electrode { ...
    { name = "emitter" voltage = 2 Resist=1 }
}
```


If AreaFactor is not 1 , then the resistance specified by Resist is effectively scaled. Since AreaFactor can be defined in either the Physics section or the Electrode section (or both), the resistance of the contact is Resist/((Physics AreaFactor) × (Electrode AreaFactor)). For single-device simulations, this means that when AreaFactor is changed, the voltage drop across the resistive contact remains the same.

The following example defines an emitter as a contact with a distributed resistance of \(0.0002 \Omega \mathrm{~cm}^{2}\) in series with a \(100 \Omega\) lump resistor, with the 2 V external voltage applied to the lump resistor:
```
Electrode { ...
    { name = "emitter" voltage = 2 Resist=100 DistResist=2e-4 }
}
```

[Page 285 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Electrical Boundary Conditions

If \(V_{\text {applied }}\) is applied to the contact through a resistor \(R\) (Resist in the Electrode section) or distributed resistance \(R_{\mathrm{d}}\) (DistResist in the Electrode section), then there is an additional equation to compute \(\phi_{F}\) in Equation 103, Equation 106, and Equation 107.

For a distributed resistance, \(\phi_{F}\) is different for each mesh vertex of the contact and is computed as a solution of the following equation for each contact vertex, self-consistently with the system of all equations:
\[
\hat{n} \cdot\left[\vec{J}_{p}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)+\vec{J}_{n}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)+\vec{J}_{\mathrm{D}}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)\right]=\frac{\left(V_{\text {applied }}-\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)}{R_{\mathrm{d}}} \tag{118}
\]

For a resistor, \(\phi_{F}\) is a constant over the contact and only one equation per contact is solved self-consistently with the system of all equations:
\[
\int_{s}^{\hat{n}} \cdot\left[\vec{J}_{p}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)+\vec{J}_{n}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)+\vec{J}_{\mathrm{D}}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)\right] d s=\frac{\left(V_{\text {applied }}-\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)}{R} \tag{119}
\]
where \(s\) is a contact area used in a Sentaurus Device simulation to compute a total current through the contact.

When both a lump resistor \(R\) and a distributed resistance \(R_{\mathrm{d}}\) are specified, \(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\) is computed for each mesh vertex of the contact as a solution of the following equations, self-consistently with the system of all equations:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \hat{n} \cdot\left[\vec{J}_{p}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)+\vec{J}_{n}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)+\vec{J}_{\mathrm{D}}\left(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)\right]=\frac{\left(V_{\text {internal }}-\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\right)}{R_{\mathrm{d}}} \tag{120} \\
& \frac{V_{\text {applied }}-V_{\text {internal }}}{R}=\int_{S} \frac{V_{\text {internal }}-\phi_{\mathrm{F}}}{R_{\mathrm{d}}} d s \tag{121}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(V_{\text {internal }}\) depends on \(\phi_{\mathrm{F}}\) along the contact (on all contact vertices).
- \(\int_{S} \frac{V_{\text {internal }}-\phi_{\mathrm{F}}}{R_{\mathrm{d}}} d s\) is the total current on the contact.

For a distributed resistance, a total current through the contact is calculated by summing the contributions for each contact vertex, scaled by a fraction of the contact assigned to the mesh vertex. In the case of contacts overlaying the oxide materials, the vertex fraction of the contact includes the oxide part for vertices at the interface between conducting and insulating materials. This gives rise to a strong sensitivity of terminal currents with respect to mesh spacing. The erroneous contributions from the oxide contact can be excluded by using the WithDistResistOnSemi keyword in the global Math section.

[Page 286 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Electrical Boundary Conditions

\section*{Note:}

In 2D simulations, \(R\) must be specified in units of \(\Omega \mu \mathrm{m}\). In 3D simulations, \(R\) must be specified in units of \(\Omega . R_{\mathrm{d}}\) is given in \(\Omega \mathrm{cm}^{2}\) (see Table 210 on page 1610).

To emulate the behavior of a Schottky contact [7], Schottky contact resistivity at zero bias was derived and a doping-dependent resistivity model of such contacts was obtained. This model is activated for Ohmic contacts by the keyword DistResist=SchottkyResist in the Electrode section.

The model is expressed as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
R_{\mathrm{d}} & =R_{\infty} \frac{300 \mathrm{~K}}{T_{0}} \exp \left(\frac{q \Phi_{\mathrm{B}}}{E_{0}}\right) \\
E_{0} & =E_{00} \operatorname{coth}\left(\frac{E_{00}}{k T_{0}}\right) \\
E_{00} & =\frac{q h}{4 \pi} \sqrt{\frac{N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}-N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}}{\varepsilon_{\mathrm{s}} m_{\mathrm{t}}}}
\end{aligned} \tag{122}
\]
where:
- \(\Phi_{\mathrm{B}}\) is the Schottky barrier (in this model, for electrons, this is the difference between the metal workfunction and the electron affinity of the semiconductor; for holes, this is the difference between the valence band energy of the semiconductor and the metal workfunction).
- \(R_{\infty}\) is the Schottky resistance for an infinite doping concentration at the contact (or zero Schottky barrier).
- \(\varepsilon_{\mathrm{s}}\) is the semiconductor permittivity.
- \(m_{\mathrm{t}}\) is the tunneling mass.
- \(\quad T_{0}\) is the device lattice temperature defined in the Physics section (see Table 241 on page 1666).

The parameters \(\Phi_{\mathrm{B}}, R_{\infty}\), and \(m_{\mathrm{t}}\) can be mole dependent, and they can be specified in the region or material sections of the parameter file. If the parameters are mole independent, they also can be specified directly in the Electrode section of the parameter file.

For example, if the contact "top" covers two semiconductor regions "reg1" and "reg2", the mole dependency of parameter \(R_{\infty}\) can be defined as:
```
Region = "reg1" {
    SchottkyResistance {
        Xmax(0) = 0.0
        Xmax(1) = 0.6
        Electrode = "top" {
            Rinf = 2.4000e-09 , 5.2000e-09 # [Ohm*cm^2]
```

