\section*{Hole Effective Mass and Density-of-States}

This section discusses the different options.

\section*{Formula=1}

For the DOS effective mass of holes, the best fit in silicon is provided by the expression [16]:
\[
\frac{m_{p}(T)}{m_{0}}=\left(\frac{a+b T+c T^{2}+d T^{3}+e T^{4}}{1+f T+g T^{2}+h T^{3}+i T^{4}}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}}+m_{\mathrm{m}} \tag{183}
\]
where the coefficients are listed in Table 41 on page 337. The parameter \(m_{\mathrm{m}}\), which defaults to zero, allows \(m_{p}\) to be defined as a temperature-independent quantity. The effective DOS for holes \(N_{\mathrm{V}}^{p}\) follows from:
\[
N_{\mathrm{V}}\left(m_{p}, T_{p}\right)=2.5094 \times 10^{19}\left(\frac{m_{p}}{m_{0}}\right)^{\frac{3}{2}}\left(\frac{T_{p}}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{\frac{3}{2}} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3} \tag{184}
\]

\section*{Formula=2}

If Formula \(=2\) in the parameter file, then the temperature-dependent DOS is computed from \(N_{\mathrm{V}}(300 \mathrm{~K})\) as given in the parameter file:
\[
N_{\mathrm{V}}\left(T_{p}\right)=N_{\mathrm{V}}(300 \mathrm{~K})\left(\frac{T_{p}}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{\frac{3}{2}} \tag{185}
\]
and the effective hole mass is given by:
\[
\frac{m_{p}}{m_{0}}=\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{V}}(300 \mathrm{~K})}{2.5094 \times 10^{19} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}} \tag{186}
\]

