\section*{Gaussian Density-of-States for Organic Semiconductors}

Gaussian DOS has been introduced to better represent electron and hole effective DOS in disordered organic semiconductors. Within the Gaussian disorder model, electron and hole DOS are represented by:
\[
\Gamma(E)=\frac{N_{\mathrm{t}}}{\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{\mathrm{DOS}}} \exp \left(-\frac{\left(E-E_{0}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{\mathrm{DOS}}^{2}}\right) \tag{187}
\]

[Page 337 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Gaussian Density-of-States for Organic Semiconductors

where \(N_{\mathrm{t}}\) is the total number of hopping sites with \(N_{\mathrm{t}}=N_{\text {LUMO }}\) for electrons (LUMO is the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital) and \(N_{\mathrm{t}}=N_{\text {HOMO }}\) for holes (HOMO is the highest occupied molecular orbital), \(E_{0}\) and \(\sigma_{\text {DOS }}\) are the energy center and the width of the DOS distribution, respectively.

Electron and hole densities in the most general case (Fermi-Dirac statistics) then are computed using Gaussian distribution from Equation 187 as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{n}{N_{\mathrm{LUMO}}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{n}} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp \left(-\frac{\left(E-E_{0 n}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{n}^{2}}\right) \frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E-E_{\mathrm{F}, n}\right) /(k T)}} d E=G_{n}\left(\zeta_{n} ; \hat{s}_{n}\right) \tag{188} \\
& \frac{p}{N_{\mathrm{HOMO}}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi} \sigma_{p}} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp \left(-\frac{\left(E-E_{0 p}\right)^{2}}{2 \sigma_{p}^{2}}\right) \frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E_{\mathrm{F}, p}-E\right) /(k T)}} d E=G_{p}\left(\zeta_{p} ; \hat{s}_{p}\right) \tag{189}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(\zeta_{n}=\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{0 n}}{k T}, \zeta_{p}=\frac{E_{0 p}-E_{F, p}}{k T}\)
- \(\hat{s}_{n}=\frac{\sigma_{n}}{k T}, \hat{s}_{p}=\frac{\sigma_{p}}{k T}\)

Sentaurus Device computes Gauss-Fermi integrals \(G_{n}\left(\zeta_{n} ; \hat{s}_{n}\right)\) and \(G_{p}\left(\zeta_{p} ; \hat{s_{p}}\right)\) using an analytic approximation [17]. The approximation covers both the nondegenerate and degenerate cases:
\[
G_{c}\left(\zeta_{c} ; \hat{s}_{c}\right)=\left\{\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{\exp \left(\frac{\hat{s}_{c}^{2}}{2}+\zeta_{c}\right)}{1+\exp \left(K\left(\hat{s}_{c}\right)\left(\zeta_{c}+\hat{s}_{c}^{2}\right)\right)} & \zeta_{c} \leq-\hat{s}_{c}^{2} & \text { (nondegenerate region) } \\
\frac{1}{2} \operatorname{erf}\left(-\frac{\zeta_{c}}{\hat{s}_{c} \sqrt{2}} H\left(\hat{s}_{c}\right)\right) & \zeta_{c}>-\hat{s}_{c}^{2} & \text { (degenerate region) }
\end{array}\right. \tag{190}
\]
where the index \(c\) is \(n\) or \(p\), and the analytic functions \(H\) and \(K\) are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& H(s)=\frac{\sqrt{2}}{s} \operatorname{erfc}^{-1}\left(\exp \left(-\frac{s^{2}}{2}\right)\right) \tag{191} \\
& K(s)=2\left(1-\frac{H(s)}{s} \sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}} \exp \left[\frac{1}{2} s^{2}\left(1-H^{2}(s)\right)\right]\right) \tag{192}
\end{aligned}
\]

The model is activated regionwise, materialwise, or globally by specifying the keyword GaussianDOS_Full in the respective Physics section together with the Fermi keyword in the global Physics section:
```
Physics(Region="Organic_sem1") {
    GaussianDOS_full
}
```

[Page 338 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Gaussian Density-of-States for Organic Semiconductors
```
Physics {
    Fermi
}
```


