\title{
}

Multivalley Band Structure

To set such an integration, the keyword DensityIntegral must be used as in the following statement:
```
Physics { (e|h)Multivalley(DensityIntegral) }
```


Similarly, to activate the carrier density computation that accounts for nonparabolicity as in Equation 202, the following statement must be used:
```
Physics { (e|h)Multivalley(Nonparabolicity) }
```


To activate the six-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) band-structure model for holes described in Strained Hole Effective Mass and DOS on page 975 and Nonparabolic Band Structure on page 343, you can specify the following:
```
Physics { hMultivalley(kpDOS) }
```


This statement creates three hole bands (light, heavy, and spin-orbit) in the multivalley model. The parameters affecting the six-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) band-structure model (see Equation 1034 for the DOS mass and Equation 203) include the deformation potentials of the model for hole bands (adp, bdp, ddp, and dso) and the Luttinger parameters (gamma_1, gamma_2, and gamma_3). All parameters can be specified in the LatticeParameters section of the parameter file and can be mole fraction dependent. These parameters define relaxed hole bands and the stress-induced change (see Deformation of Band Structure on page 967).

To control the accuracy of surface integration in Equation 203, you can use the following grid setting in \(k\)-space, Math \(\{\mathrm{kGridSizeFor6kp(Nphi,Ntheta)} \mathrm{\}} \mathrm{where} \mathrm{Nphi} \mathrm{and} \mathrm{Ntheta}\), define the number of points for an angular spherical coordinate system. Due to symmetry and possibly the stress effect in DOS, half of the \(k\)-space is used, where both angles are changed from \(0^{\circ}\) to \(180^{\circ}\). The default setting is kGridSizeFor6kp \((10,16)\).

To activate the two-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) band-structure model for electrons described in Strained Electron Effective Mass and DOS on page 972 (where three \(\Delta_{2}\) valleys will be created), specify:
```
Physics { eMultivalley(kpDOS) }
```


The parameters affecting the two-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) band-structure model for \(\Delta_{2}\) valleys (see Equation 1021-Equation 1024) include the deformation potentials of the \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) model for electron bands (xis, dbs, xiu, and xid), the Sverdlov k ⋅ p parameter (Mkp), and the relaxed nonparabolicity \(\alpha_{0}\) (this is accounted for only with the Nonparabolicity keyword in the eMultivalley statement). These parameters can be specified in the LatticeParameters section of the parameter file. In addition, the \(\Delta_{2}\) valley effective masses (me_10 and me_t0) can be defined in the stressMobility section. All parameters can be mole fraction dependent. These parameters define three relaxed \(\Delta_{2}\) valleys and the stress-induced change (see Deformation of Band Structure on page 967).

[Page 347 END]
