    eValley"L1" (1,1,1) (ml=1.69 mt=0.13 energy=1.1 alpha=0.5 degeneracy=1
            xiu=11.5 xid=-6.58)
    eValley"Delta1"(1)(ml=0.914 mt=0.196 energy=0 alpha=0.5 degeneracy=2
            xiu=9.16 xid=0.77)
    eValley"L1"(1)(ml=1.768 mt=0.0967 energy=0 alpha=0.5 degeneracy=1
        xiu=11.5 xid=-6.58)
    eValley"Delta1"(2)(ml=0.915 mt=0.201 energy=0.19 alpha=0.5
            degeneracy=2 xiu=9.42 xid=-0.54)
    eValley"L1"(2)(ml=1.768 mt=0.0967 energy=0 alpha=0.5 degeneracy=1
        xiu=11.5 xid=-6.58)
}
```


Equation 198 and Equation 199 give expressions for the total \(n\) and \(i\)-valley \(n_{i}\) carrier concentrations. The valley occupation function \(n_{i} / n\) can be plotted using the following keywords in the Plot section: eValleyOccupation_name and hValleyOccupation_name, where name should correspond exactly to a valley name defined by the eValley or hValley statement in the simulation command file. For \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) bands, you should use kpDelta1, kpDelta2, and kpDelta3 as name for electrons and kpHH, kpLH, and kpSO as name for holes. If an undefined name is used, then Sentaurus Device stops the simulation at the plotting stage.

In some cases, using the total occupation of all valleys (the sum of all individual valley occupations) might be useful. It can be plotted by using the eAllValleyOccupation and hAllValleyOccupation keywords in the Plot section. Mostly, it should give a unit value, but when using the band tail model, you can see a carrier redistribution between the conduction (or valence) band and the tail bands (see Band Tails on page 340). These keywords always work for full conduction and valence bands even when not using the multivalley model.

\section*{Intervalley Transitions}

Explicit interactions between the different valleys can be described by introducing intervalley transition rate models and solving the intervalley transition rate equations. This allows you to go beyond the equilibrium description as shown so far and compute dynamic non-equilibrium valley densities.

[Page 351 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Multivalley Band Structure

The intervalley transition rate equation for electron valley \(i\) takes the following form (for holes the expressions are analogous):
\[
\frac{\partial n_{i}}{\partial t}=\sum_{j \neq i}^{N_{n}}-n_{i} f_{i j}(w)+n_{j} f_{j i}(w) \tag{213}
\]
where \(n_{i}\) describes the electron density for valley \(i, N_{n}\) is the number of electron valleys, and \(f_{i j}(w)\) is the transition rate model that describes the transition from valley \(i\) to valley \(j\) as a function of the driving force \(w\). Furthermore, it is always ensured that the individual valley densities sum to the total density (solution of the continuity equation) shown in Equation 198:
\[
n=\sum_{i=1}^{N_{n}} n_{i} \tag{214}
\]
and that the individual equilibrium densities of Equation 198 are restored if no interaction is present:
\[
n_{i}=N_{\mathrm{C}} g_{n}^{i} F\left(\frac{E_{F, n}-E_{\mathrm{C}}-\Delta E_{n}^{i}}{k T}\right) \tag{215}
\]
for \(w=0\). The function \(F()\) depends on the carrier statistics used.
The dynamic non-equilibrium valley densities are the main components to compute the explicit multivalley mobility as described in Explicit Multivalley Mobility Model on page 463.

\section*{Intervalley Transition Rate Models}

The intervalley transitions can be defined regionwise in the Physics section. The eTransitionRate() or hTransitionRate() statements are used to define the different transitions between electron valleys or hole valleys, respectively (see Table 241 on page 1666).
```
Physics {
    ...
    eTransitionRate(
        Transition "1" (
            Model = <string>
            ParameterSetName = <string>
            FromToValleyPairs = (<string>, ...)
            DrivingForce = <string>
        )
        Transition "2" (
            Model = <string>
            ParameterSetName = <string>
            FromToValleyPairs = (<string>, ...)
            DrivingForce = <string>
        )
        Transition "3" (...)
```

[Page 352 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Multivalley Band Structure
```
    ...
    )
    ...
}
```


The different transitions are organized using the Transition() keyword together with an arbitrary string tag. The Model sets the transition rate model used to describe the transitions between the valleys defined in the FromToValleyPairs list. This list of strings is read pairwise, and it is assumed that the transition occurs from the first valley to the second valley. Note that a physical setup requires that, for all valley pairs, transitions in both directions are defined (see the example in Solving the Intervalley Transition Rate Equation on page 354). Furthermore, the name of the corresponding parameter set is defined with ParameterSetName, and the driving force is provided through DrivingForce.

The available transition rate models are described next.

\section*{Müller Model}

The Müller model is described in [19] and models the transition between the \(\Gamma\)-valley and the \(L\)-valley of III-V semiconductor materials such as GaAs and InP . The intervalley transition rate models between the two valleys take the following form:
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\Gamma \rightarrow L: & f_{\Gamma L}(w)=f_{\Gamma L, \text { equ }}+a_{f} \ln \left(1+e^{\frac{w-w_{\mathrm{ivv}}}{w_{f}}}\right) \tag{216} \\
L \rightarrow \Gamma: & f_{L \Gamma}(w)=f_{L \Gamma, 0}+\delta_{f} w \tag{217}
\end{array}
\]

Here, \(w\) indicates the driving force, and \(a_{f}, \delta_{f}\), and \(f_{L \Gamma, 0}\) are the model parameters. The parameter \(w_{f}\) is a normalization constant ( \(=1 \mathrm{kV} / \mathrm{cm}\) ). The onset \(w_{\text {ivt }}\) in Equation 216 is modeled as a doping-dependent quantity:
\[
w_{\mathrm{ivt}}=w_{\mathrm{ivt}, 0}\left(1+\frac{N_{\mathrm{dop}}}{N_{\mathrm{ivt}}}\right)^{\xi_{\mathrm{ivt}}} \tag{218}
\]
with the model parameters \(w_{\text {ivt }, 0}, N_{\text {ivt }}\), and \(\xi_{\text {ivt }}\). The \(N_{\text {dop }}\) corresponds to the doping concentration. Finally, to restore the equilibrium densities if the driving force equals zero, the \(f_{\Gamma L, \text { equ }}\) term of Equation 216 is chosen so that the following expression is fulfilled:
\[
f_{\Gamma L}(w=0)=\frac{n_{L, \text { equ }}}{n_{\Gamma, \text { equ }}} f_{L \Gamma}(w=0) \tag{219}
\]

The supported driving forces (DrivingForce=) are the electric field (ElectricField), the gradient of the quasi-Fermi potential (GradQuasiFermi), and the hydrodynamic driving force (CarrierTempDrive). For details about the driving forces, see Driving Force Models on page 468.

[Page 353 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


The model (Model=) in Equation 216 is switched on with the keyword MuellerGammaL and, for the one in Equation 217, the keyword MuellerLGamma is used. Furthermore, the model parameters must be defined in the parameter file under the named parameter set TRM_Mueller. For example:
```
TRM_Mueller "ParamSetNameT1" {
    af_ivt = 0.36e12, //[Hz]
    EO_ivt = 3.0e3, //[V/cm]
    NO_ivt = 78.6e16, //[cm-3]
    zeta_ivt = 0.46, //[1]
    f0_ivt = 1.7e12 //[Hz]
    deltaF_ivt = 5.79e6 //[Hz/(V/cm)]
}
```


