\section*{Incomplete lonization}

This chapter discusses how to account for incomplete ionization in Sentaurus Device.

\section*{Considering Incomplete Ionization}

In silicon, with the exception of indium, dopants can be considered to be fully ionized at room temperature because the impurity levels are sufficiently shallow. However, when impurity levels are relatively deep compared to the thermal energy \(k T\), incomplete ionization must be considered. This is the case for indium acceptors in silicon and nitrogen donors and aluminum acceptors in silicon carbide. In addition, for simulations at reduced temperatures, incomplete ionization must be considered for all dopants. For these situations, Sentaurus Device has an ionization probability model based on activation energy. The ionization (activation) is computed separately for each species present.

All doping species for Sentaurus Device are defined in the datexcodes.txt file. To add new doping species or to modify an existing specification, see Specifying Doping Species on page 61.

\section*{Using the Incomplete lonization Model}

The incomplete ionization model is activated with the keyword IncompleteIonization in the Physics section:
```
Physics{ IncompleteIonization }
```


The incomplete ionization model for selected species is activated with the additional keyword Dopants:
```
Physics{ IncompleteIonization(Dopants = "Species_name1
    Species_name2 ...") }
```


For example, the following command line activates the model only for boron:
```
Physics{ IncompleteIonization(Dopants = "BoronActiveConcentration") }
```

[Page 358 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Using the Incomplete Ionization Model

The incomplete ionization model can be specified in region or material physics (see Region-Specific and Material-Specific Models on page 68). In this case, the model is activated only in these regions or materials.

Using DonorPlusConcentration and AccepMinusConcentration in the Plot section of the device, you can visualize the ionized donor and acceptor concentrations, respectively. The net ionized doping concentration can be plotted using IonizedDopingConcentration or DopingConcentration:
```
IonizedDopingConcentration (DopingConcentration)=DonorPlusConcentration-
AccepMinusConcentration
```


Finally, the substitutional (active) net concentration can be plotted using
```
ActiveDopingConcentration:
ActiveDopingConcentration=DonorConcentration-AcceptorConcentration
```


\section*{Note:}

Incomplete ionization is implemented in terms of traps and, therefore, is affected by setting the trap occupation explicitly (see Explicit Trap Occupation on page 571). Use named traps to avoid affecting dopant ionization by settings intended for real traps only.

\section*{Incomplete Ionization Model}

The concentration of ionized impurity atoms is given by Fermi-Dirac distribution:
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
N_{\mathrm{D}}=\frac{N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}}{1+g_{\mathrm{D}} \exp \left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{\mathrm{D}}}{k T}\right)} & \text { for } N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}<N_{\mathrm{D}, \text { crit }} \tag{220} \\
N_{\mathrm{A}}=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}}{1+g_{\mathrm{A}} \exp \left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{A}}-E_{\mathrm{F}, p}}{k T}\right)} & \text { for } N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}<N_{\mathrm{A}, \text { crit }} \tag{221}
\end{array}
\]
where \(N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}\) and \(N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}\) are the substitutional (active) donor and acceptor concentrations, \(g_{\mathrm{D}}\) and \(g_{\mathrm{A}}\) are the degeneracy factors for the impurity levels, and \(E_{\mathrm{D}}\) and \(E_{\mathrm{A}}\) are the donor and acceptor ionization (activation) energies.

In the literature [1], incomplete ionization in SiC material has been considered and another general distribution function has been proposed, which can be expressed as:
\[
N_{\mathrm{D}}=\frac{N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}}{1+G_{\mathrm{D}}(T) \exp \left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{\mathrm{C}}}{k T}\right)} \tag{222}
\]

[Page 359 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Using the Incomplete Ionization Model
\[
N_{\mathrm{A}}=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}}{1+G_{\mathrm{A}}(T) \exp \left(-\frac{E_{\mathrm{F}, p}-E_{\mathrm{V}}}{k T}\right)} \tag{223}
\]
where \(G_{\mathrm{D}}(T)\) and \(G_{\mathrm{A}}(T)\) are the ionization factors discussed in [2][3]. These factors can be defined by a PMI (see [1] and Example: Matsuura Incomplete Ionization on page 1510).

By comparing Equation 220 and Equation 221 to Equation 222 and Equation 223, it can be seen that, in the case of the Fermi distribution function, the ionization factors can be written as:
\[
\begin{gathered}
G_{\mathrm{D}}(T)=g_{\mathrm{D}} \cdot \exp \left(\frac{\Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}}{k T}\right), \Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}=E_{\mathrm{C}}-E_{\mathrm{D}} \\
\text { and } \\
G_{\mathrm{A}}(T)=g_{\mathrm{A}} \cdot \exp \left(\frac{\Delta E_{\mathrm{A}}}{k T}\right), \Delta E_{\mathrm{A}}=E_{\mathrm{A}}-E_{\mathrm{V}}
\end{gathered} \tag{224}
\]

In Sentaurus Device, the basic variables are potential, electron concentration, and hole concentration. Therefore, it is more convenient to rewrite Equation 220 and Equation 221 in terms of the carrier concentration instead of the quasi-Fermi levels:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{\mathrm{D}}=\frac{N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}}{1+g_{\mathrm{D}} \frac{n}{n_{1}}}, \text { with } n_{1}=N_{\mathrm{C}} \exp \left(-\frac{\Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}}{k T}\right) \text { for } N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}<N_{\mathrm{D}, \text { crit }} \tag{225} \\
& N_{\mathrm{A}}=\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}}{1+g_{\mathrm{A}} \frac{p}{p_{1}}}, \text { with } p_{1}=N_{\mathrm{V}} \exp \left(-\frac{\Delta E_{\mathrm{A}}}{k T}\right) \text { for } N_{\mathrm{A}}<N_{\mathrm{A}, \text { crit }} \tag{226}
\end{aligned}
\]

The expressions for \(n_{1}\) and \(p_{1}\) in these two equations are valid for Boltzmann statistics and without quantization. If Fermi-Dirac statistics or a quantization model (see Chapter 14 on page 367 ) is used, then \(n_{1}\) and \(p_{1}\) are multiplied by the coefficients \(\gamma_{n}\) and \(\gamma_{p}\) defined in Equation 48 and Equation 49 (see Fermi Statistics on page 246). For \(N_{\mathrm{D} / \mathrm{A}}>N_{\mathrm{D} / \mathrm{A}}\), crit , the dopants are assumed to be completely ionized, in which case, every donor and acceptor species is considered in the Poisson equation. The values of \(N_{\mathrm{D}, \text { crit }}\) and \(N_{\mathrm{A}, \text { crit }}\) can be adjusted in the parameter file of Sentaurus Device.

To provide a complete ionization for high doping concentrations, the donor and acceptor activation energies are effectively reduced by the total doping in the semiconductor [4]. It also suggests to have an additional temperature dependence in the activation energy as a fitting option. This is accounted for in the expressions:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}=\Delta E_{\mathrm{D}, 0}-\alpha_{\mathrm{D}} \cdot N_{\text {tot }}^{1 / 3}+\beta_{\mathrm{D}}\left[\left(\frac{300}{T}\right)^{\gamma_{\mathrm{D}}}-1\right] \frac{k T}{q} \tag{227} \\
& \Delta E_{\mathrm{A}}=\Delta E_{\mathrm{A}, 0}-\alpha_{\mathrm{A}} \cdot N_{\text {tot }}^{1 / 3}+\beta_{\mathrm{A}}\left[\left(\frac{300}{T}\right)^{\gamma_{\mathrm{A}}}-1\right] \frac{k T}{q} \tag{228}
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 360 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Using the Incomplete Ionization Model

where:
- \(N_{\text {tot }}=N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}+N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}\) is the total doping concentration.
- \(\quad T\) is the lattice temperature.
- \(\alpha_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}, \beta_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\), and \(\gamma_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\) are model fitting parameters.

The development undertaken in [5] and [6] suggests an alternative Altermatt ionization model, which is based on accounting for changes introduced by impurities into the semiconductor density-of-states. This model is still based on Equation 225 and Equation 226, but with some modifications of the degeneracy factors \(g_{\mathrm{D}}\) and \(g_{\mathrm{A}}\), and the activation energies \(\Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}\) and \(\Delta E_{\mathrm{A}}\) :
\[
\begin{aligned}
& g_{\mathrm{D}}^{\prime}=\frac{b_{\mathrm{D}}}{g_{\mathrm{D}}+1-b_{\mathrm{D}} \frac{n}{n_{1}}}, \quad g_{\mathrm{A}}^{\prime}=\frac{b_{\mathrm{A}}}{g_{\mathrm{A}}+\left(1-b_{\mathrm{A}}\right) \frac{p}{p_{1}}}, \quad b_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}=\frac{1}{1+N_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}, 0} / N_{\mathrm{b}}^{d_{\mathrm{b}}}} \tag{229} \\
& \Delta E_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}=\frac{\Delta E_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}, 0}}{1+\left(N_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}, 0} / N_{\mathrm{E}}\right)^{d_{\mathrm{E}}}}+\beta_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\left[\left(\frac{300}{T}\right)^{\gamma_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}}-1\right] \frac{k T}{q} \tag{230}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(N_{\mathrm{b}}, d_{\mathrm{b}}, N_{\mathrm{E}}\), and \(d_{\mathrm{E}}\) are additional fitting parameters of the model defined for each impurity separately, and the last term in Equation 230 is added similarly to Equation 227 and Equation 228 for fitting purposes.

In transient simulations, the terms:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\partial N_{\mathrm{D}}}{\partial t}=\sigma_{\mathrm{D}} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{n}\left[\frac{n_{1}}{g_{\mathrm{D}}} N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}-\left(n+\frac{n_{1}}{g_{\mathrm{D}}}\right) N_{\mathrm{D}}\right] \tag{231} \\
& \frac{\partial N_{\mathrm{A}}}{\partial t}=\sigma_{\mathrm{A}} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p}\left[\frac{p_{1}}{g_{\mathrm{A}}} N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}-\left(p+\frac{p_{1}}{g_{\mathrm{A}}}\right) N_{\mathrm{A}}\right] \tag{232}
\end{aligned}
\]
are included in the continuity equations, where \(v_{\mathrm{th}}^{n, p}\) denotes the carrier thermal velocities, and \(\sigma_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\) is the capture or emission cross-section.

For very low temperature applications, a field-enhanced ionization of impurities might play an important role. Generally, the ionization equations, such as Equation 231 and Equation 232, involve an account of the emission and capture carrier fluxes with the conduction band or valence band. These equations are the same as described for the trap model in Local Capture and Emission Rates on page 576. The field-enhanced ionization of the incomplete ionization model enhances the emission cross-section with the following allowed models: J-Model for Cross Sections on page 577, Hurkx Model for Cross Sections on page 578, and Poole-Frenkel Model for Cross Sections on page 578.

