Physical Model Parameters

\section*{Physical Model Parameters}

You can access the values of the dopant level \(E_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}, 0}\), the doping- and temperature-dependent shift parameters \(\alpha_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}, \beta_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\), and \(\gamma_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\), the impurity degeneracy factor \(g_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\), and the cross section \(\sigma_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\) in the parameter set Ionization.

For each ionized doping species, the Ionization parameter set must contain a separate subsection where the parameters \(E_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}, 0}, \alpha_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}, \beta_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}, \gamma_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}, g_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\), and \(\sigma_{\mathrm{A} / \mathrm{D}}\) are defined. For example, for the dopant BoronActiveConcentration, described in Specifying Doping Species on page 61, for the material silicon, the parameter set is:
```
Material = "Silicon" {
    ...
    Ionization {
    \text { ⋯ }
        Species ("BoronActiveConcentration") {
            type = acceptor
            E_0 = 0.045 # [eV]
            alpha = 3.1e-8 # [eV cm]
            beta = 0 # [1]
            gamma = 1 # [1]
            g = 4 # [1]
            Xsec = 1.0e-12 # [cm^2]
            Xsec_formula = 1
            highdop_formula = 1
        }
    }
}
```


You can omit the field type because the dopant type is specified in the datexcodes.txt file. It is used here for informative purposes only.

To activate the Altermatt ionization model defined by Equation 229 and Equation 230, specifyhighdop_formula=2 as well as the additional parameters \(N_{\mathrm{b}}, d_{\mathrm{b}}, N_{\mathrm{E}}\), and \(d_{\mathrm{E}}\). For example, for boron, it should be as follows:
```
Species ("BoronActiveConcentration") {
    highdop_formula = 2
    b_Nref = 6e18 # [cm^-3]
    b_pow = 2.4 # [1]
    E_Nref = 1.7e18 # [cm^-3]
    E_pow = 1.4 # [1]
}
```

