For the former, the quantization mass is given by:
\[
m_{z, v}=\frac{m_{0}}{A \pm \sqrt{B+C \cdot\left(z_{1}^{2} z_{2}^{2}+z_{2}^{2} z_{3}^{2}+z_{3}^{2} z_{1}^{2}\right)}} \tag{239}
\]

For the latter, ml and mh (given as multiples of \(m_{0}\) ) determine directly the masses for the light-hole and heavy-hole bands.

The masses \(m_{x y, v}\) are chosen to achieve the same density-of-states mass as used in classical simulations. For electrons:
\[
m_{x y, \mathrm{v}}=\frac{m_{n}^{3 / 2}}{m_{z, \mathrm{v}}^{1 / 2} n_{\mathrm{v}}} \tag{240}
\]
where \(n_{\mathrm{v}}\) is the number of band valleys (or bands). The expression for holes is analogous.
SchroedingerParameters offers a parameter pair offset to model the lifting of the degeneracy of band minima in strained materials. Unless exactly two ladders exist, offset

