References

\begin{figure}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Figure 19 Thickness extraction}
\includegraphics[alt={},max width=\textwidth]{https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/f7af57de-59b5-428e-a177-d4f23fc59969-161.jpg?height=323&width=364&top_left_y=406&top_left_x=489}
\end{figure}

The angle between the normal vectors \(C_{1}\) and \(C_{2}\) is \(90^{\circ}\). Therefore, if the value of \(\beta\) is greater than \(90^{\circ}\) but smaller than \(180^{\circ}\), the smaller circle is not considered. Instead, the larger circle (with a second touch point \(C_{2}{ }^{\prime}\) ) determines the layer thickness; for this circle, the angle between the normal vectors is \(180^{\circ}\).

There is another option to compute the layer thickness, which also is based on considered spheres (or circles in Figure 19 for the 2D case), but with some of the following modifications. The above algorithm for each point \(P\) (that is, for each mesh element center) constructs a sphere that satisfies the described conditions. As a result, you have a set of spheres that cover the region where the thickness should be computed. After that, for each mesh element (the point \(P\) ), you check whether this point is inside some subset of spheres, and you take the maximum sphere diameter \(d_{m}\) from this subset as the thickness for the point \(P\). This way might be useful for spherical, circular, or nonplanar boundaries.

The user-defined keyword MaxFitWeight controls this option as follows:
\[
t_{m}=\alpha_{m} d_{m}+\left(1-\alpha_{m}\right) t \tag{258}
\]
where \(t\) is the thickness from Equation 257, and \(\alpha_{m}\) is defined by the keyword MaxFitWeight and is equal to zero by default.

