\section*{15}

\section*{Mobility}

This chapter describes the mobility models implemented in Sentaurus Device.

\section*{Introduction to Mobility Models}

Sentaurus Device uses a modular approach for the description of the carrier mobilities. In the simplest case, mobility is a function of the lattice temperature. The constant mobility model should be used only for undoped materials (see Mobility due to Phonon Scattering on page 405). For doped materials, the carriers scatter with the impurities. This leads to a degradation of the mobility. Doping-Dependent Mobility Degradation on page 406 introduces the models that describe this effect.

Models that describe the effects of carrier-carrier scattering are presented in CarrierCarrier Scattering on page 414. The Philips unified mobility model is a well-calibrated model that accounts for both impurity and carrier-carrier scattering (see Philips Unified Mobility Model on page 416).

Models that describe the mobility degradation at interfaces, for example, the silicon-oxide interface in the channel region of a MOSFET, are introduced in Mobility Degradation at Interfaces on page 421. These models account for the scattering with surface phonons and surface roughness.

Finally, models that describe mobility degradation in high electric fields are discussed in High-Field Saturation Models on page 457. A flexible model for hydrodynamic simulations is described in Energy-Dependent Mobility on page 904.

\section*{Combining Mobility Models}

Mobility models are selected in the Physics section as options to Mobility, eMobility, or hMobility:
```
Physics{ Mobility( <arguments> ) ... }
```


Specifications with eMobility apply to electrons; specifications with hMobility apply to holes; and specifications with Mobility apply to both carrier types.

[Page 404 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Mobility due to Phonon Scattering

If more than one mobility model is activated for a carrier type, then the different mobility contributions \(\left(\mu_{1}, \mu_{2}, \ldots\right)\) for bulk, surface mobility, and thin layers are combined by Matthiessen's rule:
\[
\frac{1}{\mu}=\frac{1}{\mu_{1}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{2}}+\ldots
\]

If the high-field saturation model is activated, the final mobility is computed in two steps. First, the low field mobility \(\mu_{\text {low }}\) is determined according to Equation 259. Second, the final mobility is computed from a (model-dependent) formula as a function of a driving force \(F_{\mathrm{hfs}}\) :
\[
\mu=f\left(\mu_{\mathrm{low}}, F_{\mathrm{hfs}}\right)
\]

\section*{Mobility due to Phonon Scattering}

The constant mobility model [1] is active by default. It accounts only for phonon scattering and, therefore, it is dependent only on the lattice temperature:
\[
\mu_{\text {const }}=\mu_{L}\left(\frac{T}{300 K}\right)^{-\zeta}
\]
where \(\mu_{L}\) is the mobility due to bulk phonon scattering. The default values of \(\mu_{L}\) and the exponent \(\zeta\) are listed in Table 50. The parameters of the constant mobility model are accessible in the constantMobility parameter set.

\begin{table}
