\section*{Low-Field Ballistic Mobility Models}

You can use one of the following models to describe ballistic mobility.

\section*{Simple Channel Length-Dependent Ballistic Mobility Model}

This model is based on Shur [6] and is given by the following simple expression, where ballistic mobility is proportional to the channel length:
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{bal}}=k \cdot L_{\mathrm{ch}}
\]

Both \(k\) and \(L_{\mathrm{ch}}\) are model parameters. In most cases, you specify a value for \(L_{\mathrm{ch}}\) (in nm ) that corresponds to the actual channel length for the device being simulated. You can adjust the parameter \(k\) to match measured device characteristics.

\begin{table}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Table 56 Simple ballistic mobility model: Default coefficients for silicon}
\begin{tabular}{lllll}
\hline Symbol & Parameter name & Electrons & Holes & Unit \\
\hline\(k\) & k & 20.0 & 20.0 & \(\mathrm{~cm}^{2} / \mathrm{Vsnm}\) \\
\(L_{\mathrm{ch}}\) & Lch & \(10^{7}\) & \(10^{7}\) & nm \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\section*{Injection Velocity-Dependent Ballistic Mobility Model}

This model includes the finite injection velocity from the source and drain with the mobility concept [7] and is given by the following expression:
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{bal}}=f \cdot L_{\mathrm{ch}}
\]

Here, \(f\) is a function of injection velocity. The functional form of \(f\) is given as follows:
\[
f=\frac{1}{V_{\mathrm{ds}}+V_{\mathrm{b}}} \frac{V_{\mathrm{b}}}{V_{\mathrm{ds}, \operatorname{lin}}}\left(\frac{L_{\mathrm{ch}}}{L_{\mathrm{ref}}}\right)^{\alpha} V_{\mathrm{inj}} \frac{1-\exp \left(-\frac{V_{\mathrm{ds}}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right)}{1+\exp \left(-\frac{V_{\mathrm{ds}}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right)}
\]
where:
- \(\alpha, L_{\mathrm{ch}}, L_{\mathrm{ref}}, V_{\mathrm{b}}, V_{\mathrm{ds}}, V_{\mathrm{ds}, \mathrm{lin}}\), and \(V_{\mathrm{inj}}\) are model parameters (see Table 57).
- \(\quad T\) is the lattice temperature.
- \(k_{\mathrm{B}}\) is the Boltzmann constant.

