\section*{Philips Unified Mobility Model}

The Philips unified mobility model, proposed by Klaassen [11], unifies the description of majority and minority carrier bulk mobilities. In addition to describing the temperature dependence of the mobility, the model takes into account electron-hole scattering, screening of ionized impurities by charge carriers, and clustering of impurities.

The Philips unified mobility model is well calibrated. Though it was initially used primarily for bipolar devices, it is widely used for MOS devices.

\section*{Using the Philips Unified Mobility Model}

There are different methods for activating the Philips unified mobility model.
As described in Using Doping-Dependent Mobility on page 406, you can activate the model by specifying PhuMob as an option to DopingDependence. This method is required if you want to combine PhuMob with an additional doping-dependent model (for example, a doping-dependent PMI model to account for other degradation effects).

[Page 416 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Philips Unified Mobility Model

Alternatively, you can activate the Philips unified mobility model by specifying the PhuMob option to Mobility directly:
```
Physics{ Mobility ( PhuMob ... ) ... }
```


Specifying PhuMob in this way causes Sentaurus Device to completely ignore any specification made with DopingDependence, if present, to avoid accidental double-counting of mobility effects.

The PhuMob model also can be activated with an additional option:
```
Physics{ Mobility ( PhuMob[(Arsenic | Phosphorus)] ...) ... }
```


The option Arsenic or Phosphorus specifies which parameters (see Table 61 on page 420) are used. These parameters reflect the different electron mobility degradation that is observed in the presence of these donor species.

\section*{Note:}

The Philips unified mobility model describes mobility degradation due to both impurity scattering and carrier-carrier scattering mechanisms. Therefore, the keyword PhuMob must not be combined with the keyword DopingDependence or CarrierCarrierScattering. If a combination of these keywords is specified, Sentaurus Device uses only the Philips unified mobility model.

\section*{Using an Alternative Philips Unified Mobility Model}

Sentaurus Device provides an extended PMI reimplementation of the Philips unified mobility model (see Doping-Dependent Mobility on page 1315). To use it, specify PhuMob2 as the option for DopingDependence:
```
Physics { Mobility (DopingDependence(PhuMob2)...)...}
```


The reimplementation uses the PhuMob2 parameter set. The parameter FACT_G has a default value of 1. It modifies the function \(G\left(P_{i}\right)\) shown in Equation 292 by a factor \(G\left(P_{i}\right)=\) FACT_G (right-hand side in Equation 292). Otherwise, the reimplementation fully agrees with the model described below.

\section*{Description of the Philips Unified Mobility Model}

According to the Philips unified mobility model, there are two contributions to carrier mobilities. The first, \(\mu_{i, \mathrm{~L}}\), represents phonon (lattice) scattering and the second, \(\mu_{i, \text { DAeh }}\), accounts for all other bulk scattering mechanisms (due to free carriers, and ionized donors and acceptors).

[Page 417 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Philips Unified Mobility Model

These partial mobilities are combined to give the bulk mobility \(\mu_{i, \mathrm{~b}}\) for each carrier according to Matthiessen's rule:
\[
\frac{1}{\mu_{i, \mathrm{~b}}}=\frac{1}{\mu_{i, \mathrm{~L}}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{i, \mathrm{DAeh}}}
\]

In Equation 280 and all of the following model equations, the index \(i\) takes the value 'e' for electrons and ' \(h\) ' for holes. The first contribution due to lattice scattering takes the form:
\[
\mu_{i, \mathrm{~L}}=\mu_{i, \max }\left(\frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{-\theta_{i}}
\]

The second contribution has the form:
\[
\mu_{i, \mathrm{DAeh}}=\mu_{i, N}\left(\frac{N_{i, \mathrm{sc}}}{N_{i, \mathrm{sc}, \mathrm{eff}}}\right)\left(\frac{N_{i, \mathrm{ref}}}{N_{i, \mathrm{sc}}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}+\mu_{i, \mathrm{c}}\left(\frac{n+p}{N_{i, \mathrm{sc}, \mathrm{eff}}}\right)
\]
with:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\mu_{i, N} & =\frac{\mu_{i, \max }^{2}}{\mu_{i, \max }-\mu_{i, \min }}\left(\frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{3 \alpha_{i}-1.5} \\
\mu_{i, \mathrm{c}} & =\frac{\mu_{i, \max } \mu_{i, \min }}{\mu_{i, \max }-\mu_{i, \min }}\left(\frac{300 K}{T}\right)^{0.5}
\end{aligned}
\]
for electrons:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{\mathrm{e}, \mathrm{sc}}=N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}+N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}+p \\
& N_{\mathrm{e}, \mathrm{sc}, \mathrm{eff}}=N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}+G\left(P_{\mathrm{e}}\right) N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}+f_{\mathrm{e}} \frac{p}{F\left(P_{\mathrm{e}}\right)}
\end{aligned}
\]
and for holes:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{\mathrm{h}, \mathrm{sc}}=N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}+N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}+n \\
& N_{\mathrm{h}, \mathrm{sc}, \text { eff }}=N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}+G\left(P_{\mathrm{h}}\right) N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}+f_{\mathrm{h}} \frac{n}{F\left(P_{\mathrm{h}}\right)}
\end{aligned}
\]

The effects of clustering of donors \(\left(N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}\right)\) and acceptors \(\left(N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}\right)\) at ultrahigh concentrations are described by 'clustering' functions \(Z_{\mathrm{D}}\) and \(Z_{\mathrm{A}}\), which are defined as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}=N_{\mathrm{D}, 0} Z_{\mathrm{D}}=N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}\left[1+\frac{N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}^{2}}{c_{\mathrm{D}} N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}^{2}+N_{\mathrm{D}, \text { ref }}^{2}}\right] \\
& N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}=N_{\mathrm{A}, 0} Z_{\mathrm{A}}=N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}\left[1+\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}^{2}}{c_{\mathrm{A}} N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}^{2}+N_{\mathrm{A}, \text { ref }}^{2}}\right]
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 418 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Philips Unified Mobility Model

The analytic functions \(G\left(P_{i}\right)\) and \(F\left(P_{i}\right)\) in Equation 286 and Equation 288 describe minority impurity and electron-hole scattering. They are given by:
\[
F\left(P_{i}\right)=\frac{0.7643 P_{i}^{0.6478}+2.2999+6.5502\left(m_{i}{ }_{i} / m^{*}{ }_{j}\right)}{P_{i}^{0.6478}+2.3670-0.8552\left(m^{*}{ }_{i} / m^{*}{ }_{j}\right)}
\]
and:
\[
G\left(P_{i}\right)=1-a_{\mathrm{g}}\left[b_{\mathrm{g}}+P_{i}\left(\frac{m_{0}}{m^{*}} \frac{T}{i 00 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{\alpha_{\mathrm{g}}}\right]^{-\beta_{\mathrm{g}}}+c_{\mathrm{g}}\left[P_{i}\left(\frac{m^{*}}{m_{0}} \frac{300 K}{T}\right)^{\alpha_{\mathrm{g}}}\right]^{-\gamma_{\mathrm{g}}}
\]
where \(m^{*}{ }_{i}\) denotes a fit parameter for carrier \(i\) (which is related to the effective carrier mass) and \(m^{*}{ }_{j}\) denotes a fit parameter for the other carrier.

\section*{Screening Parameter}

The screening parameter \(P_{i}\) is given by a weighted harmonic mean of the Brooks-Herring approach and Conwell-Weisskopf approach:
\[
P_{i}=\left[\frac{f_{\mathrm{CW}}}{3.97 \times 10^{13} \mathrm{~cm}^{-2} N_{i, \mathrm{sc}}^{-2 / 3}}+f_{\mathrm{BH}} \frac{(n+p)}{1.36 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}} \frac{m_{0}}{m^{*}}{ }_{i}\right]^{-1}\left(\frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{2}
\]

The evaluation of \(G\left(P_{i}\right)\) depends on the value of the screening parameter \(P_{i}\). For values of \(P_{i}<P_{i, \min }, G\left(P_{i, \min }\right)\) is used instead of \(G\left(P_{i}\right)\), where \(P_{i, \min }\) is the value at which \(G\left(P_{i}\right)\) reaches its minimum. If \(G\left(P_{i, \min }\right)\) is negative, which might happen in the model for the lattice temperature \(T\) below 50 K , then \(\left|G\left(P_{i, \text { min }}\right)\right|\) is used for \(G\left(P_{i}\right)<\left|G\left(P_{i, \text { min }}\right)\right|\).

