\section*{Stress Factors for Mobility Components}

If isotropic stress-dependent mobility enhancement factors are applied to mobility components (see Factor Models Applied to Mobility Components on page 1020), the Lombardi mobility components become:
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\mu_{\mathrm{ac}}^{\prime}=\gamma_{\mathrm{ac}} \mu_{\mathrm{ac}}, & \gamma_{\mathrm{ac}}=1+a_{\mathrm{ac}}(\gamma-1) \\
\mu_{\mathrm{sr}}^{\prime}=\gamma_{\mathrm{sr}} \mu_{\mathrm{sr}}, & \gamma_{\mathrm{sr}}=1+a_{\mathrm{sr}}(\gamma-1)
\end{array}
\]
where \(a_{\mathrm{ac}}\) and \(a_{\mathrm{sr}}\) are stress scaling parameters that can be specified in the parameter set EnormalDependence, and \(\gamma\) is an isotropic enhancement factor calculated from a stress-dependent Factor model (see Isotropic Factor Models on page 1014).

In Equation 295, the exponent of the temperature \((k)\) is a constant, which corresponds to the default behavior. For a more accurate treatment of mobility as a function of temperature (particularly, mobility at low temperatures), the exponent becomes a function of temperature itself. For more details, see Low-Temperature Phonon Exponent Correction for Mobility Models on page 453 and Enhanced Lombardi Mobility Model on page 455.

\section*{Named Parameter Sets for the Lombardi Model}

The EnormalDependence parameter set can be named. For example, in the parameter file, you can write:
```
EnormalDependence "myset" { ... }
```

to declare a parameter set with the name myset. To use a named parameter set, specify its name with ParameterSetName as an option to Lombardi in the command file.

[Page 425 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Degradation at Interfaces

For example:
```
Mobility (
    Enormal( Lombardi( ParameterSetName = "myset" ...) ...)
)
```


By default, the unnamed parameter set is used.

\section*{Auto-Orientation for the Lombardi Model}

The Lombardi model supports the auto-orientation framework (see Auto-Orientation Framework on page 91 ) that switches between different-named parameter sets based on the orientation of the nearest interface. This can be activated by specifying the Lombardi command file parameter AutoOrientation:
```
Mobility (
    Enormal( Lombardi( AutoOrientation ...) ...)
)
```


\section*{Inversion and Accumulation Layer Mobility Model}

The inversion and accumulation layer mobility (IALMob) model is based on the unified portion of the model described in [13]. This model includes doping and transverse-field dependencies and is similar to the Lucent (Darwish) model [12], but it contains additional terms that account for two-dimensional Coulomb impurity scattering. The implementation of the IALMob model is based on modified versions of the Philips Unified Mobility Model on page 416 and the Enhanced Lombardi Model on page 422, but it is completely self-contained and all parameters associated with this model are specified independently of those models. A complete description is given here.

The following expressions apply to both electron mobility and hole mobility when the following substitutions are made:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\text { Electron Mobility: } & c=n, c_{\mathrm{other}}=p, N_{\mathrm{inv}}=N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}, N_{\mathrm{acc}}=N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}, P=P_{\mathrm{e}}, m^{*}=m_{\mathrm{e}}^{*}, m_{\mathrm{other}}^{*}=m_{\mathrm{h}}^{*} \\
\text { Hole Mobility: } & c=p, c_{\mathrm{other}}=n, N_{\mathrm{inv}}=N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}, N_{\mathrm{acc}}=N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}, P=P_{\mathrm{h}}, m^{*}=m_{\mathrm{h}}^{*}, m_{\mathrm{other}}^{*}=m_{\mathrm{e}}^{*}
\end{aligned}
\]

The model has contributions from Coulomb impurity scattering, phonon scattering, and surface roughness scattering:
\[
\frac{1}{\mu}=\frac{1}{\mu_{C}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{ph}}}+\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{sr}}}
\]
where \(D=\exp \left(-x / l_{\text {crit }}\right)\) ( \(x\) is the distance from the interface).

[Page 426 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Degradation at Interfaces

\section*{Coulomb Scattering}

The Coulomb impurity scattering term has 2D and 3D contributions. The 2D contribution is primarily due to effects occurring near the interface and the 3D contribution is primarily due to effects occurring in the bulk. These contributions are combined using a field-dependent function \(f\left(F_{\perp}, t, T\right)\) and a distance factor \(D_{C}\) :
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{C}}=\mu_{\mathrm{C}, 3 \mathrm{D}}\left(1-D_{\mathrm{C}}\right)+D_{\mathrm{C}}\left[f\left(F_{\perp}, t, T\right) \mu_{\mathrm{C}, 3 \mathrm{D}}+\left(1-f\left(F_{\perp}, t, T\right)\right) \mu_{\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{D}}\right]
\]
where:
\[
f\left(F_{\perp}, t, T\right)=\frac{1}{1+\exp \left(\frac{S F_{\perp}^{2 / 3}}{T}+\frac{S_{\mathrm{t}}}{\left(t+t_{0}\right)^{2} T}-p\right)}
\]
and \(D_{\mathrm{C}}=\exp \left(-x / l_{\text {crit, } \mathrm{C}}\right)\). In Equation 303, \(t\) is the local layer thickness (see Thickness Extraction on page 400), which is calculated automatically when using the ThinLayer mobility model (see Thin-Layer Mobility Model on page 446) or if the LayerThickness command in the Physics section is used to calculate layer thickness.

Two-dimensional Coulomb scattering has both inversion and accumulation layer contributions, and also includes a dependency on the local layer thickness:
\[
\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{D}}}=\operatorname{erf}\left(\frac{t+t_{1}}{t_{\text {Coulomb }}}\right)\left(\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{inv}}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{acc}}}\right)
\]
where:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \mu_{\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \text { inv }}=\left[\left(\frac{D_{1, \text { inv }}(T / 300 \mathrm{~K})^{\alpha_{1, \text { inv }}}\left(c / N_{\mathrm{sc}, \text { ref }}\right)^{v_{0, \text { inv }, \text { dop }}}}{\left(N_{\text {inv }} / N_{\text {dop }, \text { ref }}\right)^{v_{1, \text { inv }}}}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{D_{2, \text { inv }}(T / 300 \mathrm{~K})^{\alpha_{2, \text { inv }}}}{\left(N_{\text {inv }} / N_{\text {dop }, \text { ref }}\right)^{v_{2, \text { inv }}}}\right)^{2}\right]^{1 / 2} \\
& \mu_{\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{acc}}=\left[\left(\frac{D_{1, \mathrm{acc}}(T / 300 \mathrm{~K})^{\alpha_{1, \mathrm{acc}}}\left(c / N_{\mathrm{sc}, \text { ref }}\right)^{v_{0, \mathrm{acc}, \mathrm{dop}}}}{\left(N_{\mathrm{acc}} / N_{\mathrm{dop}, \mathrm{ref}}\right)^{v_{1, \mathrm{acc}}}}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{D_{2, \mathrm{acc}}(T / 300 \mathrm{~K})^{\alpha_{2, \mathrm{acc}}}}{\left(N_{\mathrm{acc}} / N_{\mathrm{dop}, \mathrm{ref}}\right)^{v_{2, \mathrm{acc}}}}\right)^{2}\right]^{1 / 2} G(P)
\end{aligned}
\]
and:
- \(v_{0, \text { inv }, \text { dop }}=v_{0, \text { inv }}+v_{0, \text { inv }, \mathrm{A}} \ln \left(\frac{N_{\text {inv }}}{N_{\text {dop }, \text { ref }}}\right)\)
- \(v_{0, \mathrm{acc}, \mathrm{dop}}=v_{0, \mathrm{acc}}+v_{0, \mathrm{acc}, \mathrm{A}} \ln \left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{acc}}}{N_{\mathrm{dop}, \mathrm{ref}}}\right)\)

[Page 427 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Degradation at Interfaces

The 3D Coulomb scattering part of Equation 302 is taken from the Philips unified mobility model (PhuMob) and is given by:
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{C}, 3 \mathrm{D}}=\mu_{N}\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{sc}}}{N_{\mathrm{sc}, \text { eff }}}\right)\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{ref}}}{N_{\mathrm{sc}}}\right)^{\alpha}+\mu_{\mathrm{c}}\left(\frac{c+c_{\text {other }}}{N_{\mathrm{sc}, \text { eff }}}\right)
\]
where:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \mu_{N}=\frac{\mu_{\max }^{2}}{\mu_{\max }-\mu_{\min }}\left(\frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{3 \alpha-1.5} \\
& \mu_{\mathrm{c}}=\frac{\mu_{\max } \mu_{\min }}{\mu_{\max }-\mu_{\min }}\left(\frac{300 \mathrm{~K}}{T}\right)^{1 / 2} \\
& N_{\mathrm{sc}}=N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}+N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}+c_{\text {other }} \\
& N_{\mathrm{sc}, \text { eff }}=N_{\mathrm{acc}}^{*}+G(P) N_{\mathrm{inv}}^{*}+\frac{c_{\text {other }}}{F(P)}
\end{aligned}
\]

In the previous expressions, quantities marked with an asterisk (*) indicate that the clustering formulas from the Philips unified mobility model are invoked:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{\mathrm{D}}^{*}=N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}\left[1+\frac{N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}^{2}}{c_{\mathrm{D}} N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}^{2}+N_{\mathrm{D}, \text { ref }}^{2}}\right] \\
& N_{\mathrm{A}}^{*}=N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}\left[1+\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}^{2}}{c_{\mathrm{A}} N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}^{2}+N_{\mathrm{A}, \text { ref }}^{2}}\right]
\end{aligned}
\]

Optionally, the clustering formulas can be used for all occurrences of \(N_{\mathrm{A}}\) and \(N_{\mathrm{D}}\) in the model by specifying the IALMob command file parameter ClusteringEverywhere.

The AsPhPhuMob option activates linear interpolation between the arsenic and phosphorus PhuMob parameter sets with respect to the arsenic and phosphorus concentrations.

The functions \(F(P)\) and \(G(P)\) describe electron-hole and minority impurity scattering, respectively, and \(P\) is a screening parameter:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& F(P)=\frac{0.7643 P^{0.6478}+2.2999+6.5502\left(\mathrm{~m}^{*} / \mathrm{m}_{\text {other }}^{*}\right)}{P^{0.6478}+2.3670-0.8552\left(\mathrm{~m}^{*} / \mathrm{m}_{\text {other }}^{*}\right)} \\
& G(P)=1-\frac{0.89233}{\left[0.41372+P\left(\frac{m_{0}}{m^{*}} \frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{0.28227}\right]^{0.19778}}+\frac{0.005978}{\left[P\left(\frac{m^{*}}{m_{0}} \frac{300 \mathrm{~K}}{T}\right)^{0.72169}\right]^{1.80618}} \\
& P=\left[\frac{2.459}{3.97 \times 10^{13} \mathrm{~cm}^{-2} N_{\mathrm{sc}}^{-2 / 3}}+\frac{3.828\left(c+c_{\text {other }}\right)\left(m_{0} / m^{*}\right)}{1.36 \times 10^{20} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}}\right]^{-1}\left(\frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

By default, the full PhuMob model described by the previous expressions is used (FullPhuMob). However, the other carrier in these expressions can be ignored ( \(c_{\text {other }}=0\) )

[Page 428 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Degradation at Interfaces

by specifying-FullPhuMob in the command file. This specification also ignores the standard PhuMob modification of the \(G(P)\) function, which invokes \(G=G\left(P_{\min }\right)\) for \(P<P_{\min }\), where \(P_{\text {min }}\) is the value where \(G(P)\) reaches its minimum. If \(G\left(P_{\text {min }}\right)\) is negative, which might occur in the model for the lattice temperature \(T\) below 50 K , then \(\left|G\left(P_{\text {min }}\right)\right|\) is used for \(G(P)<\left|G\left(P_{\text {min }}\right)\right|\).

\section*{Phonon Scattering}

The phonon-scattering portion of Equation 301 also has 2D and 3D parts.
The way in which these parts are combined depends on the value of the PhononCombination parameter in the IALMob command file:
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{ph}}=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\min \left\{\frac{\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}}}{D}, \mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 3 \mathrm{D}}\right\}, & \text { PhononCombination }=0 \\
{\left[\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 3 \mathrm{D}}}\right]^{-1},} & \text { PhononCombination }=1 \text { (default) } \\
{\left[\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}}}+\frac{f\left(F_{\perp}, t, T\right)}{\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 3 \mathrm{D}}}\right]^{-1},} & \text { PhononCombination }=2
\end{array}\right.
\]
where:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}} & =\frac{B}{F_{\perp}}+\frac{C\left(\alpha_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{~A}}\left(\left(N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}+N_{2} / 2\right) / 1 \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\right)^{\lambda_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{~A}}}+\alpha_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{D}}\left(\left(N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}+N_{2} / 2\right) / 1 \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\right)^{\lambda_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}, \mathrm{D}}}\right)^{\lambda}}{F_{\perp}^{1 / 3}(T / 300 \mathrm{~K})^{k}} \\
\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 3 \mathrm{D}} & =\mu_{\max }\left(\frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{-\theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

\section*{Surface Roughness Scattering}

Surface roughness scattering is given by:
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{sr}}=\frac{\left(\alpha_{\mathrm{sr}, \mathrm{~A}}\left(\left(N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}+N_{2} / 2\right) / 1 \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\right)^{\lambda_{\mathrm{sr}, \mathrm{~A}}}+\alpha_{\mathrm{sr}, \mathrm{D}}\left(\left(N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}+N_{2} / 2\right) / 1 \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\right)^{\lambda_{\mathrm{sr}, \mathrm{D}}}\right)^{\lambda_{\mathrm{sr}}}}{\left(\frac{\left(F_{\perp} / 1 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{cm}\right)^{A^{*}}}{\delta}+\frac{F_{\perp}^{3}}{\eta}\right)}
\]
where:
\[
A^{*}=A+\frac{\alpha_{\perp}(n+p)}{\left(\left(N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}+N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}+N_{1}\right) / 1 \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\right)^{v}}
\]

