\section*{Mobility Degradation Components due to Coulomb Scattering}

Different mobility degradation components due to Coulomb scattering are available in Sentaurus Device that can be combined with other interface mobility degradation models:
- NegInterfaceCharge accounts for mobility degradation due to a negative interface charge (from charged traps and fixed charge).
- PosInterfaceCharge accounts for mobility degradation due to a positive interface charge (from charged traps and fixed charge).
- Coulomb2D accounts for mobility degradation due to ionized impurities near the interface.

These degradation components can be specified separately or in combination with each other. If specified, they will be combined using Matthiessen's rule:
\[
\frac{1}{\mu}=\frac{1}{\mu_{\text {other }}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\text {nic }}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\text {pic }}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{C 2 D}}
\]
where:
- \(\mu_{\text {other }}\) represents the other DopingDependence and Enormal models specified for the simulation.
- \(\mu_{\text {nic }}\) represents the NegInterfaceCharge mobility degradation component.

[Page 437 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Mobility Degradation at Interfaces
- \(\mu_{\text {pic }}\) represents the PosInterfaceCharge mobility degradation component.
- \(\mu_{\mathrm{C} 2 \mathrm{D}}\) represents the Coulomb2D mobility degradation component.

The general form of the mobility degradation components due to Coulomb scattering is given by:
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{RCS}}=\frac{\mu_{1}\left(\frac{T}{300}\right)^{k}\left\{1+\left[c /\left(c_{\text {trans }}\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}, \mathrm{D}}+N_{1}}{10^{18} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}}\right)^{\gamma_{1}}\left(\frac{N_{\text {coulomb }}}{N_{0}}\right)^{\eta_{1}}\right)\right]^{v}\right\}}{\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{A}, \mathrm{D}}+N_{2}}{10^{18} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}}\right)^{\gamma_{2}}\left(\frac{N_{\text {coulomb }}}{N_{0}}\right)^{\eta_{2}} \cdot D \cdot f\left(F_{\perp}\right)}+\mu_{\min }
\]
where:
- \(N_{\text {coulomb }}= \begin{cases}\text { negative interface charge density, } & \text { for NegInterfaceCharge component } \\ \text { positive interface charge density, } & \text { for PosInterfaceCharge component } \\ \text { local } N_{\mathrm{A}, \mathrm{D}}, & \text { for Coulomb2D component }\end{cases}\)
- \(c=n\) (electron mobility) or \(p\) (hole mobility)
- \(N_{\mathrm{A}, \mathrm{D}}=N_{\mathrm{A}, 0}\) (electron mobility) or \(N_{\mathrm{D}, 0}\) (hole mobility)
- \(f\left(F_{\perp}\right)=1-\exp \left[-\left(F_{\perp} / E_{0}\right)^{\gamma}\right]\)
- \(D=\exp \left(-x / l_{\text {crit }}\right)\), where \(x\) is the distance from the interface.
- \(\mu_{\text {min }}\) limits the lowest mobility value for Equation 330 .

Parameters associated with the components are accessible in the parameter sets
NegInterfaceChargeMobility, NegInterfaceChargeMobility_aniso, PosInterfaceChargeMobility, PosInterfaceChargeMobility_aniso, Coulomb2 DMobility, and Coulomb2DMobility_aniso. Table 68 lists their default values.

