\section*{Field Correction on Interface}

For vertices on the interface, due to discretization, the normal electric field in inversion is underestimated systematically due to screening by the charge at the same vertex.

Therefore, Sentaurus Device supports a correction of the field:
\[
F_{\text {corr }}(\vec{r})=\frac{\alpha l \rho(\vec{r})}{\varepsilon}
\]
where \(\alpha\) is dimensionless and is specified with NormalFieldCorrection in the Math section (reasonable values range from 0 to 1 ; the default is zero), \(\rho\) is the space charge, \(\varepsilon\) is the dielectric constant in the semiconductor, and \(l\) is an estimate for the depth of the box of the vertex in the normal direction.

\section*{Thin-Layer Mobility Model}

The thin-layer mobility model applies to devices with silicon layers that are only a few nanometers thick. In such devices, geometric quantization leads to a mobility that cannot be expressed with a normal field-dependent interface model such as those described in Mobility Degradation at Interfaces on page 421, but it depends explicitly on the layer thickness.

The thin-layer mobility model described here is based on the model described in the literature [19] and is used in conjunction with either the Lombardi model (see Enhanced Lombardi Model on page 422) or the IALMob model (see Inversion and Accumulation Layer Mobility Model on page 426).

\section*{Note:}

When using the thin-layer mobility model in conjunction with the Lombardi model, it is recommended to also use the Philips Unified Mobility Model on page 416. The Philips unified mobility model must be activated separately from the thin-layer mobility model.

The thin-layer mobility \(\mu_{\mathrm{tl}}\) consists of contributions of thickness fluctuation scattering, surface phonon scattering, bulk phonon scattering, and additional contributions from the normal field-dependent interface model used in conjunction with it:
\[
\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{tl}}}=\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{tf}}}+\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{sp}}}+\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{bp}}}+\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{sr}}} & , \text { Lombardi } \\
\frac{D}{\mu_{\mathrm{sr}}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 3 \mathrm{D}}}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{C}}}, & \text { IALMob }
\end{array}\right.
\]

[Page 446 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Thin-Layer Mobility Model

where:
- \(D=\exp \left(-x / l_{\text {crit }}\right)\) (see Enhanced Lombardi Model on page 422 (Lombardi) or Inversion and Accumulation Layer Mobility Model on page 426 (IALMob)).
- \(\mu_{\mathrm{sr}}\) is given by Equation 296 (Lombardi) or Equation 320 (IALMob).
- \(\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 3 \mathrm{D}}\) is given by Equation 319 (IALMob).
- \(\mu_{\mathrm{C}}\) is given by Equation 305 (IALMob).

The thickness fluctuation term is given by:
\[
\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{tf}}}=\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{tf} 0}\left(t_{\mathrm{b}} / 1 \mathrm{~nm}\right)^{\eta_{1}}\left[1+\left(\frac{F_{\perp}}{F_{\mathrm{tf} 0}}\right)^{\eta_{2}}\right]}+\frac{1}{\mu_{\mathrm{tfh} 0}\left(t_{\mathrm{b}} / 1 \mathrm{~nm}\right)^{\eta_{1}}\left(\frac{F_{\mathrm{tfh} 0}}{F_{\perp}}\right)}
\]

The surface phonon term is given by:
\[
\mu_{\mathrm{sp}}=\mu_{\mathrm{sp} 0} \exp \left(t_{\mathrm{b}} / t_{\mathrm{sp} 0}\right)
\]

The bulk phonon term is given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \mu_{\mathrm{bp}}=P_{1} \mu_{\mathrm{ac}, 1}+\left(1-P_{1}\right) \mu_{\mathrm{ac}, 2} \\
& P_{1}=p_{1}+\frac{1-p_{1}}{1+p_{2} \exp \left(-p_{3} \Delta E / k T\right)} \\
& \Delta E=\frac{\hbar^{2} \pi^{2}}{2 t_{\mathrm{b}}^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{m_{z 2}}-\frac{1}{m_{z 1}}\right) \\
& \mu_{\mathrm{ac}, \mathrm{v}}=\frac{\mu_{\mathrm{ac} 0, \mathrm{v}}}{\left[1+\left(W_{\mathrm{Tv}} / W_{F \mathrm{v}}\right)^{\beta}\right]^{1 / \beta}}\left(\frac{W_{\mathrm{Tv}}}{1 \mathrm{~nm}}\right) \\
& W_{\mathrm{Tv}}=\frac{2}{3} t_{\mathrm{b}}+W_{\mathrm{T} 0 \mathrm{v}}\left(\frac{t_{\mathrm{b}}}{1 \mathrm{~nm}}\right)^{4}\left(\frac{F_{\perp}}{1 \mathrm{MV} / \mathrm{cm}}\right) \\
& \frac{W_{F v}}{1 \mathrm{~nm}}=\zeta^{v-1} \frac{\mu_{\mathrm{ac}}}{P_{\mathrm{bulk}} \mu_{\mathrm{ac} 0,1}+\zeta\left(1-P_{\mathrm{bulk}}\right) \mu_{\mathrm{ac} 0,2}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(\mu_{\mathrm{ac}}\) is given by Equation 295 (Lombardi) or by \(\mu_{\mathrm{ph}, 2 \mathrm{D}}\) Equation 318 (IALMob).
- \(P_{\text {bulk }}=p_{1}+\left(1-p_{1}\right) /(1+p 2)\).
- The thickness \(t_{\mathrm{b}}\) is the larger of the local layer thickness and \(t_{\min }\).
- \(t_{\min }, \mu_{\mathrm{tf} 0}, F_{\mathrm{tf} 0}, \mu_{\mathrm{tfh} 0}, F_{\mathrm{tfh} 0}, \eta_{1}, \eta_{2}, \mu_{\mathrm{sp} 0}, t_{\mathrm{sp} 0}, \mu_{\mathrm{ac} 0, v}, p_{1}, p_{2}, p_{3}, m_{z 1}, m_{z 2}, \beta\), \(W_{\mathrm{T} 0 v}\), and \(\zeta\) are model parameters.

[Page 447 END]
