\section*{Carbon Nanotube Mobility Model}

The carbon nanotube (CNT) mobility model is specifically for CNT applications. The model is based on the multivalley band structure (see Multivalley Band Structure on page 342) and, particularly, on the CNT DOS (see Carbon Nanotube Density-of-States on page 346). In low-driving fields and in the relaxation time approximation, the 1D conductance of one CNT band can be expressed using the Landauer approach and as shown in [20]:
\[
G_{i}=\frac{4 q^{2}}{\hbar} \int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{\lambda_{i}(\varepsilon)}{L_{\mathrm{ch}}+\lambda_{i}(\varepsilon)}\left(-\frac{\partial f_{0}(\varepsilon)}{\partial \varepsilon}\right) d \varepsilon
\]
where \(G_{i}\) is the 1 D conductance of the \(i\)-band, \(\lambda_{i}(\varepsilon)\) is the energy-dependent mean free path (MFP) of carriers in the \(i\)-band, \(L_{\mathrm{ch}}\) is the CNT channel length, and \(f_{0}(\varepsilon)\) is the FermiDirac distribution function.

With the known band conductance \(G_{i}\) from Equation 357, a local averaged low-field mobility is computed as follows:
\[
\mu=\frac{L_{\mathrm{ch}} \sum_{i} G_{i}}{q^{A} \sum_{i} n_{i}}
\]
where \(n_{i}\) is the local carrier concentration of the \(i\)-band, and \(A\) is the CNT-conducting area as used in Equation 210 for CNT DOS.

[Page 451 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Carbon Nanotube Mobility Model

Accounting for the optical (OP) and acoustic (AC) phonon scattering, both intraband and interband scattering, Pauli blocking for final states (all as proposed in [20]), and the MFP \(\lambda_{i}(\varepsilon)\) of carriers in the \(i\)-band (in Equation 357) are computed as follows:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{\lambda_{i}(\varepsilon)} & =\sum_{k} \frac{1}{\lambda_{\mathrm{AP}(i k)}(\varepsilon)}+\frac{1-f_{0}\left(\varepsilon+\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{OP}}\right)}{\lambda_{\mathrm{OP}, i k}^{\mathrm{abs}}(\varepsilon)}+\frac{1-f_{0}\left(\varepsilon-\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{OP}}\right)}{\lambda_{\mathrm{OP}, i k}^{\mathrm{ems}}(\varepsilon)} \\
\lambda_{\mathrm{AP}(i k)}(\varepsilon) & =\lambda_{\mathrm{AP}} \frac{300}{T} \frac{D_{k}(\infty)}{D_{k}(\varepsilon)} \frac{v_{i}(\varepsilon)}{v_{i}(\infty)} \\
\lambda_{\mathrm{OP}, i k}^{\mathrm{ems} / \mathrm{abs}}(\varepsilon) & =\lambda_{\mathrm{OP}} \frac{N_{\mathrm{OP}}(300)+1}{N_{\mathrm{OP}}(T)+1 / 2 \pm 1 / 2} \frac{D_{k}(\infty)}{D_{k}\left(\varepsilon \mp \hbar \omega_{\mathrm{OP}}\right)} \frac{v_{i}(\varepsilon)}{v_{i}(\infty)} \\
v_{i}(\varepsilon) & =v_{F} \sqrt{1-\left(\frac{E_{g} / 2+\varepsilon_{i}}{E_{g} / 2+\varepsilon_{i}+\varepsilon}\right)^{2}} \\
N_{\mathrm{OP}}(T) & =1 /\left(\exp \left(\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{OP}} / k T\right)-1\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where the sum \(\Sigma\) goes over all used CNT bands and, for \(i=k\), the intraband scattering is accounted for. However, for all other cases, the interband scattering is accounted for by different user-defined MFP model parameters, \(\lambda_{\mathrm{AP}}\) and \(\lambda_{\mathrm{OP}}\), set for the temperature \(T\) equal to 300 K . The upper (lower) signs in Equation 359 correspond to the emission (absorption) of optical phonons.

The CNT DOS \(D_{k}(\varepsilon)\) is defined by Equation 210 and, correspondingly, \(D_{k}(\infty)=4 /\left(\pi \hbar v_{F} A\right)\). Based on such a CNT DOS, \(v_{i}(\varepsilon)\) is the energy-dependent carrier velocity and, correspondingly, \(v_{i}(\infty)=v_{F}\) is the Fermi velocity. The optical phonon energy \(\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{OP}}\) is a user-defined parameter and \(N_{\mathrm{OP}}(T)\) is the optical phonon occupation function.

\section*{Using the CNT Mobility Model}

To activate the CNT mobility model, use the following either globally or regionwise in the Physics section of the command file:
```
eMobility (
    CNTMob( Lch = <value> ) # <value> in [nm]
)
```


If the CNTMob model is used with other low-field mobility models defined in the Mobility section, then Matthiessen's rule is applied.

The model parameters used in Equation 359 should be set in the following section of the parameter file:
```
CNTMobility (
    hbarOmega = 0.18, 0.18 # [eV], \hbar'0P
    Lambda_OP = 60, 60 # [nm], \mp@subsup{\lambda}{OP}{}
    Lambda_AP = 1.12e3, 1.12e3 # [nm], \mp@subsup{\lambda}{AP}{}}\mathrm{ in intraband scattering
    Lambda_OP_inter = 60, 60 # [nm], \mp@subsup{\lambda}{OP}{}
```

[Page 452 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Low-Temperature Phonon Exponent Correction for Mobility Models
```
    Lambda_AP_inter = 1.12e3, 1.12e3 # [nm], \mp@subsup{\lambda}{\mathrm{ AP in interband scattering}}{}
)
```


The optical phonon energy and MFP model parameters in the example correspond to those used in [20] for a CNT diameter equal to 4 nm .

\section*{Note:}

The CNT mobility model works only with CNT bands that are defined in the parameter file (with dosmodel=CNT; see Using Multivalley Band Structure on page 346). If CNT bands are not set, then Sentaurus Device stops the simulation.

The following example shows CNT band settings, which correspond to five bands used in [20] for a CNT diameter equal to 4 nm :
```
Multivalley (
    eValley"Band1"( energy = 0 dosmodel = CNT )
    eValley"Band2"( energy = 0.102 dosmodel = CNT )
    eValley"Band4"( energy = 0.306 dosmodel = CNT )
    eValley"Band5"( energy = 0.408 dosmodel = CNT )
    eValley"Band7"( energy = 0.612 dosmodel = CNT )
)
```


To plot the CNT mobility from Equation 358, use the eCNTMobility and hCNTMobility keywords in the Plot section for electrons and holes, respectively.

\section*{Note:}

Equation 357 involves a numeric computation of the integral over the energy for each CNT band. Such an integration is performed using quadratures as for the multivalley model (see Using Multivalley Band Structure on page 346). To improve the accuracy of the computation, you can use a larger number of energy points, for example, by setting Math \{ DensityIntegral (100) \}. This might be needed for low-temperature simulations where \(\frac{\partial f_{0}(\varepsilon)}{\partial \varepsilon}\) is a function over the energy with a sharp peak at the carrier Fermi energy.

\section*{Low-Temperature Phonon Exponent Correction for Mobility Models}

For mobility models (constant mobility, Philips unified mobility, enhanced Lombardi mobility, and IALMob), the exponent of temperature ( \(\theta\) or \(\xi\) for 3D phonons, and \(k\) for 2D phonons) in the various phonon mobility models (Equation 261, Equation 281, Equation 295, Equation 318, and Equation 319) is assumed to be constant with temperature. However, temperature-dependent phonon mobility measurement [21][22] shows that the exponent itself varies with temperature, particularly at low temperatures ( \(T<150 \mathrm{~K}\) ).

[Page 453 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Low-Temperature Phonon Exponent Correction for Mobility Models

This temperature-dependent correction can be incorporated by an empirically fitted formula (for both electrons and holes) for 3D phonons:
\[
\theta(T)=\theta+\Delta \theta\left(\tanh \left[\frac{T}{T_{c}}\right]-1\right)
\]

For 2D phonons, it is:
\[
k(T)=k+\Delta \theta_{2 \mathrm{D}}\left(\tanh \left[\frac{T}{T_{c, 2 \mathrm{D}}}\right]-1\right)
\]
where \(\theta\) and \(k\) are existing constant values, and \(\Delta \theta\left(\Delta \theta_{2 \mathrm{D}}\right)\) and \(T_{c}\left(T_{c, 2 \mathrm{D}}\right)\) are user inputs. By default, the value of \(\Delta \theta\) and \(\Delta \theta_{2 D}\) is 0 , and the correction is deactivated. The correction can be switched on by defining nonzero values for \(\Delta \theta\) and \(\Delta \theta_{2 D}\) in the parameter file for the particular mobility model that is being used in the simulation.

For example, when using the Philips unified mobility model (PhuMob) in the Physics section, the low-temperature correction for phonons (PhuMob has only a 3D phonon component, Equation 279) can be switched on by specifying the values of \(\Delta \theta\) and \(T_{c}\) for electron and holes separately:
```
PhuMob {
    tc_e = 150.0
    tc_h = 65.0
    deltheta_e = 0.5
    deltheta_h = 0.43
}
```


The next sections provide default and recommended values for \(\Delta \theta\left(\Delta \theta_{2 \mathrm{D}}\right)\) and \(T_{c}\left(T_{c, 2 \mathrm{D}}\right)\) for the various mobility models.

