\section*{Extended Canali Model}

The Canali model [23] originates from the Caughey-Thomas formula [24], but has temperature-dependent parameters, which were fitted up to 430 K by Canali et al. [23]:
\[
\mu(F)=\frac{(\alpha+1) \mu_{\mathrm{low}}}{\alpha+\left[1+\left(\frac{(\alpha+1) \mu_{\mathrm{low}} F_{\mathrm{hfs}}}{v_{\mathrm{sat}}}\right)^{\beta}\right]^{1 / \beta}}
\]
where \(\mu_{\text {low }}\) denotes the low-field mobility. Its definition depends on which of the previously described mobility models have been activated (see Mobility due to Phonon Scattering on page 405 to Philips Unified Mobility Model on page 416).

The exponent \(\beta\) is temperature dependent according to:
\[
\beta=\beta_{0}\left(\frac{T}{300 \mathrm{~K}}\right)^{\beta_{\exp }}
\]

Details about the saturation velocity \(v_{\text {sat }}\) and driving field \(F_{\mathrm{hfs}}\) are discussed in Velocity Saturation Models on page 466 and Driving Force Models on page 468. All other parameters are accessible in the parameter set HighFieldDependence.

The silicon default values are listed in Table 76 on page 460.
A modified version of the Canali model is the Hänsch model [14]. It is activated by setting the parameter \(\alpha=1\). The Hänsch model is part of the Lucent mobility model (see Lucent Model on page 465). When using the hydrodynamic driving force Equation 379, \(\alpha\) must be zero.

For the hydrodynamic driving force, Equation 379 can be substituted into Equation 362. Solving for \(\mu\) yields the hydrodynamic Canali model:
\[
\mu=\frac{\mu_{\text {low }}}{\left[\sqrt{1+\gamma^{2} \max \left(w_{c}-w_{0}, 0\right)^{\beta}}+\gamma \max \left(w_{c}-w_{0}, 0\right)^{\beta / 2}\right]^{2 / \beta}}
\]
where \(\gamma\) is given by \(\gamma=\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\mu_{\text {low }}}{q \tau_{\mathrm{e}, c} v_{\text {sat }}^{2}}\right)^{\beta / 2}\).
In this form, the model has a discontinuous derivative at \(w_{0}=w_{c}\), which can lead to numeric problems. Therefore, Sentaurus Device applies a smoothing algorithm in the carrier temperature region \(T<T_{c}<\left(1+K_{d T}\right) T\) to create a smooth transition between the low-field mobility \(\mu_{\text {low }}\) and the mobility given in Equation \(364 . K_{d T}\) defaults to 0.2 and can be accessed in the parameter set HighFieldDependence.

