\section*{Physical Model Interfaces}

Sentaurus Device offers different physical model interfaces (PMIs) for high-field mobility saturation:
- The first PMI is activated by specifying the name of the model as an option of HighFieldSaturation, eHighFieldSaturation, or hHighFieldSaturation. See High-Field Saturation on page 1323.
- The second PMI allows you to implement models that depend on two driving forces. It is specified by PMIModel as the option to HighFieldSaturation, eHighFieldSaturation, or hHighFieldSaturation. See High-Field Saturation With Two Driving Forces on page 1331.

\section*{Lucent Model}

The Lucent model has been developed by Darwish et al. [12]. Sentaurus Device implements this model as a combination of:
- An extended Philips unified mobility model (see Philips Unified Mobility Model on page 416 ) with the parameters \(f_{\mathrm{e}}=0\) and \(f_{\mathrm{h}}=0\) (see Table 62 on page 421 ). The Lucent model described in [12] also does not include clustering. To deactivate clustering in the Philips unified mobility model, set the parameters \(N_{\text {ref, A }}\) and \(N_{\text {ref, D }}\) to very large numbers.
- The enhanced Lombardi model (see Enhanced Lombardi Model on page 422 ) with the parameters from Table 64 on page 424.
- The Hänsch model (see Extended Canali Model on page 459) with the parameter \(\alpha=1\) (see Table 76 on page 460). In addition, the \(\beta\) exponent in the Hänsch model is equal to 2 , which can be accomplished by setting \(\beta_{0}=2\) and \(\beta_{\exp }=0\).

