\section*{Schenk Trap-Assisted Tunneling Model}

The field dependence of the recombination rate is taken into account by the field enhancement factors:
\[
[1+g(F)]^{-1}
\]
of the SRH lifetimes [8] (see Equation 408).
In the case of electrons, \(g(F)\) has the form:
\[
\begin{aligned}
g_{n}(F)= & \left(1+\frac{(\hbar \Theta)^{3 / 2} \sqrt{E_{\mathrm{t}}-E_{0}}}{E_{0} \hbar \omega_{0}}\right)^{-\frac{1}{2}}\left(\frac{(\hbar \Theta)^{3 / 4}\left(E_{\mathrm{t}}-E_{0}\right)^{1 / 4}}{2 \sqrt{E_{\mathrm{t}} E_{0}}}\left(\frac{\hbar \Theta}{k T}\right)^{\frac{3}{2}}\right) \\
& \times \exp \left(-\frac{E_{\mathrm{t}}-E_{0}}{\hbar \omega_{0}}+\frac{\hbar \omega_{0}-k T}{2 \hbar \omega_{0}}+\frac{2 E_{\mathrm{t}}+k T}{2 \hbar \omega_{0}} \ln \frac{E_{\mathrm{t}}}{\varepsilon_{\mathrm{R}}}-\frac{E_{0}}{\hbar \omega_{0}} \ln \frac{E_{0}}{\varepsilon_{\mathrm{R}}}+\frac{E_{\mathrm{t}}-E_{0}}{k T}-\frac{4}{3}\left(\frac{E_{\mathrm{t}}-E_{0}}{\hbar \Theta}\right)^{\frac{3}{2}}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(E_{0}\) denotes the energy of an optimum horizontal transition path, which depends on field strength and temperature in the following way:
\[
E_{0}=2 \sqrt{\varepsilon_{F}}\left[\sqrt{\varepsilon_{F}+E_{\mathrm{t}}+\varepsilon_{\mathrm{R}}}-\sqrt{\varepsilon_{F}}\right]-\varepsilon_{\mathrm{R}}, \varepsilon_{F}=\frac{\left(2 \varepsilon_{\mathrm{R}} k T\right)^{2}}{(\hbar \Theta)^{3}}
\]

In this expression, \(\varepsilon_{\mathrm{R}}=S \hbar \omega_{0}\) is the lattice relaxation energy, \(S\) is the Huang-Rhys factor, \(\hbar \omega_{0}\) is the effective phonon energy, \(E_{\mathrm{t}}\) is the energy level of the recombination center (thermal depth), and \(\Theta=\left(q^{2} F^{2} / 2 \hbar m_{\Theta, n}\right)\) is the electro-optical frequency.
The mass \(m_{\Theta, n}\) is the electron tunneling mass in the field direction and is given in the parameter file. The expression for holes follows from Equation 420 by replacing \(m_{\Theta, n}\) with \(m_{\Theta, p}\) and \(E_{\mathrm{t}}\) with \(E_{\mathrm{g}, \text { eff }}-E_{\mathrm{t}}\).
For electrons, \(E_{\mathrm{t}}\) is related to the defect level \(E_{\text {trap }}\) of Equation 406 and Equation 407 by:
\[
E_{\mathrm{t}}=\frac{1}{2} E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}+\frac{3}{4} k T \ln \left(\frac{m_{n}}{m_{p}}\right)-E_{\text {trap }}-\left(32 R_{\mathrm{C}} \hbar^{3} \Theta^{3}\right)^{1 / 4}
\]
where the effective Rydberg constant \(R_{\mathrm{C}}\) is:
\[
R_{\mathrm{C}}=m_{\mathrm{C}}\left(\frac{Z^{2}}{\varepsilon^{2}}\right) R y
\]
where \(R y\) is the Rydberg energy ( 13.606 eV ), \(\varepsilon\) is the relative dielectric constant, and \(Z\) is a fit parameter.

[Page 499 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Shockley-Read-Hall Recombination

For holes, \(E_{\mathrm{t}}\) is given by:
\[
E_{\mathrm{t}}=\frac{1}{2} E_{\mathrm{g}, \mathrm{eff}}-\frac{3}{4} k T \ln \left(\frac{m_{n}}{m_{p}}\right)+E_{\text {trap }}-\left(32 R_{\mathrm{V}} \hbar^{3} \Theta^{3}\right)^{1 / 4}
\]

Note that \(E_{\text {trap }}\) is measured from the intrinsic level and not from the midgap. The zero-field lifetime \(\tau_{\text {SRH }}\) is defined by Equation 410.

\section*{Hurkx Trap-Assisted Tunneling Model}

The following equations apply to electrons and holes. Lifetimes and capture cross-sections become functions of the trap-assisted tunneling factor \(g(F)=\Gamma_{\text {tat }}\) :
\[
\tau=\tau_{0} /\left(1+\Gamma_{\mathrm{tat}}\right) \quad, \quad \sigma=\sigma_{0}\left(1+\Gamma_{\mathrm{tat}}\right)
\]
where \(\Gamma_{\text {tat }}\) is given by:
\[
\Gamma_{\text {tat }}=\int_{0}^{\tilde{E}_{n}} \exp \left[u-\frac{2}{3} \frac{\sqrt{u^{3}}}{\tilde{E}}\right] d u
\]
with the approximate solutions:
\[
\Gamma_{\mathrm{tat}} \approx \begin{cases}\sqrt{\pi} \tilde{E} \cdot \exp \left[\frac{1}{3} \tilde{E}^{2}\right]\left(2-\operatorname{erfc}\left[\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\tilde{E}_{n}}{\tilde{E}}-\tilde{E}\right)\right]\right), & \tilde{E} \leq \sqrt{\tilde{E}_{n}} \\ \sqrt{\pi \tilde{E}} \cdot \tilde{E}_{n}{ }^{1 / 4} \exp \left[-\tilde{E}_{n}+\tilde{E} \sqrt{\tilde{E}_{n}}+\frac{1}{3} \frac{\sqrt{\tilde{E}_{n}^{3}}}{\tilde{E}}\right] \operatorname{erfc}\left[\tilde{E}_{n}^{1 / 4} \sqrt{\tilde{E}}-\tilde{E}_{n}^{3 / 4} / \sqrt{\tilde{E}}\right], & \tilde{E}>\sqrt{\tilde{E}_{n}}\end{cases}
\]
where \(\tilde{E}\) and \(\tilde{E}_{n}\) are respectively defined as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{E}=\frac{E}{E_{0}} \quad \text { where } \quad E_{0}=\frac{\sqrt{8 m_{0} m_{\mathrm{t}} k^{3} T^{3}}}{q \hbar} \\
& \tilde{E}_{n}=\frac{E_{n}}{k T}=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
0, & k T \ln \frac{n}{n_{\mathrm{i}}}>0.5 E_{\mathrm{g}} \\
\frac{0.5 E_{\mathrm{g}}}{k T}-\ln \frac{n}{n_{\mathrm{i}}}, & E_{\text {trap }} \leq k T \ln \frac{n}{n_{\mathrm{i}}} \leq 0.5 E_{\mathrm{g}} \\
\frac{0.5 E_{\mathrm{g}}}{k T}-\frac{E_{\text {trap }}}{k T}, & E_{\text {trap }}>k T \ln \frac{n}{n_{\mathrm{i}}}
\end{array}\right.
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(m_{\mathrm{t}}\) is the carrier tunneling mass and \(E_{\text {trap }}\) is an energy of trap level that is taken from SRH recombination if the model is applied to the lifetimes ( \(\tau\) ) or from trap equations if it is applied to cross sections \((\sigma)\).

[Page 500 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Shockley-Read-Hall Recombination

When quantization is active (see Chapter 14 on page 367), the classical density:
\[
n_{\mathrm{cl}}=n \exp \left(\frac{\Lambda}{k T}\right)
\]
rather than the true density \(n\) enters Equation 429.
The Hurkx model has only one parameter, \(m_{\mathrm{t}}\), the carrier tunneling mass, which can be specified in the parameter file for electrons and holes as follows:
