\section*{Coupled Defect Level Recombination}

The steady-state recombination rate for two coupled defect levels (CDLs) generalizes the familiar single-level SRH formula. An important feature of the model is a possibly increased field effect that might lead to large excess currents. The model is discussed in the literature [12]. Figure 20 illustrates the notation of the model parameters.

\begin{figure}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Figure 20 Notation for CDL recombination including all capture and emission processes}
\includegraphics[alt={},max width=\textwidth]{https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/f7af57de-59b5-428e-a177-d4f23fc59969-266.jpg?height=207&width=693&top_left_y=1611&top_left_x=481}
\end{figure}

The CDL recombination rate is given by:
\[
R=R_{1}+R_{2}+\left(\sqrt{R_{12}^{2}-S_{12}}-R_{12}\right) \times \frac{\tau_{n 1} \tau_{p 2}\left(n+n_{2}\right)\left(p+p_{1}\right)-\tau_{n 2} \tau_{p 1}\left(n+n_{1}\right)\left(p+p_{2}\right)}{r_{1} r_{2}}
\]
with:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& r_{j}=\tau_{n j}\left(p+p_{j}\right)+\tau_{p j}\left(n+n_{j}\right) \\
& R_{j}=\frac{n p-n_{\mathrm{i}, \text { eff }}^{2}}{r_{j}}, \quad j=1,2
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 507 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Radiative Recombination Model
\[
\begin{aligned}
& R_{12}=\frac{r_{1} r_{2}}{2 r_{12} \tau_{n 1} \tau_{n 2} \tau_{p 1} \tau_{p 2}(1-\varepsilon)}+\frac{\tau_{n 1}\left(p+p_{1}\right)+\tau_{p 2}\left(n+n_{2}\right)}{2 \tau_{n 1} \tau_{p 2}(1-\varepsilon)}+\frac{\varepsilon\left[\tau_{n 2}\left(p+p_{2}\right)+\tau_{p 1}\left(n+n_{1}\right)\right]}{2 \tau_{n 2} \tau_{p 1}(1-\varepsilon)} \\
& S_{12}=\frac{1}{\tau_{n 1} \tau_{p 2}(1-\varepsilon)}\left(1-\frac{\tau_{n 1} \tau_{p 2}}{\tau_{n 2} \tau_{p 1}} \varepsilon\right)\left(n p-n_{\mathrm{i}, \mathrm{eff}}^{2}\right) \\
& \varepsilon=\exp \left(-\frac{\left|E_{\mathrm{t} 2}-E_{\mathrm{t} 1}\right|}{k T}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\tau_{n i}\) and \(\tau_{p i}\) denote the electron and hole lifetimes of the defect level \(i\). The coupling parameter between the defect levels is called \(r_{12}\) (keyword TrapTrapRate in the parameter file). Carrier lifetimes are calculated analogously to carrier lifetimes in the SRH model (see Shockley-Read-Hall Recombination on page 493). The number of parameters is doubled compared to the SRH model, and you can change them in the CDL parameter set.

The quantities \(n_{2}\) and \(p_{2}\) are the corresponding quantities of \(n_{1}\) and \(p_{1}\) for the second defect level. They are defined analogously to Equation 406 and Equation 407.

For Fermi statistics and quantization, the equations are modified in the same way as for SRH recombination (see Equation 409).

\section*{Using Coupled Defect Level Recombination}

You can switch on CDL recombination using the keyword CDL in the Physics section:
```
Physics{ Recombination( CDL ...) ...}
```


The contributions \(R_{1}\) and \(R_{2}\) in Equation 447 can be plotted using the keywords CDL1 and CDL2 in the Plot section. For the net rate and coupling term, \(R-R_{1}-R_{2}\), the keywords CDL and CDL3 must be specified.

\section*{Radiative Recombination Model}

The radiative (direct) recombination model expresses the recombination rate as:
\[
R_{\mathrm{net}}=C \cdot\left(n p-n_{\mathrm{i}, \mathrm{eff}}^{2}\right)
\]

By default, Sentaurus Device selects \(C=2 \times 10^{-10} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) for GaAs and \(C=0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) for other materials. For Fermi statistics and quantization, the equations are modified in the same way as for SRH recombination (see Equation 409).

