\section*{Auger Recombination Model}

The rate of band-to-band Auger recombination \(R_{\text {net }}^{\mathrm{A}}\) is given by:
\[
R_{\mathrm{net}}^{\mathrm{A}}=\left(C_{n} n+C_{p} p\right)\left(n p-n_{\mathrm{i}, \mathrm{eff}}^{2}\right)
\]
with temperature-dependent Auger coefficients [13][14][15]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& C_{n}(T)=\left(A_{\mathrm{A}, n}+B_{\mathrm{A}, n}\left(\frac{T}{T_{0}}\right)+C_{\mathrm{A}, n}\left(\frac{T}{T_{0}}\right)^{2}\right)\left[1+H_{n} \exp \left(-\frac{n}{N_{0, n}}\right)\right] \\
& C_{p}(T)=\left(A_{\mathrm{A}, p}+B_{\mathrm{A}, p}\left(\frac{T}{T_{0}}\right)+C_{\mathrm{A}, p}\left(\frac{T}{T_{0}}\right)^{2}\right)\left[1+H_{p} \exp \left(-\frac{p}{N_{0, p}}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(T_{0}=300 \mathrm{~K}\). There is experimental evidence for a decrease of the Auger coefficients at high injection levels [15]. This effect is explained as resulting from exciton decay: at lower carrier densities, excitons, which are loosely bound electron-hole pairs, increase the probability for Auger recombination. Excitons decay at high carrier densities, resulting in a decrease of recombination. This effect is modeled by the terms \(1+H \exp \left(-n / N_{0}\right)\) in Equation 453 and Equation 454.

Auger recombination is typically important at high carrier densities. Therefore, this injection dependence is seen only in devices where extrinsic recombination effects are extremely

[Page 509 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


low, such as high-efficiency silicon solar cells. The injection dependence of the Auger coefficient can be deactivated by setting H to zero in the parameter file.

For Fermi statistics and quantization, the equations are modified in the same way as for SRH recombination (see Equation 409 on page 494 ). Table 88 lists the default values for silicon.

