\section*{University of Bologna Impact Ionization Model}

This model was developed for an extended temperature range between \(25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\) and \(400^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\). It is based on impact ionization data generated by the Boltzmann solver HARM [22]. It covers a wide range of electric fields ( \(50 \mathrm{kV} \mathrm{cm}^{-1}\) to \(600 \mathrm{kV} \mathrm{cm}^{-1}\) ) and temperatures ( 300 K to \(700 \mathrm{~K})\). The model is calibrated against impact ionization measurements [23][24] in the whole temperature range.

For an updated version of this model, see New University of Bologna Impact Ionization Model on page 522.

[Page 520 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Avalanche Generation

The model reads:
\[
\alpha\left(F_{\mathrm{ava}}, T\right)=\frac{F_{\mathrm{ava}}}{a(T)+b(T) \exp \left[\frac{d(T)}{F_{\mathrm{ava}}+c(T)}\right]}
\]

The temperature dependence of the model parameters, determined by fitting experimental data, reads (for electrons):
\[
a(T)=a_{0}+a_{1} t^{a_{2}} \quad b(T)=b_{0} \quad c(T)=c_{0}+c_{1} t+c_{2} t^{2} \quad d(T)=d_{0}+d_{1} t+d_{2} t^{2}
\]
and for holes:
\[
a(T)=a_{0}+a_{1} t \quad b(T)=b_{0} \exp \left[b_{1} t\right] \quad c(T)=c_{0} t^{c_{1}} \quad d(T)=d_{0}+d_{1} t+d_{2} t^{2}
\]
where \(t=T / 1 \mathrm{~K}\).
If BandgapDependence is specified as an argument to Avalanche, then \(d(T)\) is modified as follows:
\[
d(T) \rightarrow\left(\frac{\beta E_{\mathrm{g}}}{q \lambda} / d_{0}\right)\left(d_{0}+d_{1} t+d_{2} t^{2}\right)
\]
where \(E_{\mathrm{g}}\) is the energy bandgap, \(\lambda\) is the optical-phonon mean free path for the carrier, and \(\beta\) is a proportionality constant.

The model parameters are accessible in the UniB○ parameter set.

