\section*{Hatakeyama Avalanche Model}

The Hatakeyama avalanche model [28] describes the anisotropic behavior in 4H-SiC power devices. The impact ionization coefficient \(\alpha\) is obtained according to the Chynoweth law [18]:
\[
\alpha=\gamma a e^{-\frac{\gamma b}{F}}
\]
with:
\[
\gamma=\frac{\tanh \left(\frac{\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{op}}}{2 k T_{0}}\right)}{\tanh \left(\frac{\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{op}}}{2 k T}\right)}
\]

The coefficients \(a\) and \(b\) are computed dependent on the direction of the driving force \(\vec{F}\). For the hexagonal crystal coordinate system, the direction of anisotropy usually coincides with the (0001) lattice crystal direction, while the other crystal directions are considered to be isotropic, like (1120), for example. This allows for the decomposition of the driving force

[Page 524 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Avalanche Generation

\(\vec{F}\) into two components, parallel and orthogonal to the direction of anisotropy, to account for avalanche anisotropy.
The norm \(F=\|\vec{F}\|_{2}\) satisfies the equation:
\[
F^{2}=F_{0001}^{2}+F_{11 \overline{1} 0}^{2}
\]

Based on the projections \(F_{0001}\) and \(F_{11 \overline{2} 0}\), the coefficients \(a\) and \(b\) are computed as follows:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& B=\frac{F}{\sqrt{\left(\frac{F_{11 \overline{2} 0}}{b_{11 \overline{2} 0}}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{F_{0001}}{b_{0001}}\right)^{2}}} \\
& a=a_{11 \overline{2} 0}^{\left(\frac{B F_{11 \overline{2} 0}}{b_{11 \overline{2} 0} F}\right)^{2}\left(\frac{B F_{0001}}{b_{0001} F}\right)^{2}} a_{0001} \\
& A=\log \frac{a_{0001}}{a_{11 \overline{2} 0}} \\
& b=B \sqrt{1-\theta A^{2}\left(\frac{B F_{11 \overline{2} 0} F_{0001}}{F b_{11 \overline{2} 0} b_{0001}}\right)^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

With the default \(\theta=1\), coefficient \(b\) might become undefined for large values of the driving force \(F\) (the argument of the square root in Equation 487 becomes negative). This only happens if:
\[
F>\frac{2 \min \left(b_{0001}, b_{11 \overline{2} 0}\right)}{\left|\log \frac{a_{0001}}{a_{11 \overline{2} 0}}\right|}
\]

By setting \(\theta=0\), you have \(b=B\), and coefficients \(a\) and \(b\) depend only on the direction of the driving force \(F\), not its magnitude.

