\section*{Driving Force}

In Sentaurus Device, the driving force \(F_{\text {ava }}\) for impact ionization can be computed as the component of the electrostatic field in the direction of the current, \(F_{\text {ava }}=\stackrel{\rightharpoonup}{F} \cdot J_{n, p}\), (keyword Eparallel), or the value of the gradient of the quasi-Fermi level, \(F_{\text {ava }}=\left|\nabla \Phi_{n, p}\right|\), (keyword GradQuasiFermi). For these two possibilities, \(F_{\text {ava }}\) is affected by the keyword ParallelToInterfaceInBoundaryLayer (see Field Correction Close to Interfaces on page 473). For hydrodynamic simulations, \(F_{\text {ava }}\) can be computed from the carrier temperature (keyword CarrierTempDrive, see Avalanche Generation With Hydrodynamic Transport on page 529). The default model is GradQuasiFermi and, only for hydrodynamic simulations, it is CarrierTempDrive. See Table 243 on page 1681 for a summary of keywords.

The option ElectricField is used to perform breakdown simulations using the ionization integral method (see Approximate Breakdown Analysis on page 532).

