\section*{Off-State Breakdown Analysis}

The Off-State Breakdown Analysis (OBA) method is designed to estimate the breakdown voltage (BDV) of various power applications in off-state regime only. The OBA feature is available with a license.

The Poisson solution is sufficient for this method and this gives a possibility to use it for extra-large power devices with a quick turnaround time in comparison to the full drift-diffusion solution. Such an advantage to have quick BDV estimations for technology variations might be very noticeable for device structures with more than 1 million mesh nodes.

The OBA method estimates the avalanche generation rate (Equation 464) using the electron and hole avalanche coefficients ( \(\alpha_{n}\) and \(\alpha_{p}\), see section Avalanche Generation) and the electron and hole leakage current densities ( \(J_{n}\) and \(J_{p}\) ) estimated by local thermal, band-to-band tunneling, optical, and other activated carrier generation mechanisms (see models in Generation-Recombination). The Gauss law, applied for one mesh box area, allows to estimate the carrier current densities based on the total thermal and avalanche generation rates.

The OBA BDV is estimated at applied bias where integrated OBA avalanche generation rate is equal to the integrated SRH generation rate in the device area. The latter represents a device recombination capacity at the breakdown bias.

\section*{Using Off-State Breakdown Analysis}

The off-state breakdown analysis can be activated for the Poisson-only solution, and if necessary, for the full drift-diffusion solution also. The latter might be used with AvalPostProcessing in Math to speed up drift-diffusion runs. If the Poisson-only solution is used, then the ElectricField driving force should be used in Avalanche (see section Driving Force).

To stop Quasistationary bias ramping just after found BDV, use the BreakAtOBA keyword in the Math section. The OBA avalanche generation rate can be visualized by using OBA_AvalancheGeneration in the Plot section. To directly see the integrated OBA avalanche generation and SRH generation rates during bias ramping, use the following:
```
CurrentPlot{
    OBA_AvalancheGeneration (Integrate(Semiconductor))
    SRHrecombination (Integrate(Semiconductor))
}
```


Because OBA is based on an estimation of leakage currents, you can use the following fitting factor OBA_LeakageFactor=<value> in the Math section to increase or decrease the leakage currents (default value of the factor is equal to 1 ). This leads to a decrease or increase in BDV correspondingly.

[Page 531 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Approximate Breakdown Analysis

For applications where the breakdown area is near a semiconductor-insulator interface, use OBA_InterfaceFactor=1 in the Math section (default value is equal to 0 ) which also increases the leakage currents near the interface only with corresponding reduction of BDV.

\section*{Note:}

You must be careful with the Poisson-only solution for applications with the floating doping wells (FDWs). In this case, the full drift-diffusion solution with AvalPostProcessing in Math or Poisson-only with a specific FDW model (described in Alternative Initial Guess for Quasi-Fermi Potentials From Linear Conduction Equation on page 249) should be used with the OBA method.

\section*{Approximate Breakdown Analysis}

Junction breakdown due to avalanche generation is simulated by inspecting the ionization integrals:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& I_{n}=\int_{0}^{W} \alpha_{n}(x) e^{-\int_{x}^{W}\left(\alpha_{n}\left(x^{\prime}\right)-\alpha_{p}\left(x^{\prime}\right)\right) \mathrm{d} x^{\prime}} \mathrm{d} x \\
& I_{p}=\int_{0}^{W} \alpha_{p}(x) \mathrm{e}^{-\int_{0}^{x}\left(\alpha_{p}\left(x^{\prime}\right)-\alpha_{n}\left(x^{\prime}\right)\right) \mathrm{d} x^{\prime}} \mathrm{d} x
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\alpha_{n}, \alpha_{p}\) are the ionization coefficients for electrons and holes, respectively, and \(W\) is the width of the depletion zone. The integrations are performed along field lines through the depletion zone. Avalanche breakdown occurs if both ionization integrals are greater than or equal to one. Equation 496 describes electron injection (electron primary current) and Equation 497 describes hole injection. Since these breakdown criteria do not depend on current densities, you can perform a breakdown analysis by computing only the Poisson equation and ionization integrals under the assumption of constant quasi-Fermi levels in the depletion region.

\section*{Using Breakdown Analysis}

To activate breakdown analysis, Sentaurus Device provides the driving force ElectricField, which can be computed even for constant quasi-Fermi levels.

\section*{Note:}

The driving force ElectricField is less physical than the others available in Sentaurus Device. Therefore, you should use it only for approximate breakdown analysis.

