\section*{Note:}

Only quasistationary and transient simulations support multistate configurations. Small-signal analysis (see Small-Signal AC Analysis on page 155), harmonic balance analysis (see Harmonic Balance on page 160), and noise analysis (see Chapter 23 on page 806) do not support multistate configurations.
The computation of state occupation is influenced by the TrapFilling option of the set and Unset statements in the solve section (see Table 345 on page 1767). It is frozen if the trap-filling option Frozen is set; otherwise, the occupation rates are treated as free. You can release the frozen status again by the Unset (TrapFilling) statement.

The transition dynamic might become numerically unstable, that is, it cannot be solved with sufficient accuracy if, for example, the forward and backward rates of all transitions at one operation point differ by several orders of magnitude. Using -Elimination in MSConfig applies a different solving algorithm, often improving the numeric robustness in such cases.

The state occupation probabilities can be plotted in groups or individually by specifying MSConfig (see Table 343 on page 1766) in the Plot section.

\section*{Transition Models}

The MSC framework allows an arbitrary number of transitions between two states of an MSC. Each transition model can be either the model pmi_ce_msc, or a trap capture and emission PMI (see Trap Capture and Emission Rates on page 1427).

\section*{The pmi_ce_msc Model}

The pmi_ce_msc transition model supports the following features:
- Arbitrary number of states and transitions
- Charge states
- Several transition rate models (nucleation, growth, electron and hole exchange)
- Equilibrium computation (necessary for detailed balance processes)
- Energy and particle exchange

[Page 609 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Transition Models

\section*{States}

The states are described by a base energy \(E_{i}\), a degeneracy factor \(g_{i}\), the number of negative elementary charges \(K_{i}^{-}\)(an arbitrary integer), and the energy \(E_{i}^{-}\)of one electron in the state. The inner energy of the state is then:
\[
H_{i}=E_{i}+K_{i} E_{i}^{-}
\]

The electron energy is the sum of the valence band energy and the user-specified value \(E_{i, \text { user }}^{-}\)

\section*{Equilibrium}

The equilibrium occupation probabilities \(s^{*}\) are needed to guarantee the detailed balance principle for all transitions. The equilibrium is determined by the state parameters, the temperature, and the Fermi levels of the involved particle reservoirs. You have:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& Z_{i}=g_{i} \exp \left(-\beta\left(H_{i}-K_{i} E_{\mathrm{F}}\right)\right) \\
& Z=\sum_{i} Z_{i} \\
& s_{i}^{*}=Z_{i} / Z
\end{aligned}
\]

Here, \(E_{\mathrm{F}}\) is the quasi-Fermi energy and \(\beta\) is the thermodynamic beta. The quasi-Fermi energy is approximated inside the PMI. Let the (approximated) intrinsic density \(n_{\mathrm{I}}\) and the intrinsic Fermi energy \(E_{\mathrm{I}}\) be:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& n_{\mathrm{I}}=\sqrt{N_{\mathrm{C}} N_{\mathrm{V}} \exp \left(-\beta E_{\mathrm{g}}\right)} \\
& E_{\mathrm{I}}=\frac{1}{2}\left[\left(E_{\mathrm{C}}+E_{\mathrm{V}}\right)+k T \ln \left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{V}}}{N_{\mathrm{C}}}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
\]

Then, the carrier quasi-Fermi energies are approximated from the carrier densities by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& E_{\mathrm{F}, n}=E_{\mathrm{I}}+k T \ln \left(\frac{n}{n_{\mathrm{I}}}\right) \\
& E_{\mathrm{F}, p}=E_{\mathrm{I}}-k T \ln \left(\frac{p}{n_{\mathrm{I}}}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
and equilibrium Fermi energy then as:
\[
E_{\mathrm{F}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(E_{\mathrm{F}, n}+E_{\mathrm{F}, p}\right)
\]

\section*{Transitions}

You can select the transition models, listed in Table 107, by using the Formula parameter in the parameter file.

[Page 610 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Transition Models

In this section, \(i\) denotes the to state, while \(j\) specifies the from state of the transition. For most of the models, only the forward reaction rate (capture) is given, while the backward reaction rate (emission) is computed by:
\[
\frac{e}{c}=\frac{s_{j}^{*}}{s_{i}^{*}}
\]
if not stated otherwise.

\begin{table}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Table 107 The pmi_ce_msc transition models}
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Description & Formula \\
\hline Arrhenius law & 0 \\
\hline Nucleation according to Peng & 1 \\
\hline Growth according to Peng & 2 \\
\hline Single trap & 7 \\
\hline MSC trap & 8 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\section*{Arrhenius Law (Formula=0)}

The forward reaction rate (capture) is given by:
\[
c=r_{0} \exp \left(-\beta E_{\mathrm{act}}\right)
\]
where \(r_{0}\) is the maximal transition frequency and \(E_{\text {act }}\) is the activation energy.

\section*{Nucleation According to Peng (Formula=1)}

A nucleation model, in analogy to the model in [1], [2], and [3], is given by:
\[
c_{\mathrm{N}}=r_{0} \exp \left(-\beta\left(E_{\mathrm{act}}+\Delta G^{*}(T)\right)\right)
\]
where:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \Delta G^{*}(T)=\frac{16 \pi}{3} \frac{\gamma_{\mathrm{SL}}^{3}}{\Delta G(T)^{2}} \\
& \Delta G(T)=\left\{\begin{array}{llc}
\Delta H_{2}\left[1-\frac{T}{T_{\mathrm{g}}}\left(1-\frac{\Delta H_{1}}{\Delta H_{2}} \frac{T_{\mathrm{m}}-T_{\mathrm{g}}}{T_{\mathrm{m}}}\right)\right] & \text { if } & T<T_{\mathrm{g}} \\
\Delta H_{1} \frac{T_{\mathrm{m}}-T}{T_{\mathrm{m}}} & \text { if } T_{\mathrm{g}}<T<T_{\mathrm{m}} \\
0 & \text { if } & T_{\mathrm{m}}<T
\end{array}\right.
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 611 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Transition Models

\section*{Growth According to Peng (Formula=2)}

Growing crystalline phases is often described by a growth velocity, for example, in [1]. Some of the growing model has been adopted in the following local model, which reads as:
\[
c_{\mathrm{G}}=r_{0}\left[1-\exp \left(-\beta \Delta G(T) v_{\mathrm{MM}}\right)\right] \exp \left(-\beta E_{\mathrm{act}}\right)
\]
if \(T<T_{\mathrm{m}}\); otherwise, it is zero.

\section*{Single-Trap Transition (Formula=7)}

This model depends on the carrier density \(d_{\mathrm{c}}\). It resembles some standard trap models and is intended to be used in two-state MSCs only. If the number of electrons in the reference state is greater than in the interacting state, that is, \(K_{i}^{-}>K_{i}^{-}\), then the capture process depends on the electron density and uses \(d_{\mathrm{c}}=n\). If \(K_{i}^{-}<K_{j}^{-}\), then \(d_{\mathrm{c}}=p\); otherwise, you use \(d_{\mathrm{c}}=0\). The capture rate is then given by:
\[
c=\sigma v_{\mathrm{th}} d_{\mathrm{c}}
\]
where \(\sigma\) is the cross section and \(v_{\text {th }}\) is the thermal velocity. The emission rate for electron capturing is computed as:
\[
e=c \exp \left(\beta\left(E_{\mathrm{T}}-E_{\mathrm{F}, n}\right)\right)
\]
where \(E_{\mathrm{T}}\) is the trap energy. For hole-capturing, the emission rate reads as:
\[
e=c \exp \left(\beta\left(E_{\mathrm{F}, p}-E_{\mathrm{T}}\right)\right)
\]

\section*{MSC Trap With Emulated Detailed Balance (Formula=8)}

The actual model generalizes the single-trapping model (Formula=7) to general MSC states and transitions. The capture rate is computed as in the single trapping case above. The emission rate, however, is computed as follows. Let \(N_{n}\) and \(N_{p}\) be the number of electrons and holes, respectively, which are destroyed during the process. Then, you have:
\[
N_{n}-N_{p}=K_{i}-K_{j}
\]
and you require:
\[
\frac{e}{c}=g_{j i} \exp \left(-N_{n} \beta_{n}\left(E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-\overline{E_{\mathrm{C}}}\right)+N_{p} \beta_{p}\left(E_{\mathrm{F}, p}-\overline{E_{\mathrm{V}}}\right)+\beta_{l}\left(-N_{n} \overline{E_{\mathrm{C}}}+N_{p} \overline{E_{\mathrm{V}}}-H_{j i}\right)\right)
\]
where you used \(g_{j i}=g_{j} / g_{i}\) and \(H_{j i}=H_{j}-H_{i}\).
The average conduction band and valence band energies are:
\[
\overline{E_{\mathrm{C}}}=E_{\mathrm{C}}+\frac{3}{2} k T_{n} \quad \text { and } \quad \overline{E_{\mathrm{V}}}=E_{\mathrm{V}}-\frac{3}{2} k T_{p}
\]

In thermal equilibrium, the detailed balance principle is satisfied.

[Page 612 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Transition Models

\section*{Model Parameters}

The model requires parameters for all states and transitions to allow a consistent computation of the thermal equilibrium of the MSC as a whole. Therefore, parameters are grouped into global, state, and transition parameters.

The parameters nb_states and nb_transitions determine the number of states and transitions, respectively, and must be both consistent with the command file specification. The parameter sindex<int> specifies for the <int>-th state a parameter index, which determines a prefix for the state parameters. For example, given sindex \(0=5\), the parameters prefixed with s5_are read for the 0-th state. A similar parameter index selection is available for transitions using the parameters tindex<int> (for example, tindex \(2=7\) reads the parameters prefixed by t7_).

For transitions, the specified parameter index must coincide with the model index of the transition in the command file.

