\section*{Reactions Between Mobile Elements}

In the model, you can specify an arbitrary number of bulk and interface chemical reactions between hydrogen atoms \(\left(X_{1}\right)\), hydrogen molecules \(\left(X_{2}\right)\), hydrogen ions \(\left(X_{3}\right)\), electrons \(\left(X_{4}\right)\), and holes \(\left(X_{5}\right)\). Each reaction is defined by the following reaction equation:
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{5} \alpha_{i} X_{i} \leftrightarrow \sum_{i=1}^{5} \beta_{i} X_{i}
\]
where the nonnegative integers \(\alpha_{i}\) and \(\beta_{i}\) are the particle numbers of element \(X_{i}\) to be removed and created by the forward reaction.

These coefficients must satisfy the charge and hydrogen conservation laws:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \sum_{i=1}^{5}\left(\alpha_{i}-\beta_{i}\right) K_{i}^{Q}=0 \\
& \sum_{i=1}^{5}\left(\alpha_{i}-\beta_{i}\right) K_{i}^{\mathrm{H}}=0
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(K_{i}^{Q}\) and \(K_{i}^{\mathrm{H}}\) are the number of charges and the number of hydrogen atoms for element \(X_{i}\) (for \(K_{i}^{Q}\) and \(K_{i}^{\mathrm{H}}\) of each mobile element, see Table 106 on page 606).
The forward and reverse reaction rates \(R_{\mathrm{f}}\) and \(R_{\mathrm{r}}\) are modeled as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& R_{\mathrm{f}}=k_{\mathrm{f}} \exp \left(\delta_{\mathrm{f}} F-\frac{E_{\mathrm{f}}}{k T}\right) \prod_{i=1}^{5}\left(\frac{\left[X_{i}\right]}{1 / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}} \\
& R_{\mathrm{r}}=k_{\mathrm{r}} \exp \left(\delta_{\mathrm{r}} F-\frac{E_{\mathrm{r}}}{k T}\right) \prod_{i=1}^{5}\left(\frac{\left[X_{i}\right]}{1 / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right)^{\beta_{i}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(F\) is the magnitude of the electric field [ \(\mathrm{V} / \mathrm{cm}\) ].
- \(k_{\mathrm{f}}\) and \(k_{\mathrm{r}}\) are the forward and reverse reaction coefficients, respectively ([ \(\mathrm{cm}^{-3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) ] for bulk reactions and [ \(\mathrm{cm}^{-2} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) ] for interface reactions).
- \(\delta_{\mathrm{f}}\) and \(\delta_{\mathrm{r}}\) are the forward and reverse reaction field coefficients, respectively [ \(\mathrm{cmV}^{-1}\) ].
- \(E_{\mathrm{f}}\) and \(E_{\mathrm{r}}\) are the forward and reverse reaction activation energies, respectively \([\mathrm{eV}]\).

[Page 635 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


\section*{Note:}

For a reaction specified at a semiconductor-insulator interface, the insulator electric field is used instead of the semiconductor electric field.

A reaction can be specified in the Physics section as an argument HydrogenReaction to the HydrogenDiffusion keyword. For example, consider the dimerization of two hydrogen atoms into a hydrogen molecule \(2 \mathrm{H} \leftrightarrow \mathrm{H}_{2}\) in the oxide region with \(k_{\mathrm{f}}=10^{-3} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) and \(k_{\mathrm{r}}=10^{2} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\).

