\section*{The CEModel_Depassivation Model}

The built-in capture and emission model CEModel_Depassivation models the hydrogen depassivation process. In the model, the hydrogen depassivation (electron capture) rate induced by hot-electron distribution is written as:
\[
c_{\mathrm{PMI}}=2 g_{\mathrm{v}} \sigma \int_{\varepsilon_{\min }}^{\varepsilon_{\max }} \nu(\varepsilon) g(\varepsilon) f(\varepsilon)\left(\frac{\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{\mathrm{crit}}}{k T}\right)^{p} \exp \left[\gamma\left(\frac{F}{1 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{cm}}\right)^{\rho}-\frac{\Theta\left(W_{\mathrm{f}}-q \alpha F-\chi \varepsilon\right)\left(W_{\mathrm{f}}-q \alpha F-\chi \varepsilon\right)}{k T}\right]
\]
where:
- \(\varepsilon_{\text {min }}\) and \(\varepsilon_{\text {max }}\) are the minimum and maximum kinetic energies of the integration.
- \(\sigma\) is the capture cross-section.
- \(g_{\mathrm{v}}\) is the valley degeneracy.
- \(v(\varepsilon)\) is the magnitude of the group velocity.
- \(g(\varepsilon)\) is the density-of-states.
- \(f(\varepsilon)\) is the distribution function.
- \(\varepsilon_{\text {crit }}\) is the critical activation energy for depassivation.
- \(p\) is the exponent of the activation energy.
- \(\quad \gamma\) is the field enhancement prefactor.
- \(\rho\) is the field enhancement exponent.
- \(W_{\mathrm{f}}\) is the activation energy for the depassivation process.
- \(\alpha\) is the field-induced barrier-lowering factor.
- \(\chi\) is the kinetic energy-induced barrier-lowering factor.

[Page 638 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

MSC-Hydrogen Transport Degradation Model

Similarly, the hydrogen depassivation rate induced by cold electrons can be written as:
\[
c_{\mathrm{PMI}}=\sigma v_{\mathrm{th}} n \exp \left[\gamma\left(\frac{F}{1 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{cm}}\right)^{\rho}-\frac{\Theta\left(W_{\mathrm{f}}-q \alpha F\right)\left(W_{\mathrm{f}}-q \alpha F\right)}{k T}\right]
\]
where \(v_{\text {th }}\) is the thermal velocity.
As the hydrogen passivation (electron emission) rate is not related to hot carriers, it is modeled simply as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& e=e_{\mathrm{PMI}} \times\left(\frac{[\mathrm{H}]}{1 / \mathrm{cm}^{3}}\right) \\
& e_{\mathrm{PMI}}=e_{0} \exp \left(-\frac{W_{\mathrm{r}}}{k T}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(e_{0}\) is the passivation rate prefactor, and \(W_{\mathrm{r}}\) is the activation energy for the passivation process.

The built-in capture and emission model CEModel_Depassivation can also be used to model capture emission using Arrhenius law-type rate equations:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& C_{\mathrm{PMI}}=K_{f} \exp \left\{-\frac{E_{a_{f}}}{k T}\right\} \\
& E_{\mathrm{PMI}}=K_{r} \exp \left\{-\frac{E_{a_{r}}}{k T}\right\}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(E_{a_{f}}\) is the activation energy for the capture of carriers, \(K_{f}\) is the forward rate constant, \(E_{a_{r}}\) is the activation energy for the emission of carriers, and \(K_{r}\) is the backward rate constant.

The capture-emission model CEModel_Depassivation implements Equation 618 and Equation 619 for electrons and holes. The additional index in the CEModel_Depassivation model selects the equation and the carrier type as follows:
