\section*{Two-Stage NBTI Degradation Model}

Negative bias temperature instability (NBTI) refers to the generation of positive oxide charges and interface traps in MOS structures under negative gate bias at elevated temperature, which affects the threshold voltage and on-currents of PMOSFETs [12].

Sentaurus Device provides a two-stage NBTI degradation model [1][2], which assumes that the NBTI degradation proceeds using a two-stage process:
- The first stage includes the creation of \(E^{\prime}\) centers (dangling bonds in amorphous oxides) from their neutral oxygen vacancy precursors, the charging and discharging of \(E^{\prime}\) centers, and the total annealing of \(E^{\prime}\) centers to neutral oxygen vacancy precursors.
- The second stage considers the creation of poorly recoverable \(P_{\mathrm{b}}\) centers (dangling bonds at silicon-oxide interfaces).

In the two-stage NBTI degradation model, the involved energy levels and activation energies are distributed widely and are treated as random variables. A random sampling technique is used to obtain the average change of the interface charge.

[Page 643 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Two-Stage NBTI Degradation Model

\section*{Note:}

As the two-stage NBTI model is based on the semiclassical carrier density at the semiconductor-insulator interface, it is not recommended to use the model with quantum-correction models.

\section*{Formulation}

The two-stage NBTI degradation model considers a special trap having four internal states:
- \(s_{1}\) : Oxygen vacancy as a precursor state
- \(s_{2}\) : Positive \(E^{\prime}\) center
- \(s_{3}\) : Neutral \(E^{\prime}\) center
- \(s_{4}\) : Fixed positive charge with a \(P_{\mathrm{b}}\) center

Each NBTI trap is characterized by seven independent random variables:
- \(E_{1}\) : Trap level of the precursor \([\mathrm{eV}]\) (by default, \(-1.14 \leq E_{1}<-0.31\) )
- \(\quad E_{2}\) : Trap level of the \(E^{\prime}\) center \([\mathrm{eV}]\) (by default, \(0.01 \leq E_{2}<0.3\) )
- \(\quad E_{4}\) : Trap level of the \(P_{\mathrm{b}}\) center \([\mathrm{eV}]\) (by default, \(0.01 \leq E_{4}<0.5\) )
- \(E_{\mathrm{A}}\) : Barrier energy of a transition from \(s_{3}\) to \(s_{1}[\mathrm{eV}]\) (by default, \(0.01 \leq E_{\mathrm{A}}<1.15\) )
- \(E_{\mathrm{B}}\) : Barrier energy of a transition from \(s_{1}\) to \(s_{2}[\mathrm{eV}]\) (by default, \(0.01 \leq E_{\mathrm{B}}<1.15\) )
- \(E_{\mathrm{D}}\) : Barrier energy of a transition between \(s_{2}\) to \(s_{4}[\mathrm{eV}]\) (by default,
\[
\left.\left\langle E_{\mathrm{D}}\right\rangle=1.46,\left(\left\langle E_{\mathrm{D}}^{2}\right\rangle-\left\langle E_{\mathrm{D}}\right\rangle^{2}\right)^{1 / 2}=0.44\right)
\]
- \(r\) : Uniform number between 0 and 1 ; when \(r<C\), a transition from \(s_{2}\) to \(s_{4}\) is allowed (by default, \(C=0.12\) )
\(E_{1}, E_{2}, E_{4}, E_{\mathrm{A}}\), and \(E_{\mathrm{B}}\) follow the uniform distribution between their minimum and maximum values. \(E_{\mathrm{D}}\) follows the Fermi-derivative distribution characterized by its average and standard deviation. The trap levels \(E_{1}, E_{2}\), and \(E_{4}\) are defined relative to the valence band energy.

The state occupation probability \(s_{i}\) satisfies the normalization condition:
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{4} s_{i}=1
\]

[Page 644 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Two-Stage NBTI Degradation Model

and the following rate equations:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \dot{s}_{1}=-s_{1} k_{12}+s_{3} k_{31} \\
& \dot{s}_{2}=s_{1} k_{12}-s_{2}\left(k_{23}+k_{24}\right)+s_{3} k_{32}+s_{4} k_{42} \\
& \dot{s}_{3}=s_{2} k_{23}-s_{3}\left(k_{32}+k_{31}\right) \\
& \dot{s}_{4}=s_{2} k_{24}-s_{4} k_{42}
\end{aligned}
\]
with the transition rates:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{12}=e_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, 1}+c_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 1} \\
& k_{23}=c_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, 2}+e_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 2} \\
& k_{32}=e_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, 2}+c_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 2} \\
& k_{31}=v_{1} \exp \left(-E_{\mathrm{A}} / k T\right) \\
& k_{24}=v_{2} \exp \left[-\left(E_{\mathrm{D}}-\gamma F\right) / k T\right] \Theta(C-r) \\
& k_{42}=v_{2} \exp \left[-\left(E_{\mathrm{D}}+\Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}+\gamma F\right) / k T\right] \Theta(C-r)
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(v_{1}\) and \(v_{2}\) are the attempt frequencies (default: \(v_{1}=1.0 \times 10^{13} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) and \(v_{2}=5.11 \times 10^{15} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) ).
- \(\gamma\) is the prefactor for the field-dependent barrier energy (default: \(\gamma=7.4 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm} \cdot \mathrm{eV} / \mathrm{V}\) ).
- \(\Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}\) is the additional barrier energy for \(k_{42}\) (default: \(\Delta E_{\mathrm{D}}=0 \mathrm{eV}\) ).

In addition, it is assumed that the hole occupation probability \(f_{\mathrm{it}}^{p}\) of the \(P_{\mathrm{b}}\) center in the state 4 is determined by:
\[
\dot{f}_{\mathrm{it}}^{p}=\left(e_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, 4}+c_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 4}\right)\left(1-f_{\mathrm{it}}^{p}\right)-\left(c_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, 4}+e_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 4}\right) f_{\mathrm{it}}^{p}
\]

The electron emission rate and the hole capture rate for the state 1 are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
e_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, 1} & =\sigma_{n} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{n} N_{\mathrm{C}} \exp \left[-H\left(E_{\mathrm{C}}-E_{1}\right) / k T+\Theta\left(F_{\mathrm{c}, n}\right)\left(|F| / F_{\mathrm{c}, n}\right)^{\rho_{n}}-E_{\mathrm{B}} / k T\right] \\
c_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 1} & =\sigma_{p} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p} p \exp \left[-H\left(E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{1}\right) / k T+\Theta\left(F_{\mathrm{c}, p}\right)\left(|F| / F_{\mathrm{c}, p}\right)^{\rho_{p}}-E_{\mathrm{B}} / k T\right]
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(\sigma_{n}\) and \(\sigma_{p}\) are the electron and hole capture cross-sections (default: \(\sigma_{n}=1.08 \times 10^{-15} \mathrm{~cm}^{2}\) and \(\sigma_{p}=1.24 \times 10^{-14} \mathrm{~cm}^{2}\) ).
- \(v_{\text {th }}^{n}\) and \(v_{\text {th }}^{p}\) are the electron and hole thermal velocity (default: \(v_{\text {th }}^{n}=1.5 \times 10^{7} \mathrm{~cm} / \mathrm{s}\) and \(v_{\text {th }}^{p^{1}}=1.2 \times 10^{7} \mathrm{~cm} / \mathrm{s}\) ).
- \(F\) is the insulator electric field.

[Page 645 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Two-Stage NBTI Degradation Model
- \(\quad F_{\mathrm{c}, n}\) and \(F_{\mathrm{c}, p}\) are the critical electric field (default: \(F_{\mathrm{c}, n}=-1 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{cm}\) and
\[
\left.F_{\mathrm{c}, p}=2.83 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{cm}\right) .
\]
- \(\rho_{n}\) and \(\rho_{p}\) are the exponents of the field-dependent term (default: \(\rho_{n}=2\) and \(\rho_{p}=2\) ).
- \(H(x)=x \Theta(x)\).

When the energy-dependent hole distribution is available (hSHEDistribution is activated in the semiconductor region), you can use the following expression for \(c_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 1}\) instead of Equation 637:
\[
c_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, 1}=2 g_{\mathrm{v}} \sigma_{p} \int_{0}^{\infty} v(\varepsilon) g(\varepsilon) f(\varepsilon) \exp \left[-H\left(E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{1}-\varepsilon\right) / k T+\Theta\left(F_{\mathrm{c}, p}\right)\left(|F| / F_{\mathrm{c}, p}\right)^{\rho_{p}}-E_{\mathrm{B}} / k T\right] d \varepsilon
\]

The electron capture rate, the electron emission rate, the hole capture rate, and the hole emission rate for state 2 and state 4 are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
c_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, i} & =\sigma_{n} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{n} n \exp \left[-H\left(E_{i}-E_{\mathrm{C}}\right) / k T\right] \\
e_{\mathrm{C}}^{n, i} & =\sigma_{n} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{n} N_{\mathrm{C}} \exp \left[-H\left(E_{\mathrm{C}}-E_{i}\right) / k T\right] \\
c_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, i} & =\sigma_{p} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p} p \exp \left[-H\left(E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{i}\right) / k T\right] \\
e_{\mathrm{V}}^{p, i} & =\sigma_{p} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p} N_{\mathrm{V}} \exp \left[-H\left(E_{i}-E_{\mathrm{V}}\right) / k T\right]
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(i=2\) or 4 .

\section*{Using Two-Stage NBTI Model}

You can activate the two-stage NBTI model by specifying the NBTI command in the interface-specific Physics section of the command file. For example:
```
Physics ( MaterialInterface = "Silicon/Oxide" ) {
    NBTI (
        Conc = 5.0e12 # N_0 [/ cm^2]
        NumberOfSamples = 1000 # N_sample [1]
        hSHEDistribution | -hSHEDistribution # (off by default)
    )
}
```

where Conc represents the density of the precursor \(N_{0}\), and NumberOfSamples represents the number of random samples \(N_{\text {sample }}\). Sentaurus Device generates \(N_{\text {sample }}\) random configurations for each interface vertex.

Then, the interface charge density is obtained from the ensemble average as follows:
\[
Q=Q_{\mathrm{ox}}+Q_{\mathrm{it}}=q N_{0}\left\langle s_{2}+s_{4}\right\rangle+q N_{0}\left\langle s_{4} \mathrm{p}_{\mathrm{it}}^{p}\right\rangle
\]

