\section*{Extended Nonradiative Multiphonon Model}

The extended nonradiative multiphonon (eNMP) model [3] can be used to investigate degradation related to NBTI. The model accounts for the behavior of oxide defects (traps) that can have four internal states, two of which are metastable.

As with the two-stage NBTI degradation model, the eNMP model uses a random sampling technique to obtain the average behavior of multiple sample defects ( \(N_{\text {sample }}\) ) at each interface vertex. The sample defects are considered to have random insulator positions, and distributed energy levels and activation energies.

Each sample defect is assumed to be located at a distance \(x_{\mathrm{t}}\) from the interface, where \(x_{\mathrm{t}}\) is distributed randomly between a minimum and maximum location:
\[
x_{\mathrm{t}, \min }<x_{\mathrm{t}}<x_{\mathrm{t}, \max }
\]

[Page 647 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Extended Nonradiative Multiphonon Model

\section*{Note:}

The implementation treats the average charge associated with the sample defects as an interface charge.

\section*{eNMP Model Description}

The eNMP model considers a special trap having four internal states:
- \(s_{1}\) : Neutral stable state
- \(s_{2}\) : Positive stable state
- \(s_{1}\) : Neutral metastable state
- \(s_{2^{\prime}}\) : Positive metastable state

The model describes the transitions between these states according to the diagram in Figure 24 , in which the \(k_{\mathrm{ij}}\) terms represent the transition rates between the states.

\begin{figure}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Figure 24 State diagram for the eNMP model}
\includegraphics[alt={},max width=\textwidth]{https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/f7af57de-59b5-428e-a177-d4f23fc59969-407.jpg?height=416&width=450&top_left_y=1241&top_left_x=483}
\end{figure}

The state occupation probabilities \(s_{\mathrm{i}}\) satisfy the normalization condition:
\[
s_{1}+s_{1^{\prime}}+s_{2}+s_{2^{\prime}}=1
\]

The rate equations for the transitions are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \dot{s}_{1}=-s_{1}\left(k_{11^{\prime}}+k_{12^{\prime}}\right)+s_{1^{\prime}} k_{1^{\prime} 1}+s_{2^{\prime}} k_{2^{\prime} 1} \\
& \dot{s}_{2}=-s_{2}\left(k_{21^{\prime}}+k_{22^{\prime}}\right)+s_{1^{\prime}} k_{1^{\prime} 2}+s_{2^{\prime}} k_{2^{\prime} 2} \\
& \dot{s}_{1^{\prime}}=-s_{1^{\prime}}\left(k_{1^{\prime} 1}+k_{1^{\prime} 2}\right)+s_{1} k_{11^{\prime}}+s_{2} k_{21^{\prime}} \\
& \dot{s}_{2^{\prime}}=-s_{2^{\prime}}\left(k_{2^{\prime} 1}+k_{2^{\prime} 2}\right)+s_{1} k_{12^{\prime}}+s_{2} k_{22^{\prime}}
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 648 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Extended Nonradiative Multiphonon Model

The eight transition rates are given by the following expressions:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{12^{\prime}}=\left(1+R_{1}\right)^{3 / 2} \sigma_{p} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p} p \exp \left(-\varepsilon_{12^{\prime}} / k T\right) \\
& k_{2^{\prime} 1}=\left(1+R_{1}\right)^{3 / 2} \sigma_{p} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p} N_{\mathrm{V}} \exp \left(-\varepsilon_{12^{\prime}} / k T\right) \exp \left(-\left(E_{\mathrm{t}}-E_{\mathrm{V}}-\varepsilon_{T 2^{\prime}}\right) / k T\right) \\
& k_{1^{\prime} 2}=\left(1+R_{1^{\prime}}\right)^{3 / 2} \sigma_{p} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p} p \exp \left(-\varepsilon_{1^{\prime} 2} / k T\right) \\
& k_{21^{\prime}}=\left(1+R_{1^{\prime}}\right)^{3 / 2} \sigma_{p} v_{\mathrm{th}}^{p} N_{\mathrm{V}} \exp \left(-\varepsilon_{1^{\prime} 2} / k T\right) \exp \left(-\left(E_{\mathrm{t}}^{\prime}-E_{\mathrm{V}}\right) / k T\right) \\
& k_{11^{\prime}}=v_{0} \exp \left(-\left(\varepsilon_{1^{\prime} 1}+E_{\mathrm{t}}^{\prime}-E_{\mathrm{t}}\right) / k T\right) \\
& k_{1^{\prime} 1}=v_{0} \exp \left(-\varepsilon_{1^{\prime} 1} / k T\right) \\
& k_{22^{\prime}}=v_{0} \exp \left(-\left(\varepsilon_{2^{\prime} 2}+\varepsilon_{T 2^{\prime}}\right) / k T\right) \\
& k_{2^{\prime} 2}=v_{0} \exp \left(-\varepsilon_{2^{\prime} 2} / k T\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
with:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \varepsilon_{12^{\prime}}=\frac{\left(S_{1} h \omega_{1}\right)}{\left(1+R_{1}\right)^{2}}+\frac{R_{1}}{1+R_{1}}\left(E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{\mathrm{t}}+\varepsilon_{T 2^{\prime}}\right) \\
& \varepsilon_{1^{\prime} 2}=\frac{\left(S_{1^{\prime}} h \omega_{1^{\prime}}\right)}{\left(1+R_{1^{\prime}}\right)^{2}}+\frac{R_{1^{\prime}}}{1+R_{1^{\prime}}}\left(E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{\mathrm{t}}^{\prime}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

For an insulator defect located a distance \(x_{\mathrm{t}}\) from the interface:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \sigma_{p}=\sigma_{p 0} \exp \left(-x_{\mathrm{t}} / x_{0}\right) \\
& E_{\mathrm{t}}-E_{\mathrm{V}}=E_{\mathrm{t} 0}-E_{\mathrm{V} 0}+q x_{\mathrm{t}}|F|=\Delta E_{\mathrm{t}}+q x_{\mathrm{t}}|F| \\
& E_{\mathrm{t}}^{\prime}-E_{\mathrm{V}}=E_{\mathrm{t} 0}^{\prime}-E_{\mathrm{V} 0}+q x_{\mathrm{t}}|F|=\Delta E_{\mathrm{t}}^{\prime}+q x_{\mathrm{t}}|F|
\end{aligned}
\]

In these expressions:
- \(\sigma_{p 0}\) is the hole-capture cross section, and \(\exp \left(-x_{\mathrm{t}} / x_{0}\right)\) accounts for the trap depth of tunneling.
- \(\Delta E_{\mathrm{t}}\) and \(\Delta E_{\mathrm{t}}^{\prime}\) are the energy levels of the defect in the neutral stable state and the neutral metastable state, respectively, relative to the valence band energy in the absence of an electric field.
- \(F\) is the insulator electric field.
- \(v_{\text {th }}^{p}\) is the hole thermal velocity.
- \(\varepsilon_{\mathrm{ij}}\) represent the transition energies between states.
- \(\varepsilon_{T 2^{\prime}}\) is the energy of the positive metastable state relative to the positive stable state.
- \(\omega_{\mathrm{i}}\) are vibrational frequencies.
- \(R_{1}=\omega_{1} / \omega_{2^{\prime}}\) and \(R_{1^{\prime}}=\omega_{1^{\prime}} / \omega_{2}\).

[Page 649 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Extended Nonradiative Multiphonon Model
- \(S_{\mathrm{i}} \hbar \omega_{\mathrm{i}}\) are relaxation energies, where \(S_{\mathrm{i}}\) are known as Huang-Rhys factors.
- \(v_{0}\) is the attempt frequency.

\section*{Using the eNMP Model}

You can activate the eNMP model in an interface-specific Physics section of the command file with the keyword enmp. The command syntax and options are:
```
Physics (MaterialInterface="<mat1>/<mat2>" |
            RegionInterface="<reg1>/reg2>") {
    eNMP (
        NumberOfSamples = <Nsample> # Typically, 1000
        Conc = <NO> # 1/ cm2, for example, 5e12
        [ SFactor="<dataset_name-or-pmi_model_name>" ]
        [ <eNMPTransitionRates_pmi_model_name> [StateCharge=<1 | -1>] ]
    )
}
```

where Conc represents the density of the precursor \(N_{0}\). By default, the precursor concentration is constant over the interface. However, if SFactor is specified, the precursor concentration is obtained from a dataset (or a PMI user field that is read from the file specified with PMIUserFields in the File section of the command file), or from a space factor PMI written by users (see Space Factor on page 1517). If SFactor is specified without specifying Conc, then the SFactor interface values are used directly. If SFactor is specified in addition to Conc, then the SFactor values are normalized by the largest SFactor value and multiplied by Conc.

The NumberOfSamples keyword represents the number of random samples, \(N_{\text {sample }} \cdot\) Sentaurus Device generates \(N_{\text {sample }}\) random defects for each interface vertex. Then, the interface charge density is obtained from the ensemble average of the charge states:
\[
Q=q N_{0}\left\langle s_{2}+s_{2}\right\rangle
\]
where \(\langle x\rangle=\frac{1}{N_{\text {sample }}} \sum_{j=1}^{N_{\text {sample }}} x^{j}\).
During transient simulations, the state occupation changes according to the rate equations (Equation 646 to Equation 649), which will change the interface charge density. It is assumed that \(s_{1}=1\) at the beginning, with all other states unoccupied.

