\section*{eNMP Transition Rates PMI Model}

An eNMP transition rates PMI model (see eNMP Transition Rates on page 1437) created by users can be utilized to calculate the transition rates for the eNMP model. This PMI allows for the possibility of either a positive or negative state charge, and provides additional dependencies that are not included in the built-in eNMP model.

\section*{Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model}

The hot-carrier stress (HCS) degradation model is based on work in [15], and can be used as a general degradation model for MOS-based devices.

The HCS degradation model includes different mechanisms that contribute to bond breakage and the formation of interface traps [11][16][17]:
- Single-particle (SP) processes, where a single particle is responsible for bond breakage
- Multiple-particle (MP) processes, where the combined actions of several particles contribute to bond breakage
- Field-enhanced thermal (TH) processes, where thermal interactions with the lattice contribute to bond breakage

Sentaurus Device includes both an electron version of the model (eHCSDegradation) and a hole version of the model (hHCSDegradation).

The model and its usage are described in the following sections.

\section*{Model Description}

The model equations are presented here. Details can be found in [15]. The equations presented apply to both the eHCSDegradation and hHCSDegradation models.

[Page 653 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model

\section*{Single-Particle and Multiple-Particle Interface-Trap Densities}

For the SP case, the interface trap density as a function of time and activation energy is given by:
\[
N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{SP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, t, E_{\mathrm{SP}}\right)=P_{\mathrm{SP}} N_{0}\left[1-e^{-k_{\mathrm{SP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{SP}}\right) t}\right]
\]
where:
- \(P_{\mathrm{SP}}\) is the probability for defect generation by SP processes.
- \(\quad N_{0}\) is the maximum number of interface bonds.
- \(E_{\mathrm{SP}}\) is the activation energy for SP processes.
- \(k_{\mathrm{SP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{SP}}\right)\) is the reaction rate for SP processes.

For the MP case, the interface trap density is given by:
\[
N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{MP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, t, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right)=P_{\mathrm{MP}} N_{0}\left[\frac{P_{\mathrm{emi}}}{P_{\mathrm{pass}}}\left(\frac{P_{\mathrm{u}}}{P_{\mathrm{d}}}\right)^{N_{\mathrm{l}}}\left(1-e^{-P_{\mathrm{emi}} t}\right)\right]^{1 / 2}
\]
where:
- \(P_{\mathrm{MP}}\) is the probability for defect generation by MP processes.
- \(\quad N_{1}\) is the number of energy levels in the oscillator that models the bond.

The emission and passivation probabilities \(P_{\text {emi }}\) and \(P_{\text {pass }}\) are modeled as Arrhenius laws:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& P_{\mathrm{emi}}=v_{\mathrm{emi}} e^{-E_{\mathrm{emi}} /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)} \\
& P_{\mathrm{pass}}=v_{\mathrm{pass}} e^{-E_{\mathrm{pass}} /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(v_{\text {emi }}\) and \(v_{\text {pass }}\) are the emission and passivation frequencies, respectively.
- \(E_{\mathrm{emi}}\) and \(E_{\mathrm{pass}}\) are the emission and passivation energies, respectively.

The oscillator excitation and de-excitation probability rates are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& P_{\mathrm{u}}=k_{\mathrm{ph}} e^{-E_{\mathrm{ph}} /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)}+k_{\mathrm{MP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right) \\
& P_{\mathrm{d}}=k_{\mathrm{ph}}+k_{\mathrm{MP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(E_{\mathrm{ph}}\) and \(k_{\mathrm{ph}}\) are the phonon energy and the reaction rate, respectively.
- \(E_{\mathrm{MP}}\) is the activation energy for MP processes.
- \(k_{\mathrm{MP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right)\) is the reaction rate for MP processes.

[Page 654 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model

The reaction rates for SP and MP processes are given by scattering-rate integrals:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{\mathrm{SP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{SP}}\right)=\int_{E_{\mathrm{SP}}}^{\infty} f(\boldsymbol{r}, E) g(E) v(E) \sigma_{\mathrm{SP}}(E) d E \\
& k_{\mathrm{MP}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right)=\int_{E_{\mathrm{MP}}}^{\infty} f(\boldsymbol{r}, E) g(E) v(E) \sigma_{\mathrm{MP}}(E) d E
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(f(\boldsymbol{r}, E)\) is the carrier distribution function.
- \(g(E)\) is the total density-of-states.
- \(v(E)\) is the magnitude of the carrier velocity.
- \(\sigma_{\mathrm{SP}}(E)\) and \(\sigma_{\mathrm{MP}}(E)\) are the SP and MP reaction cross-sections.

The reaction cross-sections are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \sigma_{\mathrm{SP}}(E)=\sigma_{\mathrm{SP} 0}\left(\frac{E-E_{\mathrm{SP}}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right)^{p_{\mathrm{SP}}} \\
& \sigma_{\mathrm{MP}}(E)=\sigma_{\mathrm{MP} 0}\left(\frac{E-E_{\mathrm{MP}}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right)^{p_{\mathrm{MP}}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(p_{\mathrm{SP}}\) and \(p_{\mathrm{MP}}\) are exponents characterizing the SP and MP processes.
- \(\sigma_{\mathrm{SP} 0}\) and \(\sigma_{\mathrm{MP} 0}\) are fitting parameters.

\section*{Field-Enhanced Thermal Degradation}

The interface-trap density due to field-enhanced thermal degradation is given by:
\[
N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{TH}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, t, E_{\mathrm{TH}}\right)=P_{\mathrm{TH}} N_{0}\left[1-e^{-k_{\mathrm{TH}}\left(E_{\mathrm{TH}}\right) t}\right]
\]
where:
- \(P_{\mathrm{TH}}\) is the probability for defect generation by thermal processes.
- The reaction rate for bond breakage \(k_{\mathrm{TH}}\) is given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{\mathrm{TH}}\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E_{\mathrm{TH}}\right)=v_{\mathrm{TH}} e^{-E_{\mathrm{TH}} /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)} \\
& E_{\mathrm{TH}}=E_{\mathrm{TH} 0}-p E_{\mathrm{ox}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(v_{\mathrm{TH}}\) is the lattice collision frequency.

[Page 655 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model
- \(E_{\mathrm{TH} 0}\) is the activation energy for thermal processes in the absence of oxide field \(E_{\mathrm{ox}}\).
- \(p\) is the effective dipole moment.

\section*{Carrier Distribution Function}

There are two options for obtaining the carrier distribution function \(f(\boldsymbol{r}, E)\) used in the calculation of the scattering-rate integrals (Equation 676 and Equation 677):
- From the spherical harmonics expansion (SHE) method
- From an approximate analytic formulation

\section*{Spherical Harmonics Expansion Option}

The SHE method computes the microscopic carrier-energy distribution function by solving the lowest-order SHE of the Boltzmann transport equation. When the carrier distribution function is available through the SHE method, it can optionally be used directly in the evaluation of Equation 676 and Equation 677. In this case, the band structure quantities \(g(E)\) and \(v(E)\) used in these equations are the same as those used in the SHE calculations.

\section*{Note:}

If the carrier distribution function is available through the SHE method, the SHE temperature will be used instead of the carrier temperature in the model equations, if the hydrodynamic model is not used.

\section*{Approximate Analytic Option}

A method for obtaining an approximate carrier distribution function [15] is available. In this case, \(f(\boldsymbol{r}, E)\) is modeled using an analytic non-Maxwellian formulation:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& f_{0}(\boldsymbol{r}, E)=\frac{1}{A(\boldsymbol{r})} \exp \left[-\alpha(\boldsymbol{r}) \frac{\gamma(E)}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T_{c}(\boldsymbol{r})}\right] \\
& \gamma(E)=\frac{E(1+\delta E)}{1+\beta E}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(\quad T_{c}(\boldsymbol{r})\) is the carrier temperature ( \(T_{n}\) for eHCSDegradation and \(T_{p}\) for hHCSDegradation).
- \(\delta\) and \(\beta\) are fitting parameters.

[Page 656 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model
- \(A(\boldsymbol{r})\) and \(\alpha(\boldsymbol{r})\) are position-dependent parametric factors that are determined by requiring that:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& c(\boldsymbol{r})=\int_{0}^{E_{\max }} f_{0}(\boldsymbol{r}, E) g(E) d E \\
& T_{c}(\boldsymbol{r})=\frac{2}{3 k_{\mathrm{B}}} \frac{\int_{0}^{E_{\max }} E\left(f_{0}(\boldsymbol{r}, E) g(E) d E\right)}{c(\boldsymbol{r})}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(c(\boldsymbol{r})\) is the electron concentration for eHCSDegradation and the hole concentration for hHCSDegradation. \(E_{\text {max }}=10 \mathrm{eV}\) is used as the upper integration limit.

\section*{Bond Dispersion}

The reaction rates given by Equation 676, Equation 677, and Equation 681 are for a discrete activation energy. As an option, these rates can be modified to account for bond dispersion by assuming a distribution function for the activation energies:
\[
g_{\mathrm{A}, j}(E)=\frac{1}{\sigma_{g}} \frac{\exp \left(\frac{E_{j}-E}{\sigma_{g}}\right)}{\left[1+\exp \left(\frac{E_{j}-E}{\sigma_{g}}\right)\right]^{2}}
\]
where \(\sigma_{\mathrm{g}}\) is a dispersion width and \(j=\mathrm{SP}\), MP, or TH.
The interface trap generation for each process \(j\) is then calculated from:
\[
N_{\mathrm{it}, j}(\boldsymbol{r}, t)=\frac{1}{N_{g_{A, j}}} \int_{E_{j}-m \sigma_{\mathrm{g}}}^{E_{j}+m \sigma_{\mathrm{g}}} g_{\mathrm{A}, j}(E) N_{\mathrm{it}, j}(\boldsymbol{r}, t, E) d E
\]
where:
\[
N_{g_{A, j}}=\int_{E_{j}-m \sigma_{\mathrm{g}}}^{E_{j}+m \sigma_{\mathrm{g}}} g_{\mathrm{A}, j}(E) d E
\]

Note that Equation 688 requires the scattering rates for each energy used in the calculation of the integral:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{\mathrm{SP} / \mathrm{MP}}(\boldsymbol{r}, E)=\int_{E}^{\infty} f\left(\boldsymbol{r}, E^{\prime}\right) g\left(E^{\prime}\right) v\left(E^{\prime}\right) \sigma_{\mathrm{SP}}\left(E^{\prime}\right) d E^{\prime}, E_{\mathrm{SP} / \mathrm{MP}}-m \sigma_{g}<E<E_{\mathrm{SP} / \mathrm{MP}}+m \sigma_{g} \\
& k_{\mathrm{TH}}(\boldsymbol{r}, E)=v_{\mathrm{TH}} e^{-E /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)}, E_{\mathrm{TH}}-m \sigma_{g}<E<E_{\mathrm{TH}}+m \sigma_{g}
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 657 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model

The total interface-trap generation rate is taken as the sum of the separate processes:
\[
N_{\mathrm{it}}(\boldsymbol{r}, t)=N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{SP}}(\boldsymbol{r}, t)+N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{MP}}(\boldsymbol{r}, t)+N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{TH}}(\boldsymbol{r}, t)
\]

\section*{Time-Dependent Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model}

When the reaction rates \(k_{\mathrm{SP}}\left(r, E_{\mathrm{SP}}\right), k_{\mathrm{MP}}\left(r, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right)\), and \(k_{\mathrm{TH}}\left(r, E_{\mathrm{TH}}\right)\) depend on time, the kinetic equations governing trap generation cannot be integrated to a closed form expression, as done in the previous sections (Equation 670, Equation 671, and Equation 680). For such a case, a more general time-dependent model formulation is needed [18].

The time-dependent SP and TH interface trap densities can be written as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{SP}}\left(r, t, E_{\mathrm{SP}}\right)=P_{\mathrm{SP}} N_{0}\left(1-e^{-\int_{0}^{t} k_{\mathrm{SP}}\left(r, t, E_{\mathrm{SP}}\right) d t}\right) \\
& N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{TH}}\left(r, t, E_{\mathrm{TH}}\right)=P_{\mathrm{TH}} N_{0}\left(1-e^{-\int_{0}^{t} k_{\mathrm{TH}}\left(r, t, E_{\mathrm{TH}}\right) d t}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where parameters have their usual meanings, as previously described.
For MP processes, the number of unbroken bonds \(n_{\mathrm{nB}}\) (normalized by \(N_{0}\) ) at the interface is the sum of the occupations \(n_{j}\) of the \(N_{l}\) states of the oscillator that models the bond [16][17]:
\[
\frac{d n_{\mathrm{nB}}}{d t}=\frac{d \sum_{j=0}^{N_{l}} n_{j}}{d t}=\sum_{j=0}^{N_{l}} \frac{d n_{j}}{d t}=a(t)+b(t) n_{\mathrm{nB}}+c(t) n_{\mathrm{nB}}^{2}
\]
where:
\[
\begin{aligned}
a(t) & =P_{\mathrm{pass}} \\
b(t) & =-\left[P_{\mathrm{emi}} F(q)+2 P_{\mathrm{pass}}\right] \\
c(t) & =P_{\mathrm{pass}} \\
F(q) & =\frac{q^{N_{l}}(1-q)}{1-q^{N_{l}+1}} \\
q & =\frac{P_{u}}{P_{d}}
\end{aligned}
\]

By solving Equation 695, the interface trap density for the MP process can be evaluated as:
\[
N_{\mathrm{it}, \mathrm{MP}}\left(r, t, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right)=P_{\mathrm{MP}} N_{0}\left[1-n_{\mathrm{nB}}\left(r, t, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right)\right]
\]

[Page 658 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model

These equations for the SP, MP, and TH trap densities are for a discrete activation energy \(\left(E_{\mathrm{SP}}, E_{\mathrm{MP}}\right.\), and \(\left.E_{\mathrm{TH}}\right)\). In the case of bond dispersion, the discrete activation energy must be replaced by a distribution of bond activations, as described in Bond Dispersion on page 657.

\section*{Using the HCS Degradation Model}

You can include the HCS degradation model in a transient simulation by specifying the eHCSDegradation option, or the hHCSDegradation option, or both options as part of a Traps specification for the interface of interest.

The syntax and options for these models are:
```
Physics (MaterialInterface = "Silicon/Oxide") {
    Traps (
        (eHCSDegradation([SHE] [BondDispersion]
            [BDEnergyIntervals=<int>] [TimeDependentRates])
        # Specify appropriate parameters for the generated traps.
        Acceptor Level EnergyMid=0 fromMidBandGap
        )
        (hHCSDegradation([SHE] [BondDispersion]
            [BDEnergyIntervals=<int>] [TimeDependentRates])
        # Specify appropriate parameters for the generated traps.
        Donor Level EnergyMid=0 fromMidBandGap
        )
    )
}
```


Notes regarding this specification:
- If the SHE option is selected, then the distribution function and the band-structure quantities are obtained from the SHE method specified in the Physics section. For example:
```
Physics (Material = "Silicon") {
    eSHEDistribution(FullBand)
}
```

- If SHE is not selected, then an approximate distribution function is used as described in Approximate Analytic Option on page 656. In this case, the band-structure quantities used in the calculations will be taken from the SHE full-band structure files.
- BondDispersion is used by default. Use -BondDispersion to switch off this option. The number of energy intervals to use in the bond dispersion integral (Equation 688) can be specified with BDEnergyIntervals (default: 20).

[Page 659 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model
- If TimeDependentRates is specified, then the more general time-dependent HCS model formulation is used (see Time-Dependent Hot-Carrier Stress Degradation Model on page 658).
- If using FixedCharge traps, then negative charge will be created with the eHCSDegradation model, and positive charge will be created with the hHCSDegradation model.

Parameters used in the model can be accessed through the HCSDegradation parameter set in the parameter file. Since this model describes interface trap generation, these parameters will only be recognized if they are part of a MaterialInterface or RegionInterface specification. Table 119 lists the default parameter values for siliconoxide interfaces.

