\section*{Activated Barrier Double Well Thermionic Model}

One contribution to the overall threshold voltage shift during and after negative bias temperature instability (NBTI) or positive bias temperature instability (PBTI) is due to hole or electron trapping and detrapping from process-dependent preexisting traps in the gate insulator. This effect can be described with the activated barrier double well thermionic (ABDWT) model [19].

\section*{Model Description}

The ABDWT model considers two energy levels \(E_{1}\) and \(E_{2}\) that are separated by a barrier \(E_{\mathrm{B}}\). The barrier \(E_{\mathrm{B}}\) is thermally activated and lowers by \(\Delta=\gamma E_{\text {ins }}\) with applied bias, while the energy level \(E_{2}\) lowers by \(m \Delta=m \gamma E_{\text {ins }}\) with the fit factors \(\gamma\) and \(m\), and the insulator electric field \(E_{\text {ins }}\).

The ABDWT model considers a special trap having two internal states:
- \(\quad s_{1}\) : Uncharged state at \(E_{1}\)
- \(\quad s_{2}\) : Charged state at \(E_{2}\)

The ABDWT model treats the two energy levels as being connected thermally overcoming an activation energy. In real devices, traps are also located in the bulk of the gate insulator where carriers can be captured and emitted additionally through tunneling processes. The ABDWT model is an effective model, meaning that both connecting processes are considered in an effective manner by fit factors and distributions for \(E_{\mathrm{B}}\) and \(E_{2}\).

[Page 661 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Activated Barrier Double Well Thermionic Model

The barrier energy \(E_{\mathrm{B}}\) is distributed according to a Gaussian distribution where a temperature dependence is introduced for the mean energy barrier \(\left\langle E_{\mathrm{B}}\right\rangle(T)\) and its variance \(\sigma_{E_{\mathrm{B}}}(T)\) according to:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\left\langle E_{\mathrm{B}}\right\rangle(T) & =\left\langle E_{\mathrm{B} 0}\right\rangle \cdot e^{-\frac{E_{A}}{k T}} \\
\sigma_{E_{\mathrm{B}}}(T) & =\sigma_{E_{\mathrm{B} 0}} \cdot e^{-\frac{E_{A}}{k T}}
\end{aligned}
\]
with the mean energy barrier \(\left\langle E_{\mathrm{B} 0}\right\rangle\), the variance \(\sigma_{E_{\mathrm{B} 0}}\), and the activation energy \(E_{A}\).
The energy level \(E_{2}\) is distributed according to a Gaussian distribution with the mean energy level \(\left\langle E_{2}\right\rangle\) and its variance \(\sigma_{E_{2}}\).
The rate equations are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \dot{s}_{1}=-s_{1} k_{12}+s_{2} k_{21} \\
& \dot{s}_{2}=s_{1} k_{12}-s_{2} k_{21}
\end{aligned}
\]
where the state occupation probability satisfies the normalization condition \(s_{1}+s_{2}=1\). The rate constants for the forward and backward transitions are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{12}=v \cdot e^{-\frac{E_{\mathrm{B}}-E_{1}-\gamma E_{\mathrm{ins}}}{k T}} \\
& k_{21}=v \cdot e^{-\frac{E_{\mathrm{B}}-\left(E_{2}-m \gamma E_{\mathrm{ins}}\right)-\gamma E_{\mathrm{ins}}}{k T}}
\end{aligned}
\]
with the attempt rate \(v\) and the reference energy level of the uncharged state \(E_{1}\).

\section*{Using the ABDWT Model}

You activate the ABDWT model by specifying the ABDWT command in the interface-specific Physics section of the command file. For example:
```
Physics ( MaterialInterface = "Silicon/Oxide" ) {
    ABDWT (
        Conc = 5.0e18 # N_0 in insulator [1/ cm^3]
        NumberOfSamples = 100
    )
}
```

where Conc sets the insulator trap concentration and NumberOfSamples sets the number of random samples. Sentaurus Device generates random configurations for each interface vertex.

[Page 662 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Activated Barrier Double Well Thermionic Model

Then, the interface states are obtained per interface vertex \(v\) from the ensemble average according to:
\[
\left\langle s_{2}\right\rangle=\frac{1}{N_{\text {sample }}} \sum_{j=0}^{N_{\text {sample }}} s_{2, j}^{v}
\]

During a transient simulation, state occupations change following the kinetic equations, which change the interface ABDWT states \(s_{1}\) and \(s_{2}\). It is assumed that the uncharged state \(s_{1}\) is fully occupied at the beginning of the time evolution.

You can plot the resulting position-dependent interface-specific quantities as follows:
```
Plot {
    InterfaceABDWTState1 # uncharged state 1
    InterfaceABDWTState2 # charged state 2
}
```


For a more realistic handling of electrostatics, ABDWT charges are distributed into the insulator bulk.

For this purpose, Sentaurus Device searches for all ABDWT-activated interfaces that are connected to the same insulator and computes the interface-averaged ABDWT state density \(\left\langle s_{2}\right\rangle\), which is used for the allocation of the ABDWT charge density inside the insulator volume according to:
\[
q_{\mathrm{ABDWT}}=N_{0}\left\langle s_{2}\right\rangle
\]

You can plot the resulting ABDWT charge density as follows:
```
Plot {
    ABDWTCharge # cm^-3
}
```


\section*{Note:}

ABDWT charges are considered only in the Poisson equation.
The model parameters are defined in the interface-specific ABDWT parameter set (see Table 120). For example:
```
ABDWT {
    nu = 1.4e14
    gamma = 5.0e-9
    m = 2.0
    EBMean = 1.3
    EA = 0.02
    EBSpread = 0.2
    E2Mean = 0.2
    E2Spread = 0.07
}
```

