Carrier Generation by Alpha Particles

\section*{Using the Alpha Particle Model}

The generation rate caused by an alpha particle with energy \(E\) is computed by [2]:
\[
G(u, v, w, t)=\frac{a}{\sqrt{2 \pi} \cdot s} \exp \left[-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{t-t_{\mathrm{m}}}{s}\right)^{2}-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{v^{2}+w^{2}}{w_{\mathrm{t}}^{2}}\right)\right]\left[c_{1} e^{\alpha u}+c_{2} \exp \left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{u-\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}}\right)^{2}\right)\right]
\]
if \(u<\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{3}\), and by:
\[
G(u, v, w, t)=0
\]
if \(u \geq \alpha_{1}+\alpha_{3}\). In this case, \(u\) is the coordinate along the particle path, and \(v\) and \(w\) are coordinates orthogonal to \(u\). The direction and place of incidence are defined in the Physics section of the command file with the keywords Direction and Location (or StartPoint, see Note on page 803), respectively. The \(t_{\mathrm{m}}\) parameter is the time of the generation peak defined by the keyword Time. A Gaussian time dependence can also be used to simulate the typical generation due to pulsed laser or electron beams.

The maximum of the Bragg peak, \(\alpha_{1}\), is fitted to data [3] by a polynomial function:
\[
\alpha_{1}=a_{0}+a_{1} E+a_{2} E^{2}
\]

The parameter \(c_{1}\) is given by:
\[
c_{1}=\exp \left[\alpha\left(\alpha_{1}[10 \mathrm{MeV}]-\alpha_{1}[E]\right)\right]
\]

The scaling factor \(a\) is determined from:
\[
\int_{0}^{\infty} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} G(u, v, w, t) d t d w d v d u=\frac{E}{E_{\mathrm{p}}}
\]
where \(E_{\mathrm{p}}\) is the average energy needed to create an electron-hole pair. The remaining parameters are listed in Table 140. They are available in the parameter set AlphaParticle and are valid for alpha particles with energies between 1 MeV and 10 MeV .

