Carrier Generation by Heavy lons

\section*{Note:}

User-defined heavy ions do not have default parameters. Therefore, in the parameter file, a specification of the following form must appear (see Table 142 on page 803):
```
HeavyIon(<IonName>) (...)
```


Table 288 on page 1719 describes the options for Heavyion. The generation rate by the heavy ion is generally used in transient simulations. The number of electron-hole pairs generated before the initial time of the transient is added to the carrier densities at the beginning of the simulation. The total charge density and the instant generation rate are plotted using HeavyIonChargeDensity and HeavyIonGeneration in the Plot section, respectively.

If the value of \(\mathrm{Wt} \_\mathrm{hi}\) is 0 , then uniform generation is selected. If the value of \(\mathrm{LET} \_\mathrm{f}\) is 0 , then the keyword LET_f can be ignored.

\section*{Using the Heavy Ion Model}

Figure 47 shows a simple model for the heavy ion impinging process.

\begin{figure}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Figure 47 A heavy ion penetrating a semiconductor; its track is defined by a length and the transverse spatial influence is assumed to be symmetric about the track axis}
\includegraphics[alt={},max width=\textwidth]{https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/f7af57de-59b5-428e-a177-d4f23fc59969-560.jpg?height=355&width=727&top_left_y=1392&top_left_x=485}
\end{figure}

The generation rate caused by the heavy ion is computed by:
\[
G(l, w, t)=G_{\mathrm{LET}}(l) R(w, l) T(t)
\]
if \(l<l_{\text {max }}\) ( \(l_{\text {max }}\) is the length of the track), and by:
\[
G(l, w, t)=0
\]
if \(l \geq l_{\text {max }} \cdot R(w)\) and \(T(t)\) are functions describing the spatial and temporal variations of the generation rate. \(G_{\mathrm{LET}}(l)\) is the LET generation density and its unit is pairs \(/ \mathrm{cm}^{3}\).

[Page 801 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Carrier Generation by Heavy lons

\(T(t)\) is defined as a Gaussian function:
\[
T(t)=\frac{2 \cdot \exp \left(-\left(\frac{t-t_{0}}{\sqrt{2} \cdot s_{\mathrm{hi}}}\right)^{2}\right)}{\sqrt{2} \cdot s_{\mathrm{hi}} \sqrt{\pi}\left(1+\operatorname{erf}\left(\frac{t_{0}}{\sqrt{2} \cdot s_{\mathrm{hi}}}\right)\right)}
\]
where \(t_{0}\) is the moment of the heavy ion penetration (see the keyword Time in Table 288 on page 1719), and \(s_{\mathrm{hi}}\) is the characteristic value of the Gaussian (see s_hi in Table 142 on page 803).

The spatial distribution, \(R(w, l)\), can be defined as either an exponential function (default):
\[
R(w, l)=\exp \left(-\frac{w}{w_{\mathrm{t}}(l)}\right)
\]
or a Gaussian function:
\[
R(w, l)=\exp \left(-\left(\frac{w}{w_{\mathrm{t}}(l)}\right)^{2}\right)
\]
where \(w\) is a radius defined as the perpendicular distance from the track. The characteristic distance \(w_{\mathrm{t}}\) is defined as wt_hi in the HeavyIon statement and can be a function of the length \(l\) (see Table 288).

In addition, the spatial distribution \(R(w, l)\) can be defined as a PMI function (see Heavy Ion Spatial Distribution on page 1497).

The LET generation density, \(G_{\mathrm{LET}}(l)\), is given by:
\[
G_{\mathrm{LET}}(l)=a_{1}+a_{2} l+a_{3} \mathrm{e}^{a_{4} l}+k^{\prime}\left[c_{1}\left(c_{2}+c_{3} l\right)^{c_{4}}+\text { LET_f }(l)\right]
\]
where LET_f( \(l\) ) (defined by the keyword LET_f) is a function of the length \(l\). Example 2 on page 804 illustrates how to use an array of values to specify the length dependence of LET_f(l). A linear interpolation is used for values between the array entries of LET_f.
There are two options for the units of \(\mathrm{LET} \_\mathrm{f}\) : pairs \(/ \mathrm{cm}^{3}\) (default) or \(\mathrm{pC} / \mu \mathrm{m}\) (activated by the keyword PicoCoulomb). Depending on the units chosen, \(k^{\prime}\) takes on different values in order to make Equation 803 dimensionally consistent. Table 141 summarizes the appropriate values of \(k^{\prime}\) for different device dimensions.

Exercise care when choosing the correct units for wt_hi and Length. The default unit of Wt_hi and Length is centimeter. If you specify PicoCoulomb, then the unit becomes \(\mu \mathrm{m}\). For examples illustrating the correct unit use, see Examples: Heavy lons on page 804.

Table 142 lists the other coefficients used in Equation 803 with their default values, and they can be adjusted in the parameter file of Sentaurus Device.

[Page 802 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


