\section*{Visualizing Nonlocal Tunneling}

To visualize nonlocal tunneling, specify the keyword eBarrierTunneling or hBarrierTunneling in the Plot section (see Device Plots on page 187). The quantities plotted are in units of \(\mathrm{cm}^{-3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\) and represent the rate at which electrons and holes are generated or disappear due to tunneling. To plot the Peltier heat generated in the conduction band and valence band due to nonlocal tunneling, specify eNLLTunnelingPeltierHeat and hNLLTunnelingPeltierHeat. The Peltier heat is plotted in units of \(\mathrm{Wcm}^{-3}\) and is available regardless of whether it is accounted for in the temperature equation.

The rates are plotted vertexwise and are averaged over the semiconductor volume controlled by a vertex. Therefore, they depend on the mesh spacing. This dependence can become particularly strong at interfaces where the band edges change abruptly.

\section*{Physics of Nonlocal Tunneling Model}

The nonlocal tunneling model in Sentaurus Device is based on the approach presented in the literature [2], but provides significant enhancements over the model presented there.

\section*{WKB Tunneling Probability}

The computation of the tunneling probabilities \(\Gamma_{\mathrm{C}, \mathrm{v}}\) (for carriers tunneling to the \(\nu\)-th shifted conduction band at the interface or contact) and \(\Gamma_{\mathrm{V}, v}\) (for tunneling to the \(v\)-th shifted valence band) is, by default, based on the WKB approximation.

The WKB approximation uses the local (imaginary) wave numbers of particles at position \(r\) and with energy \(\varepsilon\) :
\[
\begin{aligned}
\kappa_{\mathrm{C}, v}(r, \varepsilon) & =\sqrt{2 m_{\mathrm{C}}(r)\left|E_{\mathrm{C}, v}(r)-\varepsilon\right|} \Theta\left[E_{\mathrm{C}, v}(r)-\varepsilon\right] / \hbar \\
\kappa_{\mathrm{V}, v}(r, \varepsilon) & =\sqrt{2 m_{\mathrm{V}}(r)\left|\varepsilon-E_{\mathrm{V}, v}(r)\right|} \Theta\left[\varepsilon-E_{\mathrm{V}, v}(r)\right] / \hbar
\end{aligned}
\]

Here, \(m_{\mathrm{C}}\) is the conduction-band tunneling mass and \(m_{\mathrm{V}}\) is the valence-band tunneling mass.

Both tunneling masses are adjustable parameters (see Nonlocal Tunneling Parameters on page 855 ). \(E_{\mathrm{C}, v}\) and \(E_{\mathrm{V}, v}\) are the conduction and valence bands energies shifted by the \(v\)-th value in eoffset and hoffset (see Nonlocal Tunneling Parameters on page 855).

[Page 858 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Nonlocal Tunneling at Interfaces, Contacts, and Junctions

Using the local wave numbers and the interface transmission coefficients \(T_{\mathrm{CC}, v}\) and \(T_{\mathrm{VV}, v}\), the tunneling probability between positions \(l\) and \(u>l\) for a particle with energy \(\varepsilon\) can be written as:
\[
\Gamma_{\mathrm{CC}, v}(u, l, \varepsilon)=T_{\mathrm{CC}, v}(l, \varepsilon) \exp \left(-2 \int_{l}^{u} \kappa_{\mathrm{C}, v}(r, \varepsilon) d r\right) T_{\mathrm{CC}, v}(u, \varepsilon)
\]
and:
\[
\Gamma_{\mathrm{VV}, v}(u, l, \varepsilon)=T_{\mathrm{VV}, v}(l, \varepsilon) \exp \left(-2 \int_{l}^{u} \kappa_{\mathrm{V}, v}(r, \varepsilon) d r\right) T_{\mathrm{VV}, v}(u, \varepsilon)
\]

If the option TwoBand is specified to eBarrierTunneling (see Table 247 on page 1685), Sentaurus Device replaces \(\kappa_{C, v}\) in Equation 838 with the two-band dispersion relation:
\[
\kappa_{v}=\frac{\kappa_{C, v} \kappa_{V, v}}{\sqrt{\kappa_{C, v}^{2}+\kappa_{V, v}^{2}}}
\]

If the option TwoBand is specified to hBarrierTunneling, Sentaurus Device replaces \(\kappa_{\mathrm{V}, v}\) in Equation 839 with the two-band relation Equation 840. Near the conduction and the valence band edge, the two-band dispersion relation approaches the single band dispersion relations Equation 836 and Equation 837, and provides a smooth interpolation in between. Figure 49 illustrates this.

The two-band dispersion relation does not distinguish between electrons and holes. In particular, for the two-band dispersion relation, \(\Gamma_{\mathrm{CC}, \mathrm{v}}=\Gamma_{\mathrm{VV}, \mathrm{v}}\).

\begin{figure}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Figure 49 Comparison of two-band and single-band dispersion relations}
\includegraphics[alt={},max width=\textwidth]{https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/f7af57de-59b5-428e-a177-d4f23fc59969-618.jpg?height=660&width=824&top_left_y=1607&top_left_x=489}
\end{figure}

[Page 859 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Nonlocal Tunneling at Interfaces, Contacts, and Junctions

The two-band dispersion relation is most useful when band-to-band tunneling is active (keyword Band2Band, see Table 247 on page 1685). However, the two-band dispersion relation can be used independently from band-to-band tunneling.

By default, the interface transmission coefficients \(T_{\mathrm{CC}, v}\) and \(T_{\mathrm{VV}, v}\) in Equation 838 and Equation 839 equal one. If the Transmission option is specified to eBarrierTunneling [3]:
\[
T_{\mathrm{CC}, \mathrm{v}}(x, \varepsilon)=\frac{v_{-, \mathrm{v}}(x, \varepsilon) \sqrt{v_{-, \mathrm{v}}(x, \varepsilon)^{2}+16 v_{+, \mathrm{v}}(x, \varepsilon)^{2}}}{v_{+, \mathrm{v}}(x, \varepsilon)^{2}+v_{-, \mathrm{v}}(x, \varepsilon)^{2}}
\]

Here, \(v_{-, v}(x, \varepsilon)\) denotes the velocity of a particle with energy \(\varepsilon\) on the side of the interface or contact at position \(x\) where the particle moves freely in the conduction band, and \(v_{+, v}(x, \varepsilon)\) denotes the imaginary velocity on the side of the tunneling barrier (where the particle is in the gap). If the particle is free or in the barrier on both sides, \(T_{\mathrm{CC}, \mathrm{v}}(x, \varepsilon)=1\). Velocities are the derivatives of the particle energy with respect to the wave number, \(v_{v}=\left|\partial \varepsilon / \partial \hbar \kappa_{\mathrm{C}, v}\right|\). With the TwoBand option, \(v_{+, v}=\left|\partial \varepsilon / \partial \hbar \kappa_{v}\right|\) [4] (see Equation 840). If the Transmission option is specified to hBarrierTunneling, analogous expressions hold for \(T_{\mathrm{VV}, v}\).

By default, the band-to-band tunneling probabilities \(\Gamma_{\mathrm{CV}, v}\) and \(\Gamma_{\mathrm{VC}, v}\) are also given by the expressions Equation 838 and Equation 839, respectively. When the TwoBand and Transmission options are specified for eBarrierTunneling to compute \(\Gamma_{\mathrm{CV}}, v, v_{-, v}\) in the expression for \(T_{\mathrm{CC}, \mathrm{v}}(r, \varepsilon)\) (see Equation 841) is the velocity of the particle in the valence band and is computed from valence-band parameters. The converse holds for \(\Gamma_{\mathrm{VC}, \mathrm{v}}\) when those options are specified for hBarrierTunneling.

For metals and contacts, the band-edge energy to compute the interface transmission coefficients is obtained from the FermiEnergy parameter of the BandGap section for the metal or contact. The masses used to compute the velocities are the tunneling effective masses for the metal or contact.

\section*{Note:}

The default contact material is polysilicon, that is, a semiconductor with a band gap. The conduction band edge of the contact might be energetically close to the valence band of the device semiconductor. If you use eBarrierTunneling with the option Band2Band, then a negative differential tunneling current might occur. See Chapter 10 on page 273 to change the contact properties, for example, to use metal contacts.

For metals and contacts when the BarrierLowering option is specified for BarrierTunneling, the band edges are corrected by a position-dependent lowering potential given by:
\[
\Delta \Phi_{\mathrm{B}}(r)=\min \left(\frac{A q}{16 \pi \varepsilon r}, \mathrm{BL} \_\max \right)
\]

[Page 860 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


where \(\varepsilon\) is the material dielectric constant, \(r\) is the distance from the interface or contact, and \(A\) is a dimensionless fitting parameter. Because Equation 842 has a singularity for \(r \rightarrow 0\), Sentaurus Device limits \(r\) by imposing a minimum value. You can set the minimum value for \(r\) by specifying a maximum value for \(\Delta \Phi_{\mathrm{B}}(r)\) using the parameter BL_max (see Nonlocal Tunneling Parameters on page 855). BL_max must be positive.

The regionwise barrier-lowering fitting factor \(A\) can be specified by the A parameter (default is 1 ):
```
Material = "Silicon" {
    BarrierTunneling {
        A = 1.02 , 1.0
    }
}
```


The barrier-lowering parameter BL_max allows you to adjust the maximum of the barrier lowering (corresponding to the minimum-allowed distance to the contact or interface). Its default value is 0.3 eV .

When the BarrierLowering model is defined, the effective band edge is typically lower than the original band edge. For the energy range between the lowered band edge and the original band edge, a thermionic emission-like current is calculated with transmission equal to 1.

To better resolve the lowering potential, an adaptive nonlocal mesh is generated when the BarrierLowering model is activated in tunneling. You can control the adaptive mesh by using the following syntax:
```
Math { NonLocal "NLM" (RefinedIntervals=1e-8) }
```


A smaller RefinedIntervals gives a finer mesh. It corresponds to the position-dependent lowering potential defined in Equation 842. Its default value is 1, which produces the same results as previous releases. To have a better refinement, RefinedIntervals \(=1 e-8\) is suggested, corresponding to \(\mathrm{A}=1\) and \(\mathrm{BL} \_\max =0.3 \mathrm{eV}\). With a smaller A or larger \(\mathrm{BL} \_\)max, the value of RefinedIntervals must be smaller.

\section*{Note:}

This feature is available only for the BarrierLowering model. If the BarrierLowering model is not specified, this feature is not activated.

To visualize the BarrierLowering model and the modified band edges, you can specify the following in the NonLocalPlot section:
```
NonLocalPlot((0 0)) {
    CBBarrierLowering VBBarrierLowering
    CBEnergywithLowering VBEnergywithLowering
}
```

[Page 861 END]
