\section*{Band-to-Band Contributions to Nonlocal Tunneling Current}

When you specify the Band2Band option to eBarrierTunneling (see Table 247 on page 1685), the total current that flows to the conduction band at point \(l\) also contains electrons that originate from the valence band at position \(u>l\).

For Band2Band=Simple, the recombination rate of the valence-band electrons with energy \(\varepsilon\) at point \(u\) (in other words, the generation rate of holes at \(u\) ) due to tunneling to or from the \(v\)-th shifted conduction band at \(l\) is:
\[
\begin{aligned}
R_{\mathrm{CV}, \mathrm{v}}(u, l, \varepsilon)- & G_{\mathrm{CV}, \mathrm{v}}(u, l, \varepsilon)=\frac{A_{\mathrm{CV}}}{2 q k} \vartheta\left[\varepsilon-E_{\mathrm{V}, \mathrm{v}}(u), \frac{d E_{\mathrm{V}, \mathrm{v}}}{d u}(u)\right] \vartheta\left[\varepsilon-E_{\mathrm{C}, \mathrm{v}}(l), \frac{d E_{\mathrm{C}, \mathrm{v}}}{d l}(l)\right] \Gamma_{\mathrm{CV}, \mathrm{v}}(u, l, \varepsilon) \\
& \times\left[T_{p}(u)+T_{n}(l)\right]\left[\left(1+\exp \left[\frac{\varepsilon-E_{\mathrm{F}, p}(u)}{k T_{p}(u)}\right]\right)^{-1}-\left(1+\exp \left[\frac{\varepsilon-E_{\mathrm{F}, n}(l)}{k T_{n}(l)}\right]\right)^{-1}\right]
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(A_{\mathrm{CV}}=\sqrt{g_{\mathrm{C}} g_{\mathrm{V}}} A_{0}\). The prefactor \(g_{\mathrm{V}}\) is a fit parameter, see Nonlocal Tunneling Parameters on page \(855 . \Gamma_{\mathrm{CV}, v}\) is the band-to-band tunneling probability discussed above. The modifications for zero Permeation, contacts, metals, and the BandGap option are as for Equation 845.

[Page 866 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Nonlocal Tunneling at Interfaces, Contacts, and Junctions

The current density of electrons that tunnel from the valence band at points above \(l\) to the conduction band at point \(l\) is the integral over the recombination rate (Equation 848):
\[
\frac{d j_{\mathrm{CV}}}{d l}(l)=-q \sum_{v} \int_{l-\infty}^{\infty} \int_{\mathrm{CV}, v}^{\infty}\left[(r, l, \varepsilon)-G_{\mathrm{CV}, v}(r, l, \varepsilon)\right] d \varepsilon d r
\]

For band-to-band tunneling processes, the energy of the tunneling particles often lies deep in the gap of the barrier. The single-band dispersion relations that Sentaurus Device uses by default (see Equation 836 and Equation 837) are based on the band structure near the band edges, and might not be useful in this regime. The two-band dispersion relation according Equation 840 is a better choice. To use the two-band dispersion relation, specify the option TwoBand to eBarrierTunneling (see Table 247 on page 1685).

The options for hBarrierTunneling and the expressions for the conduction band to valence band tunneling current density \(j_{\text {VC }}\) are analogous.

\section*{Carrier Heating}

In hydrodynamic simulations, carrier transport leads to energy transport and, therefore, to heating or cooling of electrons and holes. The energy transport has a convective and a Peltier part. By default, Sentaurus Device ignores the Peltier part. To include the Peltier terms for the tunneling particles, specify the option PeltierHeat to eBarrierTunneling or hBarrierTunneling (see Table 247 on page 1685).

The convective part of the heat generation in the conduction and valence bands at position \(u\) due to tunneling of carriers with energy \(\varepsilon\) to and from the \(v\)-th shifted conduction band at \(l<u\) is approximated as:
\[
H_{\mathrm{conv}, \mathrm{CC}, v}(u, l, \varepsilon)=\frac{\delta}{2}\left[G_{\mathrm{CC}, v}(u) k T_{n}(l)-R_{\mathrm{CC}, v}(u) k T_{n}(u)\right]
\]
and:
\[
H_{\mathrm{conv}, \mathrm{CV}, v}(u, l, \varepsilon)=\frac{\delta}{2}\left[R_{\mathrm{CV}, v}(u) k T_{p}(u)-G_{\mathrm{CV}, v}(u) k T_{n}(l)\right]
\]

By default, Sentaurus Device neglects Peltier heating and uses \(\delta=3\), which corresponds to the three degrees of freedom of the carriers. If Peltier heating is included in a simulation, the convective contribution due to one degree of freedom is already contained in the Peltier heating term. Therefore, in this case, Sentaurus Device uses \(\delta=2\). The convective parts of the heat generation in the conduction band at \(l\), due to tunneling of carriers of energy \(\varepsilon\) from the conduction band and the valence band at \(u>l\), are \(-H_{\text {conv }, \mathrm{CC}, v}(u, l, \varepsilon)\) and \(-H_{\text {conv }, \mathrm{CV}, v}(u, l, \varepsilon)\).

The expressions for the convective part of the heat generation in the valence band are analogous.

If the computation of Peltier heating is activated (see Table 247 on page 1685), Sentaurus Device computes additional heating terms. The Peltier part of the heat generation in the

