Overview of Hot-Carrier Injection Models

DynamicBarrierHeight supports only electrons, so its supported HCl model options are Fiegna, eFiegna, Lucky, and eLucky. For example:

GateCurrent (eLucky(DynamicBarrierHeight))
The insulator field \(F_{\text {ins }}\) is defined as:
\[
F_{\text {ins }}=\vec{F}_{\text {ins }} \cdot \hat{n}\left[1-P_{\text {total }}+P_{\text {total }} \frac{\left|\vec{F}_{\text {ins }}\right|}{\left|\vec{F}_{\text {ins }} \cdot \hat{n}\right|}\right]
\]
where \(\hat{n}\) is a normal vector along the direction of hot-carrier injection, and \(P_{\text {total }}\) is a model parameter ( \(P_{\text {total }}=0\) by default).

In addition, all hot-carrier models contain a probability \(P_{\text {ins }}\) of scattering in the image-force potential well:
\[
P_{\text {ins }}= \begin{cases}\exp \left(-\frac{x_{0}}{\lambda_{\text {ins }}}\right) & F_{\text {ins }}<0 \\ \exp \left(-\frac{t_{\text {ins }}-x_{0}}{\lambda_{\text {ins }}}\right) P_{\text {repel }} & F_{\text {ins }}>0\end{cases}
\]
where \(\lambda_{\text {ins }}\) is the scattering mean free path in the insulator, \(t_{\text {ins }}\) is the distance between the vertex at the hot interface and the closest associated vertex, \(P_{\text {repel }}\) is a model parameter ( \(P_{\text {repel }}=1\) by default), and the distance \(x_{0}\) is given as:
\[
x_{0}=\min \left(\sqrt{\frac{q}{16 \pi \tilde{\varepsilon}_{\mathrm{ins}}\left|F_{\mathrm{ins}}\right|}}, \frac{t_{\mathrm{ins}}}{2}\right)
\]

In this expression, \(\tilde{\varepsilon}_{\text {ins }}=\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}\left(\varepsilon_{\text {sem }}+\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}\right) /\left(\varepsilon_{\text {sem }}-\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}\right)\) is the effective dielectric constant of the insulator where \(\varepsilon_{\text {sem }}\) and \(\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}\) are the high-frequency dielectric constant of the semiconductor and insulator, respectively. In the lucky electron model and Fiegna model, \(\tilde{\varepsilon}_{\text {ins }}\) is directly accessible from the parameter file. In the SHE distribution model, \(\varepsilon_{\text {sem }}\) and \(\varepsilon_{\text {ins }}\) are separately set from the parameter file.

\section*{Effective Field}

The lucky electron model and Fiegna model have an effective electric field \(F_{\text {eff }}\) as a parameter. In Sentaurus Device, there are three possibilities to calculate the effective field:
- With the electric field parallel to the carrier flow (switched on by the keyword Eparallel, which is default for hot carrier currents). See Driving Force on page 528.
- With recomputation of the carrier temperature of the hydrodynamic simulation (switched on by the keyword CarrierTempDrive). See Avalanche Generation With Hydrodynamic Transport on page 529.

[Page 874 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Classical Lucky Electron Injection
- With a simplified approach (compared to the second method): The drift-diffusion model is used for the device simulation, and carrier temperature is estimated as the solution of the simplified and linearized energy balance equation. As this is a postprocessing calculation, the keyword CarrierTemppost activates this option.

These keywords are parameters of the model keywords. For example, the lucky electron model looks like eLucky (CarrierTempDrive). However, you must remember that, if the model includes the keyword CarrierTempDrive, then Hydro and a carrier temperature calculation must be specified in the Physics section.

\section*{Classical Lucky Electron Injection}

The classical total lucky electron current from an interface to a gate contact can be written as [1]:
\[
I_{\mathrm{g}}=\iint J_{n}(x, y) P_{\mathrm{s}} P_{\text {ins }}\left(\int_{E_{\mathrm{B}}}^{\infty} P_{\varepsilon} P_{\mathrm{r}} d \varepsilon\right) d x d y
\]
where \(P_{\mathrm{s}}\) is the probability that the electron will travel a distance \(y\) to the interface without losing any energy, \(P_{\varepsilon} d \varepsilon\) is the probability that the electron has energy between \(\varepsilon\) and \(\varepsilon+d \varepsilon, P_{\text {ins }}\) is the probability of scattering in the image force potential well (Equation 857), and \(P_{\mathrm{r}}\) is the probability that the electron will be redirected. These probabilities are given by the expressions:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& P_{\mathrm{r}}(\varepsilon)=\frac{1}{2 \lambda_{\mathrm{r}}}\left(1-\sqrt{\frac{E_{\mathrm{B}}}{\varepsilon}}\right) \\
& P_{\mathrm{s}}(y)=\exp \left(-\frac{y}{\lambda}\right) \\
& P_{\varepsilon}(\varepsilon)=\frac{1}{\lambda F_{\mathrm{eff}}} \exp \left(-\frac{\varepsilon}{\lambda F_{\mathrm{eff}}}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(\lambda\) is the scattering mean free path in the semiconductor.
- \(\lambda_{\mathrm{r}}\) is redirection mean free path.
- \(F_{\text {eff }}\) is the effective electric field (see Effective Field on page 874).
- \(E_{\mathrm{B}}\) is the height of the semiconductor-insulator barrier.

The model coefficients can be changed in the parameter file in the section:
```
LuckyModel { ... }
```

