\section*{Fiegna Hot-Carrier Injection}

The total hot-carrier injection current according to the Fiegna model [2] can be written as:
\[
I_{\mathrm{g}}=q \int P_{\mathrm{ins}}\left(\int_{E_{\mathrm{B} 0}}^{\infty} v_{\perp}(\varepsilon) f(\varepsilon) g(\varepsilon) d \varepsilon\right) d s
\]
where:
- \(\varepsilon\) is the electron energy.
- \(E_{\mathrm{B} 0}\) is the height of the semiconductor-insulator barrier.

[Page 876 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Fiegna Hot-Carrier Injection
- \(v_{\perp}\) is the velocity normal to the interface.
- \(f(\varepsilon)\) is the electron energy distribution.
- \(g(\varepsilon)\) is the density-of-states of the electrons.
- \(P_{\text {ins }}\) is the probability of scattering in the image force potential well as described by Equation 857.
- \(\int d s\) is an integral along the semiconductor-insulator interface.

The following expression for the electron energy distribution was proposed for a parabolic and an isotropic band structure, and equilibrium between lattice and electrons:
\[
f(\varepsilon)=A \exp \left(-\chi \frac{\varepsilon^{3}}{F_{\mathrm{eff}}^{1.5}}\right)
\]

Therefore, the gate current can be rewritten as:
\[
I_{\mathrm{g}}=q \frac{A}{3 \chi} \int P_{\mathrm{ins}} n \frac{F_{\mathrm{eff}}^{3 / 2}}{\sqrt{E_{\mathrm{B}}}} e^{-\frac{\chi E_{\mathrm{B}}^{3}}{F_{\mathrm{eff}}^{3 / 2}}} d s
\]
where \(F_{\text {eff }}\) is an effective field (see Effective Field on page 874).

