Gaussian Transport Across Organic Heterointerfaces

\section*{Note:}

Always specify Formula \(=1\) when Fermi statistics is used. If Fermi statistics is not used, Equation 902-Equation 911 will be activated regardless of the Formula statement in the parameter file.

\section*{Gaussian Transport Across Organic Heterointerfaces}

A thermionic-like current boundary condition has been introduced to correctly account for carrier transport across organic heterointerfaces. An organic heterointerface is defined in this context as an heterointerface with the Gaussian density-of-states (DOS) model (see Gaussian Density-of-States for Organic Semiconductors on page 337) activated in both regions that are adjacent to the heterointerface.

\section*{Using Gaussian Transport at Organic Heterointerfaces}

The model is activated by switching to the Gaussian DOS model in both regions of the heterointerface that are meant to be organic:
```
Physics(Region="OrganicRegion_1") {
    EffectiveMass(GaussianDOS)
}
Physics(Region="OrganicRegion_2") {
    EffectiveMass(GaussianDOS)
}
```

and then specifying the keyword Organic_Gaussian as an option for the Thermionic model in the Physics section of the organic heterointerface:
```
Physics(RegionInterface="OrganicRegion_1/OrganicRegion_2") {
    Thermionic(Organic_Gaussian)
}
```


This syntax also automatically switches on the double points at the organic heterointerface.
You can adjust the parameters \(v_{n, \text { org }}\) and \(v_{p, \text { org }}\) in Equation 923 and Equation 925 in the ThermionicEmission section of the parameter file (their default values are \(1 \times 10^{6} \mathrm{~cm} / \mathrm{s}\) ):
```
RegionInterface="OrganicRegion_1/OrganicRegion_2" {
    ThermionicEmission {
        vel_org = 1e7, 1e7 # [cm/s]
    }
}
```

[Page 899 END]
