\section*{Anisotropic Properties}

This chapter discusses the anisotropic properties of semiconductor devices.

\section*{Anisotropic Properties of Semiconductor Devices}

In general, all equations for semiconductor devices can be written in the following form:
\[
-\nabla \cdot \vec{J}=R
\]

Here, vector \(\vec{J}=\hat{\mu} \vec{g}\) and the tensor coefficient \(\hat{\mu}=\mu \cdot \hat{A}\), where \(\mu\) is a scalar function, tensor \(\hat{A}\) is a \(3 \times 3\) (or \(2 \times 2\), in two dimensions) symmetric matrix, and vector \(\vec{g}\) is a first-order differential expression.
In the isotropic case, tensor \(\hat{A}\) is the unit matrix. In the common case, tensor \(\hat{A}\) depends on the solution. Among the reasons why tensor \(A\) is a full matrix are the anisotropic properties of semiconductors (such as SiC) and the influence of mechanical stress, which affects anisotropic mobility (see Chapter 31 on page 962).

\begin{table}
\captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
\caption{Table 153 Anisotropic models for the tensor coefficient \(\hat{\mu}\) that Sentaurus Device supports}
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|}
\hline Tensor coefficient & Equation or model \\
\hline Mobility, \(\hat{\mu}\) & Continuity equation for electrons and holes \\
\hline Electrical permittivity, \(\hat{\varepsilon}\) & Poisson equation \\
\hline Thermal conductivity, \(\hat{\kappa}\) & Thermodynamics equation \\
\hline Quantum potential parameter, \(\hat{\alpha}\) & Density gradient model \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Sentaurus Device provides different anisotropic approximations for discretization for the Poisson, continuity, and thermodynamic equations, and for the density gradient model (see Anisotropic Approximations on page 910).

[Page 909 END]
