Anisotropy Definition and Specification

To compute the anisotropic direction relative to the simulation coordinate system ( \(a_{x}, a_{y}, a_{z}\) ) from a direction specified in the crystal coordinate system ( \(c_{x}, c_{y}, c_{z}\) ), the following transformation is used:
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{x} \\
a_{y} \\
a_{z}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\vec{X} \\
\vec{Y} \\
\vec{Z}
\end{array}\right) \cdot\left(\begin{array}{c}
c_{x} \\
c_{y} \\
c_{z}
\end{array}\right)
\]
where \(\vec{X}\) and \(\vec{Y}\) are row vectors as specified in the Lattice Parameters section, and \(\vec{Z}\) is computed automatically to form an orthogonal simulation coordinate system.

The following examples specify the anisotropic direction relative to the crystal coordinate system:
- Case 1: Aniso(direction(CrystalSystem) = ( \(\begin{array}{lll}0 & 0 & 1\end{array}\) ))

As shown in Figure 53, this specification causes the anisotropic direction to lie along the negative \(x\)-direction in the simulation coordinate system, that is, aniso_dir= \(\left(\begin{array}{lll}-1 & 0 & 0\end{array}\right)\). Because this direction lies within the plane of the simulation coordinate system, it is a valid specification of the anisotropic direction.
- Case 2: Aniso(direction(CrystalSystem) = ( \(\left.\begin{array}{lll}0 & 1 & 0\end{array}\right)\) )

As shown in Figure 53, this specification causes the anisotropic direction to lie outside of the 2D simulation coordinate system, that is, aniso_dir= ( \(0,0.5,0.86603\) ). Because this direction does not lie within the 2D simulation coordinate system, it is considered an invalid specification.

\section*{Aniso Subsection Without Direction Definition}

In this case, Sentaurus Device uses only the X and Y vectors to compute aniso_dir=(ax,ay,az). If \(a z=0\), then the definition is correct. Otherwise, the definition is incorrect.

Sentaurus Device interprets the X and Y vectors differently in the following cases:
- Vectors are read from a parameter file (see X and Y Vectors Read From Parameter File on page 917).
- Vectors are read from a TDR file (see X and Y Vectors Read From TDR File (Sentaurus Process) on page 917).

[Page 916 END]
