Anisotropic Mobility

\section*{Orthogonal Matrix From Eigenvectors Q}

Let \(A=(x, y, z)\) be a vector row and let \(\vec{A}=(x, y, z)^{\prime}\) be a vector column.
If the anisotropic direction has the default value ( \(z\)-axis in three dimensions or \(y\)-axis in two dimensions), then the matrix \(Q\) is:
\[
Q=R^{T}, R=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\overrightarrow{\underline{X}} & \vec{Y} & \vec{Z} \\
\|\overrightarrow{\hat{X}}\| & \|\vec{Y}\| & \frac{\vec{Z}}{\| \vec{Z}} \|
\end{array}\right]
\]
where the vector rows \(\mathrm{X}, \mathrm{Y}\), and Z are defined in the LatticeParameters section.
If the anisotropic direction is a vector \(\vec{A}_{d}=(x, y, z)^{\prime}\) in the crystal coordinate system, then the matrix \(Q\) is:
\[
Q=\left[\overrightarrow{\vec{A}_{x}} \overrightarrow{A_{y}} \overrightarrow{A_{z}}\right], \overrightarrow{A_{z}}=R^{T} \cdot \overrightarrow{A_{d}} /\left\|\vec{A}_{d}\right\|
\]

If the anisotropic direction is a vector \(\vec{A}_{d}=(x, y, z)^{\prime}\) in the simulation coordinate system, then the matrix \(Q\) is:
\[
Q=\left[\overrightarrow{\vec{A}_{x}} \overrightarrow{A_{y}} \overrightarrow{A_{z}}\right], \overrightarrow{A_{z}}=\vec{A}_{d} /\left\|\vec{A}_{d}\right\|
\]

Sentaurus Device computes the vectors \(\overrightarrow{\mathrm{A}}_{x}, \overrightarrow{\mathrm{~A}}_{y}\) to ensure that the matrix \(Q\) is orthogonal.

\section*{Anisotropic Mobility}

In some semiconductors, such as silicon carbide, electrons and holes can exhibit different mobilities along different crystallographic axes.

\section*{Anisotropy Factor}

In a 3D simulation, Sentaurus Device assumes that electrons or holes exhibit a mobility \(\mu\) along the \(x\)-axis and \(y\)-axis, and an anisotropic mobility \(\mu_{\text {aniso }}\) along the \(z\)-axis. In a 2D simulation, the regular mobility \(\mu\) is observed along the \(x\)-axis, and \(\mu_{\text {aniso }}\) is observed along the y -axis. The anisotropy factor \(r\) is defined as the ratio:
\[
r=\frac{\mu}{\mu_{\text {aniso }}}
\]

[Page 919 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Anisotropic Mobility

\section*{Current Densities}

In the isotropic case, current densities can be expressed by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{J}_{n}=\mu_{n} \vec{g}_{n} \\
& \vec{J}_{p}=\mu_{p} \vec{g}_{p}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\vec{g}_{n}\) and \(\vec{g}_{p}\) are the currents without mobilities.
In the drift-diffusion model, you have:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{g}_{n}=-n q \nabla \Phi_{n} \\
& \vec{g}_{p}=-p q \nabla \Phi_{p}
\end{aligned}
\]
as can be seen from Equation 62 and Equation 63. For the thermodynamic model, Equation 64 and Equation 65 imply that:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{g}_{n}=-n q\left(\nabla \Phi_{n}+P_{n} \nabla T\right) \\
& \vec{g}_{p}=-p q\left(\nabla \Phi_{p}+P_{p} \nabla T\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

In the hydrodynamic case, you have:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{g}_{n}=n \nabla E_{\mathrm{C}}+k T_{n} \nabla n+f_{n}^{\mathrm{td}} k n \nabla T_{n}-1.5 n k T_{n} \nabla \ln m_{n} \\
& \vec{g}_{p}=p \nabla E_{\mathrm{V}}-k T_{p} \nabla p-f_{p}^{\mathrm{td}} k p \nabla T_{p}-1.5 p k T_{p} \nabla \ln m_{p}
\end{aligned}
\]
according to Equation 66 and Equation 67.
For anisotropic mobilities, Equation 940 and Equation 941 must be rewritten as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{J}_{n}=\mu_{n} A_{r_{n}} \vec{g}_{n} \\
& \vec{J}_{p}=\mu_{p} A_{r_{p}} \vec{g}_{p}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(r_{n}\) and \(r_{p}\) are the anisotropy factors for electrons and holes, respectively. If the crystal coordinate system coincides with the simulation coordinate system of Sentaurus Device, depending on the dimension of the problem, the matrices \(A_{r}\) are given by:
\[
A_{r}=\left[\begin{array}{lll}
1 & & \\
& 1 & \\
& & 1 / r
\end{array}\right] \quad \text { or } \quad \mathrm{A}_{r}=\left[\begin{array}{ll}
1 & \\
& 1 / r
\end{array}\right]
\]

[Page 920 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Anisotropic Mobility

In general, however, \(A_{r}\) must be written as:
\[
A_{r}=Q\left[\begin{array}{lll}
1 & & \\
& 1 & \\
& & 1 / r
\end{array}\right] Q^{\mathrm{T}} \quad \text { or } \quad \mathrm{A}_{r}=Q_{2: 2}\left[\begin{array}{ll}
1 & \\
& 1 / r
\end{array}\right] Q_{2: 2}^{\mathrm{T}}
\]
where \(Q\) is defined in Equation 935-Equation 937.

\section*{Driving Forces}

In the isotropic case, the electric field parallel to the electron or hole current is given by (see Equation 373 on page 468):
\[
F_{c}=\frac{\vec{F} \cdot \vec{J}_{c}}{J_{c}}=\frac{\vec{F} \cdot \vec{g}_{c}}{g_{c}}
\]

For anisotropic mobilities:
\[
F_{c}=\frac{\vec{F} \cdot \overrightarrow{A g}_{c}}{\left|\overrightarrow{A g_{c}}\right|}
\]

Similarly, the electric field perpendicular to the current, as given in Equation 345, must be rewritten as:
\[
F_{c, \perp}=\sqrt{F^{2}-\frac{\left(\vec{F} \cdot \vec{A}_{g}\right)^{2}}{\left|\vec{A} \vec{g}_{c}\right|^{2}}}
\]

Equation 375 shows how the gradient of the Fermi potential \(\Phi_{c}\) can be used as the driving force in high-field saturation models. For this case, Sentaurus Device has two formulas:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& F_{c}=\left|A \nabla \Phi_{c}\right| \quad \text { (default formula) } \\
& F_{c}=\frac{\left(A \nabla \Phi_{c}, \nabla \Phi_{c}\right)}{\left|A \nabla \Phi_{c}\right|} \quad \text { (second formula) }
\end{aligned}
\]

The global Math parameter AnisoGradQF_formula=0 | 1 selects the corresponding formula.
In the isotropic hydrodynamic Canali model, the driving force \(\vec{F}_{c}\) satisfies:
\[
\vec{F}_{c} \cdot \mu \vec{F}_{c}=\frac{w_{c}-w_{0}}{\tau_{\mathrm{e} c} q}
\]
as can be seen from Equation 379. To derive the appropriate expression in the anisotropic case, it is assumed that \(F_{c}\) operates parallel to the current, that is:
\[
\vec{F}_{c}=F_{c} \hat{e}_{c}
\]

[Page 921 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Anisotropic Mobility

where:
\[
\hat{e}_{c}=\frac{A \vec{g}_{c}}{\left|\overrightarrow{A \vec{g}_{c}}\right|}
\]
is the direction of the electron or hole current.
Instead of Equation 957, you now have:
\[
\mu F_{c}^{2}\left(A \hat{e}_{c}\right) \cdot \hat{e}_{c}=\frac{w_{c}-w_{0}}{\tau_{\mathrm{e} c} q}
\]
or:
\[
F_{c}=\sqrt{\frac{w_{c}-w_{0}}{\tau_{\mathrm{e} c} q \mu A \hat{e}_{c} \cdot \hat{e}_{c}}}
\]

\section*{Total Anisotropic Mobility}

This is the simplest mode in Sentaurus Device. Only a total anisotropy factor \(r_{e}\) or \(r_{h}\) is specified in the command file:
```
Physics {
    Aniso(
        eMobilityFactor (Total) = re
        hMobilityFactor (Total) = rh
    )
}
```


Sentaurus Device computes the mobility \(\mu\) for electrons or holes along the main crystallographic axis as usual. The mobility \(\mu_{\text {aniso }}\) is then given by:
\[
\mu_{\text {aniso }}=\frac{\mu}{r}
\]

\section*{Note:}

In this mode, Sentaurus Device does not update the driving forces as discussed in Driving Forces on page 921.

\section*{Self-Consistent Anisotropic Mobility}

This is the most accurate, but also the most expensive, mode in Sentaurus Device. The electron and hole mobility models specified in the Physics section are evaluated separately for the major and minor crystallographic axes, but with different parameters for each axis.

[Page 922 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


This option is activated in the Physics section for electron or hole mobilities as follows:
```
Physics {
    Aniso(
        eMobility
        hMobility
    )
}
```


To simplify matters, you can specify the following option to activate self-consistent, anisotropic, mobility calculations for both electrons and holes:
```
Physics {
    Aniso( Mobility )
}
```


