\section*{Total Anisotropic Metal Resistivity Factor}

This option is similar to Total Anisotropic Mobility on page 922. Sentaurus Device assumes that the metal resistivity \(\rho\) is the same in all directions perpendicular to the anisotropic direction (see Aniso(direction) Versus LatticeParameters on page 918) and is \(\rho_{\text {aniso }}\) along the direction. The anisotropy factor \(r\) is defined as the ratio:
\[
r=\frac{\rho}{\rho_{\text {aniso }}}
\]

To activate this option, specify the metal resistivity anisotropy factor \(r\) in the command file regionwise or globally, as follows:
```
Physics {
    Aniso( MetalResistivityFactor(Total) = r )
}
```


\section*{Self-Consistent Anisotropic Metal Resistivity}

This option works similarly to Self-Consistent Anisotropic Mobility on page 922. To set this option, both the MetalResistivity and MetalResistivity_aniso sections in the parameter file should be used to define the metal resistivity anisotropy and its temperature dependence.

To activate this option, use the following regionwise or global specification in the command file:
```
Physics{
    Aniso( MetalResistivity )
}
```


