\section*{Multivalley Band Structure}

The multivalley model is an alternative that accounts for the carrier population in various valleys presented in the semiconductor band structure where the stress effect is accounted for in each valley separately. Therefore, this model does not require to have effective corrections applied to the conduction and valence band edge-energy and DOS. Based on such detailed consideration of the carrier repopulation between valleys, this model gives a possibility to account for the stress effect in both the carrier density and mobility consistently.

For a general description of the multivalley model and its implementation, see Multivalley Band Structure on page 342. The multivalley model accounts for the stress effect in the band structure by stress-induced change of the energy and effective masses in each valley.

The stress-induced change in the valley energy is described in Deformation of Band Structure on page 967. It is accounted for in both \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) bands [12][13] and arbitrary valleys defined in the parameter file (see Using Multivalley Band Structure on page 346).

The stress-induced change in the valley effective mass is accounted for in the two-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) model [13] for electrons and the \(6 \times 6 \mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) model [12] for holes by a computation of the effective DOS factors \(g_{n, i}, g_{p, i}\) in Equation 198 and Equation 199. The stress-induced change of the effective DOS masses for each valley is described in Strained Effective Masses and Density-of-States on page 972.

Referring to Equation 1025 and Equation 1032, and using their variables, the effective DOS factors of each \(\Delta_{2}\) valley can be expressed as follows if only \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) bands are defined in the multivalley model:
\[
g_{n, i}=\frac{1}{3} \sqrt{\left(\frac{m_{\mathrm{t} 1, i}}{m_{\mathrm{t}}}\right)\left(\frac{m_{\mathrm{t} 2, i}}{m_{\mathrm{t}}}\right)\left(\frac{m_{1, i}}{m_{1}}\right)} \quad g_{p, i}=\left(\frac{m_{\mathrm{cc}, i}}{m_{p}}\right)^{3 / 2}
\]

For a general case, where both \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) bands and arbitrary valleys are defined, the effective DOS factors are computed similarly to Equation 211 on page 350.

In most III-V materials, electron transport in the \(\Gamma\)-valley must be accounted for properly. Usually, this valley is strongly nonparabolic and its properties are affected by the stress.

[Page 977 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Deformation of Band Structure

According to the \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) perturbation theory [17], the electron \(\Gamma\)-valley mass \(m_{\Gamma}\) can be represented as \(m_{0} / m_{\Gamma}-1=\left(P^{2} / 3\right)\left(2 / E_{\Gamma}+1 /\left(E_{\Gamma}+\Delta_{0}\right)\right)\) where:
- \(E_{\Gamma}\) is the \(\Gamma\)-valley energy in reference to the valence band energy.
- \(m_{0}\) is the free electron mass.
- \(\quad \Delta_{0}\) is the valence band spin-orbit splitting energy.
- \(P^{2}\) is the squared conduction-to-valence momentum matrix element.

An assumption that \(P^{2}\) does not depend on the stress gives the following expression for the stress-dependent \(\Gamma\)-valley mass \(m_{\Gamma}^{\prime}\) :
\[
\begin{aligned}
R_{m} & =\left(\frac{\frac{2}{E_{\Gamma}}+\frac{1}{E_{\Gamma}+\Delta_{0}}}{\frac{2}{E_{\Gamma}^{\prime}}+\frac{1}{E_{\Gamma}^{\prime}+\Delta_{0}}}-1\right) A_{m}+1 \\
\frac{m_{\Gamma}^{\prime}}{m_{0}} & =\frac{R_{m}}{\frac{m_{0}}{m_{\Gamma}}+R_{m}-1}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(E_{\Gamma}^{\prime}=E_{\Gamma}+\Delta E_{\Gamma}, \Delta E_{\Gamma}\) is the stress-related energy shift of the \(\Gamma\)-valley, \(A_{m}\) is a fitting parameter where, if \(A_{m}=0\), there is no stress effect in the \(\Gamma\)-valley mass.

Similarly, based on [18], the stress-dependent band nonparabolicity \(\alpha_{\Gamma}^{\prime}\) of the \(\Gamma\)-valley could be expressed as follows:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& R_{\alpha}=\left(\frac{E_{\Gamma}}{E_{\Gamma}^{\prime}}\left(\frac{1-\frac{m_{\Gamma}^{\prime}}{m_{0}}}{1-\frac{m_{\Gamma}}{m_{0}}}\right)^{2}-1\right) A_{\alpha}+1 \\
& \alpha_{\Gamma}^{\prime}=\alpha_{\Gamma} R_{\alpha}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\alpha_{\Gamma}\) is the relaxed band nonparabolicity of the \(\Gamma\)-valley, \(A_{\alpha}\) is a fitting parameter where, if \(A_{\alpha}=0\), there is no stress effect in the \(\Gamma\)-valley nonparabolicity.

\section*{Using Multivalley Band Structure}

The multivalley model is activated with the keyword MultiValley in the Physics section. If the model must be activated only for electrons or holes, the keywords eMultiValley and hMultiValley can be used. All options of the multivalley model can be used in stress simulations (see Using Multivalley Band Structure on page 346).

