\section*{Effective Mass}

It is known that the effective mass of electrons does not change significantly if the stress is applied along the crystal axis, and it allows you to write the stress-induced mobility change in the form of Equation 1040 and Equation 1046. However, an analysis based on the empirical nonlocal pseudopotential theory [21] shows that, for the stresses applied along \(\langle 110\rangle\), the effective mass changes strongly and it affects the electron mobility. The literature [21] suggests a simple empirical polynomial approximation for the dependency of the effective mass on stress applied along \(\langle 110\rangle\). Later, the two-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) theory [13] was developed for electrons with the main analytic results for the effective masses described in Strained Electron Effective Mass and DOS on page 972.

To formulate the stress-induced change of the mobility generally (accounting for arbitrary channel and interface orientations), the inverse conductivity mass tensor for the valley \(i\) is represented in the following very general form:
\[
\left(\bar{m}_{\mathrm{cond}, i}\right)^{-1}=\frac{1}{\hbar^{2}} \frac{\partial^{2} \varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})}{\partial k_{j} \partial k_{l}}
\]
where:
- \(\quad \varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})\) is the energy dispersion of valley \(i\) defined by the two-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) theory.
- \(k_{j}, k_{l}\) are the wavevectors.
- The inverse mass tensor \(\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }}, i\right)^{-1}\) is computed in the valley energy minima, which is a good approximation for electron conductivity masses in silicon.

Near an interface, you can assume zero current perpendicular to the interface. This assumption and a consideration of the carrier quantization near the interface [22] suggest that the \(3 \times 3\) inverse conductivity mass tensor of Equation 1047 should be recomputed into a \(2 \times 2\) in-plane tensor. For the inverse conductivity mass tensor in the interface coordinate system (with components \(w_{i j}\) ) where the perpendicular axis has an index 3 , the following recomputation into the \(2 \times 2\) in-plane symmetric tensor should be performed:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& w_{11}^{\prime}=w_{11}-\frac{w_{13}^{2}}{w_{33}} \\
& w_{22}^{\prime}=w_{22}-\frac{w_{23}^{2}}{w_{33}} \\
& w_{12}^{\prime}=w_{12}-\frac{w_{13} w_{23}}{w_{33}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Setting \(w^{\prime}{ }_{13}=w^{\prime}{ }_{23}=0\) and \(w^{\prime}{ }_{33}=w_{33}\), this tensor is rotated back to the crystal coordinate system and is used as ( \(m_{\text {cond }, i}\) ). Such a recomputation has an effect for cases where the valley ellipsoid in k -space is not aligned to the interface.

[Page 984 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Modeling

Another optional mass transformation can be performed for 1D carrier transport that appears, for example, in nanowires. The 1D mass transformation is performed in the vicinity of the interface and with a specified direction of the 1D carrier transport. This direction (the user-defined vector in the simulation coordinate system) is projected on to the interface plane. The projected in-plane vector and the normal vector to the interface define a coordinate system where the tensor from Equation 1048 (with 2D transport mass transformation) is rotated.

Assuming that the index 1 of the rotated tensor is along the 1 D transport direction, the corresponding inverse mass tensor component can be written as:
\[
w_{11}^{\prime \prime}=w_{11}^{\prime}-\frac{\left(w_{12}^{\prime}\right)^{2}}{w_{22}^{\prime}}
\]

Similar to Equation 1048, when setting \(w^{\prime \prime}{ }_{12}=w^{\prime \prime}{ }_{13}=w^{\prime \prime}{ }_{23}=0\) and \(w^{\prime \prime}{ }_{22}=w^{\prime}{ }_{22}, w^{\prime \prime}{ }_{33}=w^{\prime}{ }_{32}\), this diagonal tensor is rotated back to the crystal coordinate system and is used as \(\left(m_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\).

To account for such stress-induced mass change, Equation 1040 and Equation 1046 are generalized as stated in the next section, Inversion Layer.

\section*{Inversion Layer}

Generally, using only the valley data, the total mobility tensor could be written in the following general form, which generalizes Equation 1040, and Equation 1046:
\[
\bar{\mu}_{n}=q \tau_{0} \sum_{i} \frac{n_{i}}{n} \frac{\tau_{i}}{\tau_{0}}\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}
\]
where:
- \(n_{i} / n\) is a local valley occupation.
- \(\tau_{i} / \tau_{0}\) is the ratio of stressed and unstressed relaxation times as it is in Equation 1045.
- ( \(\left.\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\) is the inverse conductivity mass tensor Equation 1047.

To use Equation 1050 in Sentaurus Device stress modeling, the mobility tensor \(\bar{\mu}_{n}\) should be divided by unstressed mobility \(\mu_{n 0}\) because the stress effect is accounted for as a multiplication factor to TCAD mobility (for example, the Lombardi model) used in the device simulation. Therefore, the unstressed mobility \(\mu_{n 0}\) also is computed by Equation 1050, but with zero stress.

In the multivalley representation, Equation 1050 is general enough to describe the mobility for both bulk and MOSFET inversion layer cases, but a difference between these cases is in the \(n_{i} / n\) and \(\tau_{i} / \tau_{0}\) terms. For inversion layers, the quantization effect must be accounted for in each valley separately.

[Page 985 END]
