Mobility Modeling

At this point, only the multivalley MLDA model gives such a possibility (see Modified Local-Density Approximation Model on page 388). Therefore, for the inversion layer mobility, the local valley occupation is computed by the multivalley MLDA model where the quantization mass \(m_{\mathrm{q}}\) in the perpendicular direction to the interface is computed using stressed \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) bands (by a rotation of the inverse mass tensor \(\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\) to an interface coordinate system).

\section*{Note:}

The multivalley MLDA model accounts for arbitrary interface orientation automatically (see Interface Orientation and Stress Dependencies on page 389), which complements the general inverse mass tensor \(\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\) in Equation 1047, and it gives you an automatic option that accounts for both channel and interface orientations simultaneously.

For the inversion layer mobility model, there are some changes to the scattering ratio \(\tau_{i} / \tau_{0}\) in Equation 1044. First, the DOS used in Equation 1042 is a parabolic bulk DOS, which makes such a scattering model mostly applicable to the bulk case. The MLDA quantization model (Equation 250) gives an MLDA DOS \(D^{l}(\varepsilon, z)\) that becomes the bulk DOS at a distance from the interface where the quantum effect is small. Second, Equation 1042 accounts only for the intervalley optical phonon scattering, but Equation 1051 includes both intervalley and intravalley scattering with acoustic and optical phonons.

In addition, this equation takes into account an effect of the interface quantization in the scattering by the following use of both MLDA and bulk DOS:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\sum_{j} D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)}{\tau_{\mathrm{ac}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)} & =\frac{2 \pi k T}{\bar{h} \rho}\left(\frac{D_{\mathrm{ac}}}{c_{1}}\right)^{2} \sum_{j} \sum_{k} D_{\mathrm{bulk}}^{j}(\varepsilon) D_{\mathrm{bulk}}^{k}\left(\varepsilon-\Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}\right) \\
\frac{\sum_{j} D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)}{\tau_{\mathrm{ope}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)} & =\frac{\pi \bar{h} D_{\mathrm{op}}^{2}}{\rho \hbar \omega_{\mathrm{opt}}}\left(N_{\mathrm{op}}+1\right) \sum_{j} \sum_{k} D_{\mathrm{bulk}}^{j}(\varepsilon) D_{\mathrm{bulk}}^{k}\left(\varepsilon-\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{opt}}-\Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}\right) \\
\frac{\sum_{j}^{j} D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)}{\tau_{\mathrm{opa}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)} & =\frac{\pi \bar{h} D_{\mathrm{op}}^{2}}{\rho \hbar \omega_{\mathrm{opt}}} N_{\mathrm{op}} \sum_{j} \sum_{k} D_{\mathrm{bulk}}^{j}(\varepsilon) D_{\mathrm{bulk}}^{k}\left(\varepsilon+\hbar \omega_{\mathrm{opt}}-\Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}\right) \\
S^{i}(\varepsilon, z) & =\frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{ac}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}+\frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{ope}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}+\frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{opa}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(D_{\text {bulk }}^{i}(\varepsilon)=\frac{2}{(2 \pi)^{3}} \oint_{\varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})=\varepsilon} \frac{d S}{\left|\nabla_{k} \varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})\right|}\) is the electron bulk DOS of the valley \(i\).
- \(\Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}=\Delta E_{\mathrm{C}, k}-\Delta E_{\mathrm{C}, i}\) is a valley minimum energy difference between valleys \(i\) and \(k\).

[Page 986 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Modeling
- \(\frac{D_{\mathrm{ac}}}{c_{1}}\) is the ratio of the acoustic-phonon deformation potential and the sound velocity.
- \(\rho\) is the mass density.
- \(\hbar \omega_{\text {opt }}\) is the optical-phonon energy.
- \(D_{\text {op }}\) is the optical-phonon deformation potential.
- \(N_{\text {op }}=\left[\exp \left(\hbar \omega_{\text {opt }} / k T\right)-1\right]^{-1}\) is the phonon number.

Note:
For the bulk case, \(D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)=D_{\text {bulk }}^{j}(\varepsilon)\) and, therefore, Equation 1051 can be simplified to regular bulk scattering rate equations. Equation 1051 accounts for both interband and intraband phonon scattering with the same deformation potentials, but there is an option to control the interband scattering factor.

Using Equation 1051 will activate a numeric integration in Equation 1043 with GaussLaguerre quadratures as described in Nonparabolic Band Structure on page 343. Another change in the scattering ratio \(\tau_{i} / \tau_{0}\) is based on comparisons to various stress- and orientation-dependent experimental data. It gives the new user-defined parameter \(\beta\) for the inversion layer (see Using Multivalley Electron Mobility Model on page 987).

For the bulk case, the unstressed mobility \(\mu_{n 0}\) computed by Equation 1050 is always isotropic. However, for the MOSFET on a (110) silicon substrate, it is not. In this case, Equation 1050 without stress gives anisotropic unstressed electron mobility, and a ratio between the mobilities of the <100> and <110> channel orientations is equal to approximately 1.1. This ratio is in reasonable agreement to experimentally observed data where the ratio changes from 1.2 to 1.1 for a high-gate electric field.

\section*{Note:}

By default, the unstressed mobility \(\mu_{n 0}\) (in Equation 1039) is always computed for a <110> channel orientation and for a substrate orientation that corresponds to the auto-orientation Lombardi option (see Auto-Orientation for the Lombardi Model on page 426). Such a default requires you to have calibrated the Lombardi model parameters for the <110> channel (critical for MOSFETs on (110) substrate where the unstressed mobility is anisotropic).

\section*{Using Multivalley Electron Mobility Model}

The stress-induced mobility model can be activated regionwise or materialwise. To activate the inversion layer model (see Inversion Layer on page 985), the eMultivalley (MLDA) statement must be specified in the Physics section. In this case, all valleys defined by the multivalley model (for example, with eMultivalley (kpDOS parfile); see Multivalley Band Structure on page 342) will be used in the model. However, it is calibrated for silicon, germanium, and SiGe band structures (with \(\Delta_{2}\) valleys and L-valleys), and for InGaAs materials where the \(\Gamma\)-valley carrier transport is mostly important.

[Page 987 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


The keyword MLDA activates the multivalley MLDA quantization model (see Modified Local-Density Approximation Model on page 388), which is applied to both the density and the inversion layer stress-induced mobility models. To use another quantization model in the density computation, specify the -Density option in the eMultivalley statement (see Notes on the Use of the MLDA Model on page 396).

To ensure that electron stress-related models are consistent and physically correct, the Physics section should contain the following:
```
Physics {
    eMultiValley(MLDA)
    Piezo (Model(
        Mobility(eSubband(Fermi EffectiveMass Scattering(MLDA)))
    ))
}
```


