\section*{Multivalley Hole Mobility Model}

Similar to the electron stress-induced mobility model (Equation 1050), the total hole mobility tensor can be written in the following general form, which can be applied to both bulk and inversion layer cases [23]:
\[
\bar{\mu}_{p}=q \tau_{0} \sum_{i} \frac{p_{i}}{p} \frac{\tau}{\tau_{0}}\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}
\]
where:
- \(p_{i} / p\) is a local hole-band occupation.
- \(\tau / \tau_{0}\) is a ratio of the stressed and unstressed valence-band relaxation times.
- \(\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\) is the inverse conductivity hole mass tensor.

The model accounts for the six-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) hole band structure [14] in all of the above three terms of Equation 1052. In the case of the inversion layer, the model computes the six-band \(\mathrm{k} \cdot \mathrm{p}\) MLDA DOS of each band as described in Modified Local-Density Approximation Model on page 388 and, correspondingly, it affects all terms of Equation 1052. Finally, the model computes the mobility ratio ( \(3 \times 3\) tensor), which corrects the relaxed current density in Equation 1039.

[Page 990 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Modeling

\section*{Effective Mass}

The inverse mass tensor \(\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\) of the band \(i\) in Equation 1052 is based on an averaging of the reciprocal mass tensor in \(\mathbf{k}\)-space and energy space. If the reciprocal mass tensor at any \(\mathbf{k}\)-vector is expressed as follows:
\[
w_{j l}^{i}(\vec{k})=\frac{1}{\hbar^{2}} \frac{\partial^{2} \varepsilon_{i}(\vec{k})}{\partial k_{j} \partial k_{l}}
\]
then the averaging in \(\mathbf{k}\)-space is performed in accordance to the DOS computation (Equation 253), which for the inversion layer can be formulated as:
\[
w_{j l}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)=\frac{\frac{2}{(2 \pi)^{3}} \oint_{\varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})=\varepsilon} \frac{w_{j l}^{i}(\vec{k})}{\left|\nabla_{k} \varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})\right|}\left[1-\exp \left(i 2 z \gamma_{\mathrm{kp}} \sum_{j} k_{j} \frac{w_{j 3}(\vec{k})}{w_{33}(\vec{k})}\right)\right] d S}{D^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}
\]

Finally, the inverse mass tensor of the band \(i\) is computed as an averaged value over the energy space with the carrier distribution function \(f\left(\varepsilon, F_{p}\right)\) accounted:
\[
\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}=\frac{\int_{0}^{\infty} D^{i}(\varepsilon, z) w_{j l}^{i}(\varepsilon, z) f\left(\varepsilon, F_{p}\right) d \varepsilon}{p_{i}}
\]
where:
- \(p_{i}\) is a hole-band concentration \(\left(p_{i}\left(F_{p}, z\right)=\int_{0}^{\infty} D^{i}(\varepsilon, z) f\left(\varepsilon, F_{p}\right) d \varepsilon\right)\).
- \(\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\) is a symmetric \(3 \times 3\) tensor, which depends on the quasi-Fermi energy \(F_{p}\) and the distance from interface \(z\) (for the inversion layer case).

Similar to the computation of the hole-band concentration \(p_{i}\), the integral over the energy in Equation 1055 is computed using Gauss-Laguerre quadratures and, for that, the energy-dependent reciprocal mass tensor (Equation 1054) is computed on a predefined energy mesh (same as for the DOS \(D^{i}(\varepsilon, z)\) ).

Optionally, you can account for the 2D (in the vicinity of interfaces) or the 1D (in nanowires) carrier transport nature in the inverse mass tensor \(\left(\bar{m}_{\text {cond }, i}\right)^{-1}\). This is similar to recomputation of the electron transport effective masses (Equation 1048 and Equation 1049). However, for holes, it is performed for all considered energies and, correspondingly, it uses the inverse mass tensor components \(w_{j l}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)\).

\section*{Scattering}

The scattering model defines the ratio of the stressed and unstressed valence-band momentum relaxation times \(\tau / \tau_{0}\). The model considers four scattering mechanisms (which are affected by the stress) for holes in each band assisted by: acoustic phonon, optical phonon emission, optical phonon absorption, and simplified impurity scattering.

[Page 991 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Modeling

The phonon-assisted relaxation times can be expressed as follows for the band \(i\) in the case of the inversion layer:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\sum_{j} D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)}{\tau_{\mathrm{ac}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}=\frac{2 \pi k T}{\bar{h} \rho}\left(\frac{D_{\mathrm{ac}}}{c_{1}}\right)^{2} \sum_{j} \sum_{k} D_{\text {bulk }}^{j}(\varepsilon) D_{\text {bulk }}^{k}\left(\varepsilon-\Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}\right) \\
& \frac{\sum_{j} D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)}{\tau_{\text {ope }}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}=\frac{\pi \bar{h} D_{\text {op }}^{2}}{\rho \varepsilon_{\mathrm{op}}}\left(N_{\mathrm{op}}+1\right) \sum_{j} \sum_{k} D_{\text {bulk }}^{j}(\varepsilon) D_{\text {bulk }}^{k}\left(\varepsilon-\varepsilon_{\mathrm{op}}-\Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}\right) \\
& \frac{\sum_{j} D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)}{\tau_{\text {opa }}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}=\frac{\pi \bar{h} D_{\text {op }}^{2}}{\rho \varepsilon_{\mathrm{op}}} N_{\text {op }} \sum_{j} \sum_{k} D_{\text {bulk }}^{j}(\varepsilon) D_{\text {bulk }}^{k}\left(\varepsilon+\varepsilon_{\mathrm{op}}-\Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(D_{\text {bulk }}^{i}(\varepsilon)=\frac{2}{(2 \pi)^{3}} \oint_{\varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})=\varepsilon} \frac{d S}{\left|\nabla_{k} \varepsilon^{i}(\vec{k})\right|}\) is the hole bulk DOS of the band \(i\).
- \(\quad \Delta \varepsilon_{0}^{k, i}\) is a band minimum energy difference between bands \(i\) and \(k\).
- \(\frac{D_{\mathrm{ac}}}{c_{1}}\) is a ratio of the acoustic-phonon deformation potential by the sound velocity.
- \(\rho\) is the mass density.
- \(\varepsilon_{\text {op }}\) is the optical-phonon energy.
- \(D_{\text {op }}\) is the optical-phonon deformation potential.
- \(N_{\mathrm{op}}=\left[\exp \left(\varepsilon_{\mathrm{op}} / k T\right)-1\right]^{-1}\) is the phonon number.

Note:
For the bulk case, \(D^{j}(\varepsilon, z)=D_{\text {bulk }}^{j}(\varepsilon)\) and, therefore, Equation 1056 can be simplified to regular bulk scattering rate equations. Equation 1056 accounts for both interband and intraband phonon scattering with the same deformation potentials, but you have an option to control the interband scattering factor.

Based on Equation 1056, the total phonon-limited hole-scattering rate in the band \(i\) is written as:
\[
\frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{ph}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}=\frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{ac}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}+\frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{ope}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}+\frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{opa}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)}
\]

[Page 992 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Modeling

Therefore, the macroscopic phonon-limited momentum relaxation time of the full valence band can be expressed similarly for electrons (Equation 1044):
\[
\frac{1}{\tau^{\mathrm{ph}}}=\frac{\sum_{i} \int_{0}^{\infty} D^{i}(\varepsilon, z) \frac{1}{\tau_{\mathrm{ph}}^{i}(\varepsilon, z)} f\left(\varepsilon, F_{p}\right) d \varepsilon}{p}
\]
where \(\tau^{\mathrm{ph}}\) depends on the quasi-Fermi energy \(F_{p}\) and the distance from interface \(z\) (for the inversion layer case). The impurity scattering is introduced also similarly to how it is performed for electrons in Equation 1045, and the ratio of the stressed and unstressed valence-band relaxation times in Equation 1052 is expressed as follows:
\[
\frac{\tau}{\tau_{0}}=\frac{1}{1+\left(\frac{\tau_{0}^{\mathrm{ph}}}{\tau^{\mathrm{ph}}}-1\right) \frac{1-\beta^{-1}}{1+\left(\frac{N_{\mathrm{tot}}}{N_{\mathrm{ref}}}\right)^{\alpha}}}
\]
where:
- \(\tau_{0}^{\mathrm{ph}}\) is the phonon-limited momentum relaxation time in the valence band for zero stress computed using Equation 1057 and Equation 1058.
- \(\quad N_{\text {tot }}\) is the doping concentration.
- \(\quad N_{\text {ref }}, \alpha\) are fitting parameters of the impurity scattering model.
- \(\beta\) is a fitting parameter that can be represented as \(\beta=1+\tau^{\text {indep }} / \tau_{0}^{\text {ph }}\), where \(\tau^{\text {indep }}\) is a relaxation time of other scattering mechanisms that are not accounted for in Equation 1056 and that are independent of the stress. Therefore, for example, if the stress-independent scattering rate (not accounted for in Equation 1056) is much higher than \(1 / \tau_{0}^{\mathrm{ph}}\), then \(\beta=1\) and therefore \(\tau / \tau_{0}=1\). However, if this rate is negligible, then \(\beta^{-1}=0\).

\section*{Note:}

The default value of the parameter \(\beta\) differs for the bulk and inversion layer simulations. Some fitting of this parameter was performed to obtain a reasonable agreement of the model (Equation 1052) to multiple stress and orientation data.

