\section*{Doping and Temperature Dependency}

A simple model for the doping and temperature variation of the first-order and second-order piezoconductance coefficients is given by [7][28]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\Pi_{i j}(N, T) & =P_{1}(N, T) \Pi_{i j}(0,300 \mathrm{~K}) \\
\Pi_{i j k}(N, T) & =P_{2}(N, T) \Pi_{i j k}(0,300 \mathrm{~K})
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\Pi_{i j}(0,300 \mathrm{~K})\) and \(\Pi_{i j k}(0,300 \mathrm{~K})\) are piezoconductance coefficients for low-doped silicon at 300 K , and \(P_{1}(N, T)\) and \(P_{2}(N, T)\) are doping factors given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& P_{1}(N, T)=\left(\frac{300 \mathrm{~K}}{T}\right) \frac{F_{-1}(\eta)}{F_{0}(\eta)} \\
& P_{2}(N, T)=\left(\frac{300 \mathrm{~K}}{T}\right)^{2} \frac{F_{-2}(\eta)}{F_{0}(\eta)}
\end{aligned}
\]

In Equation 1077, \(F_{r}(\eta)\) is a Fermi-Dirac integral of order \(r\), and \(\eta\) is the Fermi energy measured from the band edge in units of \(k T\left(\eta_{n}=\left(E_{\mathrm{F}, n}-E_{\mathrm{C}}\right) /(k T)\right.\) and \(\eta_{p}=\left(E_{\mathrm{V}}-E_{\mathrm{F}, p}\right) /(k T)\) ). Doping dependency is introduced by assuming charge neutrality in the calculation of the Fermi energy.

\section*{Note:}

For minority carriers, the doping factors \(P_{1}(N, T)\) and \(P_{2}(N, T)\) are equal to 1 . In addition, Sentaurus Device allows the calculation to be suppressed for majority carriers when the doping is below a user-specified doping threshold (see Stress Mobility Model for Minority Carriers on page 1021).

The temperature and doping variation of the piezoresistance coefficients is obtained by combining Equation 1073 and Equation 1076. An exception to this is when the first-order model is used. In this case, the piezoresistance coefficients are split between a constant part (associated with changes in the effective masses) and a part that varies with temperature and doping (associated with anisotropic scattering):
\[
\pi_{i j}(N, T)=\pi_{i j, \operatorname{var}} P_{1}(N, T)+\pi_{i j, \operatorname{con}}
\]

The default values of the piezoresistance coefficients for low-doped silicon at 300 K are listed in Table 165 on page 1006 and Table 166 on page 1006. They can be changed in the parameter file as described in Using Piezoresistance Mobility Model on page 1005.

