\section*{Mobility Stress Factor PMI Model}

A mobility stress factor PMI model (see Mobility Stress Factor on page 1412) created by the user can be utilized to obtain a mobility enhancement factor. In addition to stress, this type of PMI model allows a dependency on the normal electric field.

If specified, the Factor options ChannelDirection=<n>, AutoOrientation, and ParameterSetName="<psname>" are passed as parameters to the mobility stress factor PMI model (AutoOrientation is passed as AutoOrientation=1).

[Page 1019 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mobility Modeling

\section*{SFactor Dataset or PMI Model}

The sFactor parameter can be used to obtain an isotropic mobility enhancement factor from a dataset or a PMI model.

If SFactor="<dataset_name>" is used, then the vertex values of \(\gamma\) are taken directly from the specified dataset name, which can include the PMI user fields PMIUserField0 through PMIUserField299.

If SFactor="<pmi_model_name>" is used, then the vertex values of \(\gamma\) are calculated from a space factor PMI model (see Space Factor on page 1517). If specified, then the Factor options ChannelDirection=<n>, AutoOrientation, and ParameterSetName="<psname>" are passed as parameters to the space factor PMI model (AutoOrientation is passed as AutoOrientation \(=1\) ).

\section*{Isotropic Factor Model Options}

This section discusses options of the isotropic factor model.

\section*{Kanda Parameter}

The Kanda parameter can be specified for all isotropic factor models to include a doping and temperature dependency in the enhancement factor calculation. In the case of the FirstOrder and secondOrder piezoresistance models, this is included as described in Doping and Temperature Dependency on page 1005. For the EffectiveStressModel and SFactor models, the enhancement factor given by Equation 1081 is modified to include the \(P_{1}(N, T)\) factor (see Equation 1077):
\[
\gamma=1+P_{1}(N, T) \frac{\Delta \mu_{\mathrm{low}}}{\mu_{\mathrm{low}, 0}}
\]

\section*{Named Parameter Sets and Auto-Orientation}

The piezoresistance models and the EffectiveStressModel support the use of named parameter sets (see Named Parameter Sets on page 90) and the auto-orientation framework (see Auto-Orientation Framework on page 91). To use one of these capabilities, specify ParameterSetName="<psname>" or AutoOrientation as an argument to Factor in the command file.

\section*{Factor Models Applied to Mobility Components}

By default, the isotropic mobility enhancement factor \(\gamma\) calculated by a Factor model is applied to total low-field mobility. However, the calculated enhancement factor can be applied to select mobility components (for example, only to acoustic phonon mobility or surface roughness mobility in the Lombardi model) by specifying the ApplyToMobilityComponents option. When this option is selected, mobility models that

[Page 1020 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


support this feature apply an enhancement factor \(\gamma_{i}\) to the \(i^{\text {th }}\) mobility component for which a stress scaling factor \(a_{i}\) is available:
\[
\gamma_{i}=1+a_{i}(\gamma-1)
\]

If \(a_{i}=1\), then \(\gamma_{i}=\gamma\).
If \(a_{i}=0\), then \(\gamma_{i}=1\) and no stress enhancement factor is applied to this component. In most cases, the stress scaling factors have a value of 0 or 1 , but intermediate values are allowed.

The \(a_{i}\) parameters are specified in the parameter file in the parameter set associated with the mobility model. The mobility models that support this feature and the available stress scaling parameters are shown in Table 168.

