Numeric Approximations for Tensor Mobility

\section*{Plotting Mobility Enhancement Factors}

The mobility multiplication tensor ( \(\bar{\mu} / \mu_{0}\) ) can be plotted on the mesh nodes. This tensor is a symmetric \(3 \times 3\) matrix and, therefore, has six independent values. To plot these values on the mesh nodes for electron and hole mobilities, use the keywords:
- eMobilityStressFactorXX, eMobilityStressFactorYY, eMobilityStressFactorZZ
- eMobilityStressFactorYZ, eMobilityStressFactorXZ,eMobilityStressFactorXY
- hMobilityStressFactorXX, hMobilityStressFactorYY, hMobilityStressFactorZZ
- hMobilityStressFactorYZ, hMobilityStressFactorXZ, hMobilityStressFactorXY

\section*{Numeric Approximations for Tensor Mobility}

This section discusses numeric approximations for tensor mobility.

\section*{Tensor Grid Option}

Due to an applied mechanical stress, the mobility can become a tensor. The numeric approximation of the transport equations with tensor mobility is complicated (see Chapter 28 on page 909). However, if the mesh is a tensor one, the approximation is simpler. For this option, off-diagonal mobility elements are not used and, therefore, there are no mixed derivatives in the approximation. Such an approximation gives an M-matrix property for the Jacobian and it permits stable stress simulations. Very often, critical regions are simple and the mesh constructed in such regions can be close to a tensor one.

\section*{Note:}

The off-diagonal elements of the mobility tensor appear only if there is a shear stress or the simulation coordinate system of Sentaurus Device is different from the crystal system.

By default, Sentaurus Device uses this simple tensor-grid approximation (keyword TensorGridAniso in the Math section).

The stressSG approximation gives the most accurate results and is independent of the mesh orientation (see StressSG on page 911). Convergence, however, might be worse than for TensorGridAniso.

The AverageAniso approximation is based on a local transformation of an anisotropic problem (stress-induced mobility tensor) to an isotropic one (see AverageAniso on page 912).

[Page 1025 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Numeric Approximations for Tensor Mobility

\section*{Note:}

All approximation options do not guarantee a correct solution for arbitrary mesh and stress. Experiments with these options can give an estimation of ignored terms.

\section*{Stress Tensor Applied to Low-Field Mobility}

In all the previous models, the stress tensor factor was a linear factor applied to high-field mobility. Sentaurus Device allows also to apply the following diagonal mobility tensor factor to the low-field mobility:
\[
\mu_{\text {high }}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\mu_{\text {high }}\left(\mu_{\text {low }} \cdot s_{x x}, \ldots\right) & 0 & 0 \\
0 & \mu_{\text {high }}\left(\mu_{\text {low }} \cdot s_{y y}, \ldots\right) & 0 \\
0 & 0 & \mu_{\text {high }}\left(\mu_{\text {low }} \cdot s_{z z}, \ldots\right)
\end{array}\right]
\]
where:
- \(s_{i i}\) are the diagonal elements of the stress tensor factor \(\left(\overline{1}+\beta \frac{\Delta \bar{\mu}_{\text {stress }}}{\mu_{0}}\right)\) in Equation 1094. In this model, off-diagonal elements are not used.
- \(\mu_{\text {high }}(\ldots)\) is a scalar function that computes the high-field mobility (see High-Field Saturation Models on page 457).

This model can be specified in the Math section of the command file as follows:
```
Math { StressMobilityDependence = TensorFactor }
```


In this case, the dependency of saturation velocity on stress is given by:
\[
v_{\mathrm{sat}, i}=v_{\mathrm{sat}, 0} \cdot\left(1+\alpha \cdot t_{i}\right)
\]
which results in the same dependency on SaturationFactor described in Dependency of Saturation Velocity on Stress on page 1023 when a Caughey-Thomas-type mobility model is used.

The high-field mobility tensor (in Equation 1098) and the corresponding factors \(\mu_{\text {high }}\left(\mu_{\text {low }} \cdot s_{i i}, \ldots\right) / \mu_{\text {high }}\left(\mu_{\text {low }}, \ldots\right)\) can be plotted on the mesh nodes.
To plot these values for electron and hole mobilities, use the following keywords in the Plot section:
- eTensorMobilityXX, eTensorMobilityYY, eTensorMobilityZZ
- hTensorMobilityXX, hTensorMobilityYY, hTensorMobilityZZ

[Page 1026 END]
