\section*{Thermal Conductivity}

Sentaurus Device uses the following temperature-dependent thermal conductivity \(\kappa\) in silicon [3]:
\[
\kappa(T)=\frac{1}{a+b T+c T^{2}}
\]
where \(a=0.03 \mathrm{~cm} \mathrm{KW}^{-1}, b=1.56 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{cmW}^{-1}\), and \(c=1.65 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{~cm} \mathrm{~W}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}\). The range of validity is from 200 K to well above 600 K . Table 172 lists values of the thermal conductivity for some materials.

