Furthermore, a simple PMI and a multistate configuration-dependent PMI are available to compute thermal conductivity. See Thermal Conductivity on page 1385 and Multistate Configuration-Dependent Thermal Conductivity on page 1367.

\section*{The AllDependent Thermal Conductivity Model}

In general, thermal conductivity \(\kappa\) is a function of lattice temperature \(T\), doping density \(N\), layer thickness \(d_{\mathrm{Ly}}\), and mole fraction \(x\).

[Page 1045 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Thermal Conductivity

Starting with the Boltzmann transport equation for phonons and with relaxation time approximations, \(\kappa\) is expressed as an integral over phonon frequency [5]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \kappa=\frac{1}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{2 \pi^{2}} \cdot n_{j} \cdot \sum_{j} \int_{0}^{\omega_{0, j}} \frac{\tau_{\omega, j}}{v_{\omega, j}} C(\omega) \omega^{2} d \omega \\
& C(x)=k x^{2} e^{x}\left(e^{x}-1\right)^{-2} \\
& x=\frac{\hbar \omega}{k T}
\end{aligned}
\]

For each phonon branch \(\kappa, \omega_{0, j}\) is the peak frequency, \(v_{0, j}\) is the sound velocity, and \(\tau_{0, j}\) is the total relaxation time. For the longitudinal mode \((j=L), n_{L}=1\). For the transverse mode \((j=T), n_{T}=1\).

\section*{Bulk Thermal Conductivity Computation}

The total relaxation time is calculated with given scattering mechanisms. For pure bulk material [5]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \tau_{\mathrm{LN}}^{-1}=B_{\mathrm{L}} \omega^{2} T^{3}+\tau_{I}^{-1}+\tau_{\mathrm{b}}^{-1}, 0<\omega<\omega_{3} \\
& \tau_{\mathrm{TN}}^{-1}=B_{\mathrm{T}} \omega T^{4}+\tau_{I}^{-1}+\tau_{\mathrm{b}}^{-1}, \omega<\omega_{1} \\
& \tau_{\mathrm{TU}}^{-1}=B_{\mathrm{TU}} \omega^{2} / \sinh x+\tau_{I}^{-1}+\tau_{\mathrm{b}}^{-1}, \omega_{1}<\omega<\omega_{2} \\
& \tau_{I}^{-1}=A_{I} \omega^{4} \\
& \tau_{\mathrm{b}}^{-1}=\frac{v_{s}}{F L} \\
& v_{s}=\left[\frac{1}{3}\left(v_{\mathrm{L}}^{-1}+2 v_{\mathrm{T}}^{-1}\right)\right]^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

Equation 1119, Equation 1120, and Equation 1121 represent the phonon relaxation time for the longitudinal and transverse branches. For the transverse branch, the normal ( N ) process and the Umklapp (U) process are solved separately. Frequencies and phonon velocities are extracted from the bulk phonon dispersion:
- \(\quad \omega_{1}\) is the turning point of the transverse branch, where the \(U\) process starts to have an effect.
- \(\quad \omega_{2}\) is the peak frequency of the transverse branch.
- \(\quad \omega_{3}\) is the peak frequency of the longitudinal branch.
- \(\omega_{4}\) is the turning point of the longitudinal branch.
- \(v_{\mathrm{L}}\) is the velocity of the longitudinal mode when \(\omega<\omega_{4}\).
- \(v_{\mathrm{Lp}}\) is the velocity of the longitudinal mode when \(\omega_{4}<\omega<\omega_{3}\).

[Page 1046 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Thermal Conductivity
- \(\quad v_{\mathrm{T}}\) is the velocity of the transverse mode when \(\omega<\omega_{1}\).
- \(\quad v_{\mathrm{TU}}\) is the velocity of the transverse mode when \(\omega_{1}<\omega<\omega_{2}\).
- \(\quad B_{\mathrm{L}}, B_{\mathrm{T}}\), and \(B_{\mathrm{TU}}\) are fitting parameters.
- \(\tau_{I}^{-1}\) and \(\tau_{\mathrm{b}}^{-1}\) represent scattering due to point defects and the boundary, where:
- \(A_{I}\) is the scattering strength due to defects.
- \(L\) is the bulk sample dimension.

The model is activated in the command file by:
```
Physics (...) {
    ThermalConductivity ( AllDep )
}
```


