\section*{Note:}

To achieve good agreement with measurement, you need to understand the relative contribution of the three phonon branches to \(\kappa\) : \(\kappa_{\mathrm{TU}}\) mainly determines the high-temperature range. The absolute values of \(\kappa_{T}\) and \(\kappa_{L}\) determine the peak value of \(\kappa\), while their relative ratio \(\kappa_{T} / \kappa_{L}\) affects the slope of \(\kappa\) at low temperatures: the lower the ratio, the larger the slope. The fitting parameters \(B_{\mathrm{L}}\), \(B_{\mathrm{T}}\), and \(B_{\mathrm{TU}}\) are determined accordingly.

\section*{Bulk Relaxation Time With Doping}

In the case of doped samples, \(\kappa\) decreases due to phonon scattering with impurities and free carriers. The phonon-impurity scattering is treated in a similar way to point defects [6]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \tau_{\text {impurity }}^{-1}=A \omega^{4} \\
& A=A_{I}+A_{\delta M}+A_{\delta R}+A_{x} \\
& A_{\delta M}=\frac{N V^{2}}{4 \pi v_{s}^{3}}\left(\frac{M-M_{\text {doped }}}{M}\right)^{2} \\
& A_{\delta R}=\frac{2 N V^{2}}{\pi v_{s}^{3}} Q_{0}^{2} \Upsilon^{2}\left(\frac{R-R_{\text {doped }}}{R}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 1048 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Thermal Conductivity

\(A_{\delta M}\) and \(A_{\delta R}\) model the impact of mass and radius differences between the host atom and the impurity atom with the given doping concentration \(N\), where:
- \(V\) is the crystal volume of the host atom.
- \(M\) is the mass of the host atom.
- \(M_{\text {doped }}\) is the mass of the impurity atom.
- \(R\) is the radius of the host atom.
- \(R_{\mathrm{doped}}\) is the radius of the impurity atom.
- \(Q_{0}\) is a constant corresponding to the impurity.
- \(A_{x}\) is a fitting parameter.

The impact of phonon-carrier scattering is considered with two parts: the free carriers in the metallic state and the carriers bound to the impurity center. With a given carrier concentration \(n\), the concentrations of bound carriers \(N_{n}\) and metallic carriers \(N_{m}\) are [7]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{n}=n \exp \left(-t_{c}\right) \\
& N_{m}=n\left[1-\exp \left(-t_{c}\right)\right] \\
& t_{c}=(4 \pi / 3) n r_{c}^{3} \\
& r_{c}=\left(144 / \pi^{2}\right)^{1 / 3} a_{\mathrm{B}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where the Bohr radius \(a_{\mathrm{B}}\) is:
\[
a_{\mathrm{B}}=\left(\frac{4 \pi \varepsilon_{0} \hbar^{2}}{m_{0} e^{2}}\right)\left(\frac{\varepsilon_{s}}{\varepsilon_{0}}\right)\left(\frac{m_{0}}{m_{e}}\right)
\]

Here:
- \(\varepsilon_{s}\) is the dielectric constant.
- \(m_{e}\) (or \(m_{h}\) ) is the electron (or hole) effective mass of the host atom.

The relaxation time related to bound carriers is [8]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \tau_{\text {bound }, j}^{-1}=\frac{\omega^{4}\left[(1 / 3) \Xi_{u}\right]^{4}}{10 \pi \rho^{2} v_{s}^{2}} \chi^{2}\left(\frac{\omega}{v_{s}}\right)\left[v_{L}^{-5} \chi^{2}\left(\frac{\omega}{v_{L}}\right)+\frac{3}{2} v_{T}^{-5} \chi^{2}\left(\frac{\omega}{v_{T}}\right)\right] \cdot w_{j} \cdot \frac{2 \Delta^{2}}{\left(\Delta^{2}-\hbar^{2} \omega^{2}\right)^{2}}\left(2 N_{n}\right) \\
& \chi\left(q_{j}\right)=\left[1+(1 / 4) a_{B}^{2} q_{j}^{2}\right]^{-2}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(\Xi_{u}\) is the shear deformation potential.
- \(\rho\) is the crystal mass density.
- \(w_{\mathrm{L}}, w_{\mathrm{T}}\), and \(w_{\mathrm{TU}}\) are parameters corresponding to each phonon mode.

[Page 1049 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Thermal Conductivity

For carriers in metallic states, the relaxation time is [6]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \tau_{\text {free }}^{-1}=\frac{\left(m_{e} E_{\mathrm{D}}\right)^{2} \omega}{2 \pi \rho \hbar^{3} v_{s}}, q<2 k_{F} \\
& \tau_{\text {free }}^{-1}=\frac{b N_{m}\left(m_{e} E_{\mathrm{D}}\right)^{2}}{\rho \hbar^{3} q^{5} a_{\mathrm{B}}^{3}}, q>2 k_{F}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(E_{\mathrm{D}}\) is the deformation potential, and \(b\) is a fitting parameter.
Equation 1136 and Equation 1137 are continuous at \(q=2 k_{F}\), which imposes the following relation:
\[
k_{F}=\left(\frac{b N_{m} \pi}{32 a_{\mathrm{B}}^{3}}\right)^{1 / 6}
\]

Equation 1125, Equation 1134, Equation 1136, and Equation 1137 are added to Equation 1119, Equation 1120, and Equation 1121 to solve for \(\tau_{B, j}\), which is the bulk relaxation time.

