To achieve good agreement with measurements for various doping concentrations, it is suggested to first determine \(w_{\mathrm{L}}, w_{\mathrm{T}}\), and \(w_{\mathrm{TU}}\) for low-doping concentration samples: \(w_{\text {TU }}\) mainly determines the high-temperature range, and \(w_{\mathrm{L}}\) and \(w_{\mathrm{T}}\) determine the peak value and their ratio \(w_{\mathrm{L}} / w_{\mathrm{T}}\) determines the slope of the low-temperature range. For moderate doping cases, free-carrier scattering starts to have an effect; therefore, \(E_{\mathrm{D}}\) and \(b\) are used to further fit the low-temperature range. For high doping cases, bound-carrier scattering is insignificant; therefore, \(\kappa\) is mainly determined by \(E_{\mathrm{D}}, b\), and \(A_{x}\).

