\section*{Thin-Layer Relaxation Time}

For thin layers with thickness \(d_{\mathrm{Ly}}\), the relaxation time decreases [9]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \tau_{\mathrm{Ly}, j}=F\left(\delta_{j}, p\right) \tau_{B, j} \\
& F\left(\delta_{j}, p\right)=1 /\left[1+\frac{3}{8 \delta_{j}}(1-p)\right]
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\delta_{j}=r_{\delta} d_{\mathrm{Ly}} /\left(v_{j} \tau_{B, j}\right)\) and \(p=\exp \left(-\frac{16 \pi^{3} \eta^{2}}{\lambda^{2}}\right)\), and where:
- \(r_{\delta}\) is a constant to adjust the mean free path in some situations.
- \(d_{\mathrm{Ly}}\) is the layer thickness.
- \(\eta\) is a fitting parameter.
- \(\lambda=2 \pi v_{s} / \omega\).

The layer thickness is computed internally by setting the LayerThickness command in the Physics section (see Extracting Layer Thickness on page 398). Alternatively, you can define the layer thickness by setting the parameter \(d_{\text {Ly }}\) if LayerThickness is not defined. By default, \(d_{\mathrm{Ly}}\) is 0.3 m , which ensures \(F\left(\delta_{j}, p\right)=1\), thereby the bulk relaxation time is taken into account.

