\section*{PMI_ThermoElectricPower Model}

In the most general case, thermoelectric powers in semiconductors can be computed using the thermoelectric power PMI (see Thermoelectric Power on page 1390) as functions of the lattice temperature and the carrier density. Both the standard and simplified PMI (with automatic derivatives) are supported.

\section*{Thermoelectric Power in Metals}

In metals, thermoelectric power is defined as a PMI depending on the gradient of the Fermi potential \(\nabla \Phi_{\mathrm{M}}\) and the lattice temperature \(T\) (see Metal Thermoelectric Power on page 1381). It is used in connection with thermodynamic transport in metals (the Seebeck effect).

\section*{Using Thermoelectric Power}

Thermoelectric powers in semiconductors are computed automatically when the Temperature equation is solved and the keyword Thermodynamic is specified in the global Physics section. By default, tabulated silicon data is used. For materials other than silicon, it is recommended to use the analytic formulas if no PMI model is available.

[Page 1059 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


To activate an analytic formula (Equation 1146, Equation 1147) or thermoelectric power PMI models either regionwise, or materialwise, or globally, the keyword TEPOwer with Analytic or the PMI name as an option must be specified in the corresponding Physics section.

The following example activates an analytic formula in "region1", the thermoelectric power PMI pmi_tepower in "region2", and tabulated data interpolation in all other semiconductor regions:
```
Physics(Region="region1") {
    TEPower(Analytic) # analytic formula TEP model in "region1"
}
Physics(Region="region2") {
    TEPower(pmi_tepower) # PMI in "region2"
}
```


For backward compatibility, the keyword AnalyticTEP in the Physics section is still available to activate an analytic formula for thermoelectric power globally. It is equivalent to specifying TEPower (Analytic) in the global Physics section. In addition, for degenerate semiconductors where Fermi statistics is used it is possible to consistently add the Fermi correction to the analytic formulas (see Equation 1148 and Equation 1149) by adding the keyword FermiFortEPAnalytic to the global Physics section:
```
Physics {
    Fermi
    FermiForTEPAnalytic
}
```


The coefficients for the thermoelectric powers defined by the analytic formula are available in the TEPower parameter set (see Table 172 on page 1044).

Thermoelectric power in metals is activated selectively when the Temperature equation is solved and the keyword Thermodynamic is specified in the global Physics section. To activate it regionwise, materialwise, or globally, the keyword MetalTEPower with the metal thermoelectric power PMI name as an option must be specified in the corresponding Physics sections.

