\section*{Electronic Band Structure for Wurtzite Crystals}

To account for the strong coupling of the three valence bands (heavy holes (HH), light holes (LH), and crystal-field split-holes (CH)) in wurtzite crystals, the localized quantum-well model in Sentaurus Device supports a parabolic band approximation using effective masses at the \(\Gamma\)-point. It is derived from the three-band \(\vec{k} \cdot \overrightarrow{\mathbf{p}}\) method and considers strain effects assuming a growth direction along the \(c\)-axis of the hexagonal lattice. Based on general band-structure parameters for wurtzite crystals and a given strain defined by the mismatch of lattice constants, the band offsets and effective masses parallel and perpendicular to the growth direction are computed.

Starting from the diagonal strain tensor defined as:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \varepsilon_{x x}=\varepsilon_{y y}=\frac{a_{\mathrm{s}}-a_{0}}{a_{0}} \\
& \varepsilon_{z z}=-2 \frac{C_{13}}{C_{33}} \varepsilon_{x x} \\
& \varepsilon_{x y}=\varepsilon_{y z}=\varepsilon_{z x}=0
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(a_{\mathrm{s}}\) corresponds to the lattice constant of the substrate, and \(a_{0}\) is the lattice constant of the unstrained layer. The energies of the valence band edge can be written as [2]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& E_{\mathrm{hh}}^{0}=E_{\mathrm{v}}^{0}+\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2}+\theta_{\varepsilon}+\lambda_{\varepsilon} \\
& E_{\mathrm{lh}}^{0}=E_{\mathrm{v}}^{0}+\frac{\Delta_{1}-\Delta_{2}+\theta_{\varepsilon}}{2}+\lambda_{\varepsilon}+\sqrt{\left(\frac{\Delta_{1}-\Delta_{2}+\theta_{\varepsilon}}{2}\right)^{2}+2 \Delta_{3}^{2}} \\
& E_{\mathrm{ch}}^{0}=E_{\mathrm{v}}^{0}+\frac{\Delta_{1}-\Delta_{2}+\theta_{\varepsilon}}{2}+\lambda_{\varepsilon}-\sqrt{\left(\frac{\Delta_{1}-\Delta_{2}+\theta_{\varepsilon}}{2}\right)^{2}+2 \Delta_{3}^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]
with \(\theta_{\varepsilon}\) and \(\lambda_{\varepsilon}\) expressing their dependency on the shear deformation potentials \(D_{1}\) to \(D_{4}\) :
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \theta_{\varepsilon}=D_{3} \varepsilon_{z z}+D_{4}\left(\varepsilon_{x x}+\varepsilon_{y y}\right) \\
& \lambda_{\varepsilon}=D_{1} \varepsilon_{z z}+D_{2}\left(\varepsilon_{x x}+\varepsilon_{y y}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

The strain-dependent conduction band edge is given by:
\[
E_{c}^{0}=E_{v}^{0}+\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2}+E_{g}+P_{c \varepsilon}
\]
where the energy shift \(P_{c \varepsilon}\) is due to the hydrostatic deformation potentials parallel ( \(a_{c z}\) ) and perpendicular ( \(a_{c t}\) ) to the growth direction:
\[
P_{c \varepsilon}=a_{c z} \varepsilon_{z z}+a_{c t}\left(\varepsilon_{x x}+\varepsilon_{y y}\right)
\]

In the expressions for the band edges (Equation 1198-Equation 1200, and Equation 1203), \(E_{\mathrm{v}}^{0}\) is used as the reference energy and stands for the CH band-edge energy in the absence of spin-orbit interaction. Table 185 and Table 186 summarize all band structure-related and

