\section*{Optical Transition Matrix Element for Wurtzite Crystals}

To compute the spontaneous emission spectrum, \(r^{\mathrm{sp}}(E)\), in LED simulations as defined in Equation 1178 on page 1103, the optical transition matrix element must be evaluated. For quantum wells grown along the \(c\)-axis of the wurtzite crystal, the polarization-dependent transition matrix element for the different conduction band-to-valence band transitions can be written as [5]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \left|M_{\mathrm{hh}}^{\mathrm{TE}}\right|^{2}=\frac{3}{2} O_{i j}\left(M_{b}^{\mathrm{TE}}\right)^{2} \\
& \left|M_{\mathrm{lh}}^{\mathrm{TE}}\right|^{2}=\frac{3}{2} \cos ^{2}\left(\theta_{e}\right) O_{i j}\left(M_{b}^{\mathrm{TE}}\right)^{2} \\
& \left|M_{\mathrm{ch}}^{\mathrm{TE}}\right|^{2}=0 \\
& \left|M_{\mathrm{hh}}^{\mathrm{TM}}\right|^{2}=0 \\
& \left|M_{l h}^{\mathrm{TM}}\right|^{2}=\frac{3}{2} \sin ^{2}\left(\theta_{e}\right) O_{i j}\left(M_{b}^{\mathrm{TM}}\right)^{2} \\
& \left|M_{\mathrm{ch}}^{\mathrm{TM}}\right|^{2}=\frac{3}{2} O_{i j}\left(M_{b}^{\mathrm{TM}}\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 1112 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Simple Quantum-Well Subband Model
where \(O_{i j}\) refers to the overlap integral between the envelope wavefunctions of the \(i\)-th electron subband and the \(j\)-th valence subband. The anisotropic bulk momentum matrix elements are given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \left(M_{b}^{\mathrm{TE}}\right)^{2}=\frac{m_{0}}{6}\left(\frac{1}{m_{c}^{z}}-1\right) \frac{\left(E_{g}+\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2}\right)\left(E_{g}+2 \Delta_{2}\right)-2 \Delta_{3}^{2}}{E_{g}+2 \Delta_{2}} \\
& \left(M_{b}^{\mathrm{TM}}\right)^{2}=\frac{m_{0}}{6}\left(\frac{1}{m_{c}^{t}}-1\right) \frac{E_{g}\left[\left(E_{g}+\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2}\right)\left(E_{g}+2 \Delta_{2}\right)-2 \Delta_{3}^{2}\right]}{\left(E_{g}+\Delta_{1}+\Delta_{2}\right)\left(E_{g}+\Delta_{2}\right)-\Delta_{3}^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(m_{c}^{z}\) and \(m_{c}^{t}\) denote the relative electron mass parallel and perpendicular to the quantization direction, respectively, and \(m_{0}\) denotes the electron rest mass. The angle \(\theta_{e}\) is defined as:
\[
k_{z}=|\vec{k}| \cos \left(\theta_{e}\right)
\]
where \(\vec{k}\) refers to the electron vector, and \(\cos \left(\theta_{e}\right)=1\) at the G-point of the quantum-well subband.

Arbitrary polarization is modeled as a linear combination of TE and TM polarization according to:
\[
\left|M_{i, j}\right|^{2}=a \cdot\left|M_{i, j}^{\mathrm{TE}}\right|^{2}+(1-a) \cdot\left|M_{i, j}^{\mathrm{TM}}\right|^{2}
\]
where \(a\) is called the PolarizationFactor, which can be set in the QWLocal section as shown here. For purely TE or TM simulations, it is sufficient to set Polarization to the respective identifier:
```
Physics {
    QWLocal (
        Polarization = TE # TM
        # or
        Polarization = Mixed
        PolarizationFactor = 0.4 # must be in interval [0 1]
    )
}
```


\section*{Simple Quantum-Well Subband Model}

This section describes the solution of the Schrödinger equation for a simple finite quantum-well model. This is the default model in Sentaurus Device. This simple quantum-well (QW) subband model is combined with separate QW strain (see Strain Effects on page 1116) to model most (III-V material) quantum-well systems.

In a quantum well, the carriers are confined in one direction. Of interest are the subband energies and wavefunctions of the bound states, which can be solved from the Schrödinger equation. In this simple QW subband model, it is assumed that the bands for the electron,

[Page 1113 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Simple Quantum-Well Subband Model

heavy hole, and light hole are decoupled, and the subbands are solved independently by a 1D Schrödinger equation.

The time-independent 1D Schrödinger equation in the effective mass approximation is:
\[
\left(-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2} \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \frac{1}{m(x)} \frac{\partial}{\partial x}+V(x)-E^{i}\right) \zeta^{i}(x)=0
\]
where \(\zeta^{i}(x)\) is the \(i\)-th quantum mechanical wavefunction, \(E^{i}\) is the \(i\)-th energy eigenvalue, and \(V(x)\) is the finite well shape potential.

With the following ansatz for the even wavefunctions:
\[
\zeta(x)=C_{1}\left\{\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos \left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right) e^{-\alpha(|x|-l / 2)} & , & |x|>l / 2 \\
\cos (\kappa x) & , & |x| \leq l / 2
\end{array}\right.
\]
and the odd wavefunctions:
\[
\zeta(x)=C_{2}\left\{\begin{array}{cl} 
\pm \sin \left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right) e^{\mp(x \mp l / 2)} & ,|x|>l / 2 \\
\sin (\kappa x) & ,|x| \leq l / 2
\end{array}\right.
\]

Equation 1221 becomes [1]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \alpha \frac{l}{2}+\frac{m_{b}}{m_{w}} \kappa \frac{l}{2} \cot \left(\kappa \frac{l}{2}\right)=0 \\
& \alpha \frac{l}{2}-\frac{m_{b}}{m_{w}} \kappa \frac{l}{2} \tan \left(\kappa \frac{l}{2}\right)=0
\end{aligned}
\]
with:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& \kappa=\frac{\sqrt{2 m_{w} E}}{\hbar} \\
& \alpha=\frac{\sqrt{2 m_{b}\left(\Delta E_{c}-E\right)}}{\hbar}
\end{aligned}
\]

The first transcendental equation gives the even eigenvalues, and the second one gives the odd eigenvalues. The wavefunctions are immediately obtained with Equation 1222 and Equation 1223 after the subband energy \(E\) has been computed.

[Page 1114 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Simple Quantum-Well Subband Model

Having obtained the wavefunctions and subband energies, the carrier densities of the 1D-confined system are also computed by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& n(x)=N_{e}^{2 D} \sum_{i}\left|\zeta_{i}(x)\right|^{2} F_{0}\left(\eta_{n}-E_{i}\right) \\
& p(x)=N_{h h}^{2 D} \sum_{j}\left|\zeta_{j(x)}\right|^{2} F_{0}\left(\eta_{p}-E_{h h}^{j}\right)+N_{l h}^{2 D} \sum_{m}\left|\zeta_{m(x)}\right|^{2} F_{0}\left(\eta_{p}-E_{l h}^{m}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(F_{0}(x)\) is the Fermi integral of the order 0 , and \(\eta_{n}, \eta_{p}\) denote the chemical potentials. The indices \(h h\) and \(l h\) denote the heavy and light holes, respectively.

The effective densities of states are:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& N_{e}^{2 D}=\frac{k_{B} T m_{e}}{\hbar^{2} \pi L_{x}} \\
& N_{l h / h h}^{2 D}=\frac{k_{B} T m_{l h / h h}}{\hbar^{2} \pi L_{x}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(L_{x}\) is the thickness of the quantum well. The thickness of each quantum well is automatically detected in Sentaurus Device by scanning the material regions for the keyword Active.

The effective masses of the carriers in the quantum well can be changed inside the parameter file:
```
