\section*{Direct Tunneling}

You specify the DirectTunneling option to select direct tunneling, which accounts for the direct electrode-to-electrode tunneling of electrons.

[Page 1140 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Tunneling Processes

The KMC direct tunneling rate \(d R_{\mathrm{DT}}\) associated with a portion of the source electrode with area \(d A\) is calculated from:
\[
d R_{\mathrm{DT}}=\frac{d A m_{1}^{*} k_{\mathrm{B}} T}{2 \pi^{2} \hbar^{3}} \int_{E_{c 1}}^{E_{b}} T(E) \ln \left(\frac{e^{\left(E_{f 1}-E_{c 1}-E\right) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T}+1}{e^{\left(E_{f 2}-E_{c 1}-E\right) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T}+1}\right) d E
\]
where, \(m_{1}^{*}\) is the electrode effective tunneling mass (metun), and \(T(E)\) is the transmission coefficient calculated using a WKB approximation:
\[
T(E)=\exp \left(-2 \int_{x_{1}}^{x_{2}} d x \sqrt{\frac{2 m_{\mathrm{ins}}^{*}}{\hbar^{2}}(V(x)-E)}\right)
\]

For a semiconductor electrode:
\[
d R_{\mathrm{DT}}=\frac{d A k_{\mathrm{B}} T}{2 \pi^{2} \hbar^{3}} m_{c}^{*} \Theta\left(E_{e}-E_{c}\right) \int_{E_{c 1}}^{E_{b}} T(E) \ln \left(\frac{e^{\left(E_{f 1}-E_{c 1}-E\right) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T}+1}{e^{\left(E_{f 2}-E_{c 1}-E\right) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T}+1}\right) d E
\]

If the potential energy \(V(x)\) is linear along the tunneling path, then the integral can be calculated analytically giving:
\[
T(E)=\exp \left(-\frac{4 \sqrt{2 m_{\mathrm{ins}}^{*}}}{3 \hbar\left(V_{\mathrm{ins}} / t_{\mathrm{ins}}\right)}\left[\left(E_{b}-E\right)^{3 / 2}-\left(E_{b}-E-e V_{\mathrm{ins}}\right)^{3 / 2}\right]\right)
\]
where \(m_{\mathrm{ins}}^{*}\) is the insulator effective tunneling mass (metun).

