Tunneling Processes

\section*{Poole-Frenkel Emission}

You select Poole-Frenkel emission with the PooleFrenkelEmission option, which accounts for the field-enhanced thermal emission of electrons from defects to the insulator conduction band.

The KMC Poole-Frenkel emission rate \(R_{\text {PF }}\) is given by [1]:
\[
R_{\mathrm{PF}}=v \cdot \exp \left(-\frac{E_{D}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right)\left\{\left(\frac{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}{\beta \sqrt{F}}\right)^{2}\left[1+\left(\frac{\beta \sqrt{F}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}-1\right) \exp \left(\frac{\beta \sqrt{F}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right)\right]+\frac{1}{2}\right\}
\]
where:
- \(\beta=\sqrt{\frac{e^{3}}{\pi \varepsilon_{0} \varepsilon_{\mathrm{opt}}}}\).
- \(F\) is the insulator electric field.
- \(v\) is the lattice vibration frequency (insulator PhononFrequency).
- \(E_{D}\) is the trap depth (defect EtFill).
- \(\varepsilon_{\text {opt }}\) is the insulator OpticalPermittivity.

\section*{Elastic Electrode-to-Trap and Trap-to-Electrode Tunneling}

You select elastic electrode-to-trap tunneling with the ElasticElectrodeToTrapTunneling option and elastic trap-to-electrode tunneling with the ElasticTrapToElectrodeTunneling option.

The KMC tunneling rates \(R_{\mathrm{ED}}\) and \(R_{\mathrm{DE}}\) are given by [1]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& R_{\mathrm{ED}}=\left(\frac{m_{e}}{m_{i}}\right)^{5 / 2}\left(\frac{8 E_{e}^{3 / 2}}{3 \hbar \sqrt{E_{D}}}\right) f\left(E_{e}\right) T\left(E_{e}\right) \\
& R_{\mathrm{DE}}=\left(\frac{m_{e}}{m_{i}}\right)^{5 / 2}\left(\frac{8 E_{e}^{3 / 2}}{3 \hbar \sqrt{E_{D}}}\right)\left(1-f\left(E_{e}\right)\right) T\left(E_{e}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(m_{e}\) is the electrode density-of-states (DOS) mass (medos).
- \(m_{i}\) is the insulator effective tunneling mass (metun).
- \(E_{D}\) is the trap depth of the empty or filled defect (EtEmpty or EtFill).
- \(E_{e}\) is the electron energy.

[Page 1142 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Tunneling Processes
- \(T\left(E_{e}\right)\) is the transmission coefficient for the barrier between the electrode and the defect.
- \(f\left(E_{e}\right)\) is the Fermi-Dirac distribution function given by \(f\left(E_{e}\right)=\frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E_{e}-E_{f}\right) /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)}}\).

For a semiconductor electrode:
\[
\begin{aligned}
R_{\mathrm{ED}}= & \left(\frac{m_{c}}{m_{i}}\right)^{5 / 2}\left(\frac{8\left(E_{e}-E_{c}\right)^{3 / 2}}{3 \hbar \sqrt{E_{D}}}\right) f\left(E_{e}\right) T\left(E_{e}\right) \theta\left(E_{e}-E_{c}\right) \\
& +\left(\frac{m_{v}}{m_{i}}\right)^{5 / 2}\left(\frac{8\left(E_{v}-E_{e}\right)^{3 / 2}}{3 \hbar \sqrt{E_{D}}}\right) f\left(E_{e}\right) T\left(E_{e}\right) \theta\left(E_{v}-E_{e}\right) \\
R_{\mathrm{DE}}= & \left(\frac{m_{c}}{m_{i}}\right)^{5 / 2}\left(\frac{8\left(E_{e}-E_{c}\right)^{3 / 2}}{3 \hbar \sqrt{E_{D}}}\right)\left(1-f\left(E_{e}\right)\right) T\left(E_{e}\right) \theta\left(E_{e}-E_{c}\right) \\
& +\left(\frac{m_{h}}{m_{i}}\right)^{5 / 2}\left(\frac{8\left(E_{v}-E_{e}\right)^{3 / 2}}{3 \hbar \sqrt{E_{D}}}\right)\left(1-f\left(E_{e}\right)\right) T\left(E_{e}\right) \theta\left(E_{v}-E_{e}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\section*{Option for Elastic Tunneling}

As an alternative to Equation 1241 and Equation 1242, you can use elastic tunneling rates based on the inelastic expressions in Inelastic Electrode-to-Trap and Trap-to-Electrode Tunneling.

If you specify the ElasticUsePZeroSZero option, then the elastic electrode-to-trap and elastic trap-to-electrode tunneling rates are calculated from the \(p=0\) term in Equation 1245 and Equation 1246 with the Huang-Rhys parameter set to zero ( \(S=0\) ). The latter condition is equivalent to setting \(L_{p}(z)=1\) in Equation 1245 and Equation 1246.

\section*{Inelastic Electrode-to-Trap and Trap-to-Electrode Tunneling}

You can select inelastic electrode-to-trap tunneling with the option
InelasticElectrodeToTrapTunneling and inelastic trap-to-electrode tunneling with the InelasticTrapToElectrodeTunneling option.
The KMC tunneling rates \(R_{\mathrm{ED}}^{\mathrm{MP}}\) and \(R_{\mathrm{DE}}^{\mathrm{MP}}\) are given by [1]:
\[
\begin{aligned}
R_{\mathrm{ED}}^{\mathrm{MP}}= & \sum_{p<0}^{\infty} c_{0} N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right) f\left(E_{p}\right) T\left(E_{p}\right) L_{p}(z) \cdot e^{\frac{p \hbar \omega}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}}+\sum_{p>0}^{\infty} c_{0} N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right) f\left(E_{p}\right) T\left(E_{p}\right) L_{p}(z) \\
R_{\mathrm{DE}}^{\mathrm{MP}}= & \sum_{p<0}^{\infty} c_{0} N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right)\left(1-f\left(E_{p}\right)\right) T\left(E_{p}\right) L_{p}(z)+\sum_{p>0}^{\infty} c_{0} N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right)\left(1-f\left(E_{p}\right)\right) T\left(E_{p}\right) L_{p}(z) \cdot e^{\frac{-p \hbar \omega}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}}
\end{aligned}
\]

[Page 1143 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Tunneling Processes

where:
- The electron tunneling energy \(E_{p}\) is given by \(E_{p}=E_{e}+p \hbar \omega\), where \(p\) is the integer phonon number, and \(\hbar \omega\) is the phonon energy in the insulator (PhononEnergy).
- The DOS in the electrode \(N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right)\) is given by:
\[
N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right)=\frac{1}{2 \pi^{2}}\left(\frac{2 m_{e}}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{3 / 2} \sqrt{E_{p}-E_{c}} \cdot \theta\left(E_{p}-E_{c}\right)
\]
where \(m_{e}\) is the electrode DOS mass (medos), and \(E_{c}\) is the conduction band edge of the electrode.
- The DOS in the semiconductor electrode \(N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right)\) is given by:
\[
N_{E}\left(E_{p}\right)=\frac{1}{2 \pi^{2}}\left(\frac{2 m_{c}}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{3 / 2} \sqrt{E_{p}-E_{c}} \cdot \theta\left(E_{p}-E_{c}\right)+\frac{1}{2 \pi^{2}}\left(\frac{2 m_{v}}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{3 / 2} \sqrt{E_{v}-E_{p}} \cdot \theta\left(E_{v}-E_{p}\right)
\]
where \(m_{c}, m_{v}\) is the electrode DOS mass (medos), and \(E_{c}\) the conduction band edge of the electrode.
- The capture coefficient \(c_{0}\) is given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& c_{0}=\frac{(4 \pi)^{2} r_{D}^{3}}{\hbar E_{\mathrm{g}}}\left(h E_{0}\right)^{3} \\
& \left(\hbar E_{0}\right)^{3}=\frac{e^{2} \hbar^{2} F^{2}}{2 m_{i}}
\end{aligned}
\]
where:
- \(E_{\mathrm{g}}\) is the insulator band gap (Eg0).
- \(m_{i}\) is the insulator effective tunneling mass (metun).
- \(F\) is the insulator electric field.
- The localization radius \(r_{D}\) is given by \(r_{D}=\frac{\hbar}{\sqrt{2 m_{i} E_{D}}}\).

If you specify DeltaTrapPotential, then a field-independent \(c_{0}\) is used instead:
\[
c_{0}=\frac{(4 \pi)^{2} r_{D}^{3}}{\hbar}\left(E_{D}\right)^{2}
\]
- The Fermi-Dirac distribution \(f\left(E_{p}\right)\) is \(f\left(E_{p}\right)=\frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E_{p}-E_{f}\right) /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)}}\).

[Page 1144 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


- The multiphonon transition probability \(L_{p}(z)\) is given by:
\[
L_{p}(z)=\exp \left[-S\left(2 f_{\mathrm{BE}}+1\right)+\frac{p \hbar \omega}{2 k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right] \cdot I_{p}(z)
\]
where:
- \(S\) is the Huang-Rhys parameter in the insulator (HuangRhys).
- \(f_{\mathrm{BE}}\) is the Bose-Einstein distribution:
\[
f_{\mathrm{BE}}=\frac{1}{\exp \left(\frac{\hbar \omega}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right)-1}
\]
- \(I_{p}(z)\) is a modified Bessel function of order \(p\) with:
\[
z=2 S \sqrt{f_{\mathrm{BE}}\left(f_{\mathrm{BE}}+1\right)}
\]

\section*{Options for Inelastic Tunneling}

You can use variants of these expressions, mainly related to which phonon energies are included in the tunneling rate calculations. The following options allow the phonon energy summations in Equation 1245 and Equation 1246 to be modified:
- InelasticIgnorePMinus: Ignores the \(p<0\) terms in Equation 1245 and Equation 1246
- InelasticIncludePZero: Includes the \(p=0\) term in Equation 1245 and Equation 1246
- InelasticPZeroOnly: Uses only the \(p=0\) term in Equation 1245 and Equation 1246

\section*{Trap-to-Trap Tunneling}

This section discusses the trap-to-trap tunneling models.

\section*{Trap-to-Trap Tunneling Model}

You select trap-to-trap tunneling (both elastic and inelastic) with the TrapToTrapTunneling option, which accounts for electron tunneling between defects. The trap-to-trap rate \(R_{i j}\) from defect \(i\) to defect \(j\) is given by [1]:
\[
R_{i j}=v \cdot T_{i j} \cdot\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\exp \left(-\frac{\Delta E_{j i}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right), & \text { if } \Delta E_{j i}>0 \\
1, & \text { otherwise }
\end{array}\right.
\]
where:
- \(v\) is the lattice vibration frequency (insulator PhononFrequency).
- \(\quad T_{i j}\) is the transmission coefficient for the energy barrier between defect \(i\) and defect \(j\).

[Page 1145 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Tunneling Processes
- \(\Delta E_{j i}\) is the energy difference between the final defect state and the initial defect state.

This model is an extension of the Miller-Abrahams hopping model [1] and is obtained by replacing \(\exp \left(-2 r_{i j} / r_{\mathrm{D}}\right)\) in the Miller-Abrahams expression with a calculation of the transmission coefficient \(T_{i j}\).

\section*{Inelastic Phonon Trap-to-Trap Tunneling Model}

You can select the inelastic phonon trap-to-trap tunneling model as an alternative to the TrapToTrapTunneling model by specifying TrapToTrapTunneling(InelasticPhonon).

When selected, the trap-to-trap electron capture rate from defect 1 to defect 2 is calculated using:
\[
R_{12}=\frac{1}{\tau_{0}} \cdot T_{12}(E) \cdot\left[\frac{\alpha(S-p)^{2}}{S}+1-\alpha\right] \cdot L_{p}(z) \cdot\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\exp \left(-\frac{\Delta E_{21}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}\right), & \text { if } \Delta E_{21}>0 \\
1, & \text { otherwise }
\end{array}\right.
\]
where:
- \(\tau_{0}\) is a fitting parameter (insulator tau0; default \(=10^{-4} \mathrm{~s}\) ).
- \(T_{12}(E)\) is the transmission coefficient for the energy barrier between defect 1 and defect 2.
- \(\alpha\) is a user-specified parameter (insulator alpha; default \(=1\) ).
- \(S\) is the Huang-Rhys parameter (insulator HuangRhys).
- \(p\) is the phonon number given by:
\[
p=\left|\frac{E_{1}-E_{2}}{\hbar \omega}\right|
\]
where \(\hbar \omega\) is the phonon energy in the insulator (PhononEnergy).
- \(\Delta E_{21}\) is the energy difference between the trap levels of defect 2 and defect 1 .
- \(L_{p}(z)\) is the multiphonon transition probability (see Equation 1252 to Equation 1254).

The phonon number, \(p\), is usually taken to be an integer. In the implementation of this model, however, \(p\) can take a floating-point value given by Equation 1257, and the modified Bessel function, \(I_{p}(z)\) in Equation 1252, is approximated with the expression given in Specifying the Approximate Bessel Function on page 1132.

\section*{Multiphonon Trap-to-Trap Tunneling Model}

You can select a multiphonon description of trap-to-trap tunneling [2][3] by specifying TrapToTrapTunneling (MultiPhonon). For a transition from defect 1 to defect 2, this model provides expressions for capture and emission.

[Page 1146 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Tunneling Processes

For capture by defect 2 from defect 1 , the transition rate is given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& R_{\mathrm{ca}, 12}=\sum_{p=0}^{\infty} c_{0} N_{1}\left(E_{2, p}\right) f_{1}\left(E_{2, p}\right) T_{12}\left(E_{2, p}\right) L_{p}(z) \\
& N_{1}\left(E_{2, p}\right)=\frac{1}{2 \pi^{2}}\left(\frac{2 m_{1}}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{3 / 2} \sqrt{E_{2, p}-E_{1}} \cdot \Theta\left(E_{2, p}-E_{1}\right) \\
& f_{1}\left(E_{2, p}\right)=\frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E_{2, p}-E_{1}\right) /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)}} \\
& E_{2, p}=E_{2}+p \hbar \omega
\end{aligned}
\]

For emission from defect 1 to defect 2 , the transition rate is given by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
& R_{\mathrm{em}, 12}=\sum_{p=0}^{\infty} c_{0} N_{2}\left(E_{1, p}\right)\left(1-f_{2}\left(E_{1, p}\right)\right) T_{12}\left(E_{1, p}\right) L_{p}(z) e^{\frac{-p \hbar \omega}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}} \\
& N_{2}\left(E_{1, p}\right)=\frac{1}{2 \pi^{2}}\left(\frac{2 m_{2}}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{3 / 2} \sqrt{E_{1, p}-E_{2}} \cdot \Theta\left(E_{1, p}-E_{2}\right) \\
& f_{2}\left(E_{1, p}\right)=\frac{1}{1+e^{\left(E_{1, p}-E_{2}\right) /\left(k_{\mathrm{B}} T\right)}} \\
& E_{1, p}=E_{1}+p \hbar \omega
\end{aligned}
\]

In Equation 1258 and Equation 1262, \(c_{0}\) is taken from Equation \(1249\left(c_{0}\right.\) is taken from Equation 1251 if with the DeltaTrapPotential option), \(L_{p}(z)\) is taken from Equation 1252, and \(T_{12}(E)\) is the transmission coefficient calculated at energy \(E\). In Equation 1259 and Equation 1263, \(m_{1}\) and \(m_{2}\) are DOS masses (medos).
For the KMC trap-to-trap rate, the minimum of \(R_{\mathrm{ca}, 12}\) and \(R_{\mathrm{em}, 12}\) is used:
\[
R_{12}=\min \left(R_{\mathrm{ca}, 12}, R_{\mathrm{em}, 12}\right)
\]

[Page 1147 END]
