\section*{Time-Dependent Dielectric Breakdown Simulations}

If you select the thdB option, then Sentaurus Device accounts for time-dependent dielectric breakdown (TDDB). The TDDB feature is selected in the general Physics section as follows:
```
Physics{
    Traps ((TDDB))
}
```


The KMC simulator is used to generate defects according to the following expression [4]:
\[
G(x, y, z)=v \cdot \exp \left(-\frac{E_{A}-p_{0} \frac{2+\kappa}{3} \cdot F(x, y, z)}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T(x, y, z)}\right)
\]
where:
- \(v\) is the maximum frequency of the generation process (nu_max); default: \(10^{14} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\).
- \(E_{A}\) is the activation energy ( EA ); default: \(2.4 \mathrm{eV}\left(\mathrm{SiO}_{2}\right)[4], 3.0 \mathrm{eV}\left(\mathrm{HfO}_{2}\right)[4]\).
- \(p_{0}\) is the molecular dipole moment (p0); default: \(4.1 \mathrm{eA}\left(\mathrm{SiO}_{2}\right)[4], 5.2 \mathrm{eA}\left(\mathrm{HfO}_{2}\right)[4]\).
- \(\kappa\) is the dielectric constant.
- \(F\) is the local electric field.
- \(\quad T\) is the local lattice temperature.

Parameter values for \(\mathrm{ZrO}_{2}\) from [5][6] are \(E_{A}=1.87 \mathrm{eV}\) and \(p_{0}=2.1 \mathrm{e} \AA\). Parameter values for \(\mathrm{SiO}_{2}\) from [7] considering a double electron capture process are \(E_{A}=0.7 \mathrm{eV}\) and \(p_{0}=\) 1.0 eA .

When you specify tddB, Sentaurus Device automatically uses the following settings:
- SkipKMC (KMC statement in the Math section), which instructs Sentaurus Device not to use the KMC simulator for the calculation of leakage current
- RateEquationCurrent (KMC_MIM_Transport statement in the Physics section), which instructs Sentaurus Device to calculate the current through the MIM structure using the REC method

The other parameters in Tunneling Processes define the tunneling mechanisms and options used for leakage current calculations. The MIM leakage current is calculated after each Sentaurus Device/KMC time interval and is stored in the standard *.plt file as MIMTotalCurrent. For 2D structures, the width of the unsimulated dimension is defined by AreaFactor in the Physics section, in \(\mu \mathrm{m}\) ( \(1 \mu \mathrm{~m}\) by default). Leakage current and conduction current have the unit of A.

[Page 1155 END]
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Tunneling Processes

In a nonuniform insulator, there can be a spatial distribution on the activation energy and molecule dipole moment. To simulate the nonuniformity, assuming that the spatial variation of the activation energy and molecule dipole moment follow a normal distribution, their standard deviations \(\sigma_{E_{A}}\) (SigmaEA) and \(\sigma_{p_{0}}\) (SigmaP0) can be defined. By default, both values are zero, meaning there is no spatial variation on the activation energy and molecule dipole moment.

The conductive effect of individual defects should be independent of the size of the simulation mesh. To ensure that the conductive effect has an influence across multiple meshes, the conductive radius (ConductiveRadius) can be defined in units of \(\mu \mathrm{m}\). Meshes within this radius will have a high conductance. By default, a conductive radius is 0 means the defect does not influence neighboring meshes. The influence of the conductive radius of a trap does not extend beyond material boundaries.

When you specify tDDB, the ConductanceEquation and HeatEquation options are switched on by default. The steady-state conductance equation is given by:
\[
\vec{\nabla} \cdot \vec{j}=\vec{\nabla} \cdot(\sigma \vec{\nabla} \psi)=0
\]

The steady-state heat equation with Joule heating is given by:
\[
\vec{\nabla} \cdot(\kappa \vec{\nabla} T+\psi \vec{\sigma} \nabla \psi)=0
\]

In these equations, \(\psi\) is the potential, \(T\) is the temperature, and \(\sigma\) and \(\kappa\) are the spatially dependent electrical and thermal conductivities that account for the presence of defects in KMC cells.

The solution of these equations over the KMC cells provides better values for the potential (and electric field) and temperature to use in the generation expression, Equation 1271. If you select -HeatEquation, then the heat equation is not solved. If you select -ConductanceEquation, then neither equation is solved.

\section*{Adjustment for Vacancy Sites per Volume}

Equation 1271 is an expression for the vacancy generation rate at a single site. In KMC simulations, since only one vacancy is allowed to occupy a KMC cell, a rate adjustment must be made to account for the cell size used in the simulation.

To this end, Equation 1271 is multiplied by a factor that represents the number of vacancies that could potentially occupy the volume of a KMC cell:
\[
\text { factor }=\text { SitesPerVolume } \text { × } \text { CellLength }{ }^{3}\left(\frac{10^{-4} \mathrm{~cm}}{\mu \mathrm{~m}}\right)^{3} \text { (in three dimensions) }
\]

[Page 1156 END]
