\section*{Fluence Dependency}

The fluence of an electrode \(F(t)\) and the fluence density at location \(x(f(x, t))\) are defined by:
\[
\begin{aligned}
F(t) & =\int_{0}^{t} I(t) d \tau \\
f(x, t) & =\int_{0}^{t} j(x, t) d \tau
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(I(t)\) is the current flowing through the electrode, and \(j(x, t)\) is the current density at location \(x\).

Experiments show that the trap density versus fluence follows the square root law \(N_{T}(t) \propto F(t)^{m}\), with close to 0.5 [9]. Therefore, the total generation rate follows:
\[
G=\frac{d N_{T}(t)}{d t} \propto \frac{d F(t)^{m}}{d t}=F(t)^{m-1} I(t)
\]

For the generation rate at a given location, you add the fluence-dependent term to the existing electric field-dependent model \(G_{\mathrm{E}}(x)\) :
\[
G_{f}(x, t)=G_{\mathrm{E}}(x) \frac{f(x, t)^{m-1} j(x, t)}{f_{0}^{m}}
\]

Here, \(f_{0}\) is the user-defined reference fluence.
The impact of conduction fluence is limited to the KMC cell itself. In contrast, tunneling fluence can impact the generation rate within a radius. To activate the dependency of the generation rate on tunneling fluence from neighboring defects, set FluenceRadius greater than 0 in the parameter file. One KMC cell can be influenced by the tunneling fluence of more than one neighboring defect.

