\section*{Cluster Size-Dependent Conductance Model}

By default, an insulator cell has the conductance of SigmaIns. A trap site, together with its surrounding cells within the conductive radius, has the conductance of SigmaDef. To delay the insulator-conductor transition of the trap sites, you can use the parameter ClusterConductance(StepFunc(1)) in the Material-KMC_MIM_Transport section. ClusterConductance (StepFunc ( \(n_{\text {crit }}\) ) ) defines the critical cluster size \(n_{\text {crit }}\), such that the conductance of the trap sites follows a step function:
\[
\sigma=\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\sigma_{\text {ins }}, \text { if } n_{\text {cluster }}<n_{\text {crit }} \\
\sigma_{\text {def }}, \text { if } n_{\text {cluster }} \geq n_{\text {crit }}
\end{array}\right.
\]

A trap site is determined to belong to a cluster if it holds the same trap type of the cluster, and the cluster has a trap that is within the conductive radius of the trap site in question. When \(n_{\text {crit }}\) is 1 , the model reduces to the default setting that the first trap will increase the conductance to SigmaDef.

